{ Welcome to the course!  This course presents a GM-level repertoire against 1.e4 based on the Scandinavian. This defense is very reliable and a whole host of top players have it in their arsenal, including the world champion who has essayed it with great success. Magnus used this defense to beat Fabiano Caruana in the 2014 Tromsø Chess Olympiad, draw him in the 2016 Baku Olympiad, and defeat 5-time world champion Viswanathan Anand in the 2019 Kolkata Grand Chess tour. Bent Larsen, who was at the bottom of the standings table in the 1979 Montreal Star tournament, famously used the 3...Qa5 Scandi to defeat Anatoly Karpov, who had become World Champion earlier that year and was on an undefeated streak.  The repertoire proposed is based on the 3...Qa5 variation, which stands head and shoulders above its cousins 3...Qd6 and 3...Qd8. Retreating the queen to these more passive squares is inferior and totally uncalled for!  I’ve designed it from the ground up to be both practical and ambitious. To this end, theImportant lines feature was used, which you can enable in the course options tab. I have also added a Quickstarter with a selection of the 20 most important lines.  With less than 200 trainable variations, you can master this repertoire in no time. How come it’s so compact? The reason is I’ve turned theory on its head and suggested an array of novelties and never before seen plans that shortcut vast amounts of inferior, highly theoretical lines.  All the cutting-edge analysis herein was powered by the latest versions of the revolutionary neural network engines Stockfish and Leela running on superfast cloud servers. While I don’t have access to AlphaZero, this is as close as it gets!  But wait, didn’t you write a course against the Scandinavian where you claimed a White advantage? I finally managed to crack that line for Black with a super-strong cloud engine with 64 cores @@StartBracket@@and several other features I cannot disclose@@EndBracket@@. I’m very confident in this repertoire, having spent hundreds of hours searching for the best lines for both White and Black. Finally, I've done my best to remain objective and recommend the best moves for both sides, which I believe is key to effective opening preparation.  The Scandinavian is a fully playable and viable opening at every level, including the GM level. I’ve completely neutralized anti-Scandinavian recommendations from various top GMs, including suggestions in Lifetime Repertoires here on Chessable. Be sure to check out therepertoire clashes file for more details.  As in all of my courses, you can count on a high support level. I will promptly answer any questions you have and regularly update the course with new theoretical developments.   That's all for the intro, I hope you enjoy the course and have great success with this repertoire! }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "The Scandinavian is a great defense. Here's why"]
[Result "*"]

{ Here are a few reasons why the Scandinavian is a great defense to 1.e4:  •Fully playable at the GM level. 99% of the lines give White no advantage whatsoever. White has a small edge in only a handful of lines, which can be neutralized with precise play. I'll show you exactly how to do so! Many top GMs have tried and failed to show a White advantage as laid out in therepertoire clashes file.  •Easy to learn. Black's setups are very similar in almost all the lines with simple middlegame and endgame plans you can master in no time.  •Extremely practical. This course presents a full repertoire playable at the GM level in only 180 trainable lines. Forget about having to learn 100s upon 100s of lines of theory up to move 30 to just survive the opening, as in the Najdorf or Marshall. Sure, if you're a top GM striving to play openings with the highest pedigree, those defenses are the way to go. The Scandinavian, while objectively not as strong, is far easier to master and definitely a better choice for club players. This frees up time to study other important areas of the game rather than spending all your time memorizing reams of theory.  •Home-court advantage. Your can autopilot the first 10-15 moves and then rely on your superior understanding of and experience in the arising middlegames. White’s position is often harder to play so your opponent will have to make most of the tough decisions.  •Excellent in fast time controls. Playing the Scandinavian will often result in you having a time advantage out of the opening. Former world #1 blitz player GM Maxim Dlugy even said @@StartBlockQuote@@The Scandinavian is the best blitz opening vs 1.e4@@EndBlockQuote@@•Fantastic surprise weapon. I’d be fully confident in employing this repertoire on a regular basis, but if you’re looking for a low-maintenance, secondary defense to spring on your unsuspecting opponents, the Scandinavian is a great choice. }
