{ The following lists all of the books/courses/DVDs that feature anti-scandinavian recommendations and my preferred way of neutralizing their recommendations.   I will do my best to keep this list as up to date as possible. If there is a specific repertoire recommendation that I missed and you think I should address, please leave a comments in the Comments & Notes box below and I'll update this informational line. }
1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5
{ 2.d4  The Blackmar-Diemer Gambit was recommended in the Chessable course Blackmar-Diemer for Blitz. I show how Black can emerge out of the opening with a clear advantagehere.  IM Christopher Scheerer's The Blackmar-Diemer Gambit: A Modern Guide to a Fascinating Chess Opening is a popular book amongst BDG players. The specific clash with this source occurshere }
3. Nc3
{ 3.Nf3  Bg4  4.Be2  Nc6  5.h3  was recommended by GM Avetik Grigoryan in the chessmood.com video series Crushing the Scandinavian, which I prove is completely harmlesshere.   5.d4  was recommended in the Chessable course Smash the Scandinavian Defense by Zac Attack. The specific clash occurshere where Black can count on a slight advantage.   This variation was also recommended by IM Andrew Greet in the book Beating Unusual Chess Defences: 1 e4: Dealing with the Scandinavian, Pirc, Modern, Alekhine and other tricky lines. I propose a deviation on move12 that gives Black excellent prospects.   Finally, GM Gawain Jones recommended it in the book Coffeehouse Repertoire 1.e4: Volume 1. Clickhere for the clash.   5.O-O  was recommended by GM Simon Williams and IM Richard Palliser in the Chessable course Grandmaster Gambits: 1.e4 Part 2. As describedhere, Black is in great shape and it's White that has to be careful.   3.d3  was recommended by FM Kamil Plichta in the Chessable course Reign Supreme: The King's Indian Attack. He failed to consider Black's best move in  3...Bf5!  As explainedhere, if White insists on the typical KIA setup, he'll end up significantly worse.   3.Nf3  Bg4  4.Nc3  was GM Gawain Jones' main recommendation in the book Coffeehouse Repertoire: 1.e4 Volume 1. Best play leads to an endgame, which I show is perfectly fine for Blackhere. }
3... Qa5 4. d4
{ 4.Bc4  Nf6  5.d3  was recommended in the modern-chess.com database Complete Repertoire against the Alekhine and Scandinavian by GM Zahar Efimenko. He did not consider Black's strongest option in  5...a6  , a move which was also not considered by IM Sam Collins in the book A Simple Chess Opening Repertoire for White! The details can be foundhere. }
4... Nf6 5. Nf3
{ 5.Bd2  Bg4  6.f3  Bd7  7.f4!?  is a creative idea by GM Parimarjan Negi proposed in the book GM Repertoire: 1. e4 vs Minor Defences. I show Black is finehere.   7.Bc4!  was my recommendation in the course Crush the Alekhine and Scandinavian. It was nice to see GM Justin Tan later recommend this same exact variation in the book 1.e4! The Chess Bible. After many hours of analysis, I managed to find the path to equalityhere.   5.Bc4  Bg4  6.Nge2  e6  7.h3  was recommended by GM John Shaw in the book Playing 1.e4: Caro-Kann, 1...e5 and Minor Lines. This approach is completely harmless, as shownhere.   7.O-O  was recommended by NM Logozar in the Chessable course 1.e4: A Comprehensive White Repertoire. I show that White has no advantage whatsoeverhere. }
5... Bf5 6. Ne5
{ 6.Bc4  e6  7.Bd2  Bb4  8.a3  Bxc3  9.Bxc3  Qb6  10.d5  was Wesley So's recommendation in the Chessable course Lifetime Repertoires: Wesley So's 1. e4. I was not impressed and neutralized his suggestionshere andhere.   GM Larry Kaufman recommended a similar approach in the book Kaufman's New Repertoire for White and Black. He failed to consider Black's best optionhere. }
6... c6 7. Bc4
{ 7.g4  Be6!  was not considered in the book Chess Openings for White, Explained by GMs Lev Alburt, Roman Dzindzichashvil, and Eugene Perelshteyn. Clickhere for more information. }
7... e6 8. g4
{ was recommended by both GM Sethuraman in the Chessable course Lifetime Repertoires: Sethuraman's 1.e4, and IM Christof Sielecki in Keep it Simple 1.e4. They both missed Black's best option onmove 15.   This variation was also recommended in the book A Startling Chess Repertoire for White by IM Chris Baker and FM Graham Burgess. The specific clash occurshere.  I will regularly update this list as new literature is published. If there are any other repertoire book/database/course recommendations you think I should address, please leave a comment below and I'll add it to this list. }
