[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame & Endgame Themes"]
[Black "Capablanca Pawn Structure"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "6k1/pp3ppp/2p1p3/8/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/6K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ The Capablanca structure is the most frequent pawn formation in the Scandinavian. Here are some important strategic considerations, which will be illustrated with several examples in the next couple of informational lines:   •White's space advantage The d4 pawn gives White a space advantage and superior control over the center. The e5 square is a natural outpost for White's f3 knight, from where it supports aggressive kingside expansions with g4 and h4. Oftentimes, these pawn advances are aimed at chasing down or even trapping Black's light-squared bishop.   •Attack the d4-pawn Black, who has no pawn weaknesses, will be targeting White's d4-pawn and attempting to prove it is more of a weakness than an asset. The second player has several ways of attacking this pawn such as doubling rooks on the d-file and undermining White's f3 knight with ...Bg4/...Be4  (and potentially even exchanging it off with ...Bxf3)  . An important feature of the Scandinavian is that the early positioning of White's knight on c3 prevents the first player from being able to reinforce the d4 pawn with c2-c3.   •Black's pawn breaks A recurring plan is to engineer the ...c6-c5  (or ...e6-e5)  pawn breaks to undermine White's center. Once again, White's c3 knight prevents the first player from being able to easily reinforce the center with the c-pawn.  •d5 outpost Yet another consequence of Nc3 is that the d5 square becomes a good outpost for Black's pieces as they cannot be driven away with c2-c4. In some variations of the Scandinavian, White's dark-squared bishop finds itself on c3  (after for example ...Bf8-b4xc3 being met with Bc1-d2xc3)  . The f4 square then becomes particularly weak, with Black frequently using the d5 square as a basis of operations from which a knight can spring into f4.   •Light-square strategy Black typically places his pawns on light squares to neutralize White's bishops. Not only is the scope of White's light-squared bishop limited, White often finds his dark-squared bishop is staring into empty space since it has no targets.   •Queenside Expansion The ...b7-b5 pawn advance to clamp down on the c4 square is another important theme. Black's b8 knight, which is usually developed to d7, can then quickly hop onto c4 via the b6 square. In some instances, Black can even consider marching his a and b-pawns down the board with ...a5-a4 and ...b5-b4 to knock back White's pieces. }
