[SetUp "1"]

{ In the game Kasparov, G  (2795)  - Anand, Viswanathan  (2725)  from the 1995 PCA World Championship in New York, Anand underestimated the power of }
15... c5
{ This thematic pawn break undermines White's d4 pawn, the knight on e5, and attempts to blast open the d-file.   Anand opted for the inferior  15...Nd5  in the aforementioned game, which is extensively annotated in thenext informational line. }
16. Ne2
{ 16.Bxb7?  Going pawn-hunting is ill-advised here. After  16...Nxe5  17.fxe5  Ng4-+  White is in big trouble with the d4 pawn about to drop. Once it falls, the e5 pawn will drop soon after. }
16... Nxe5 17. fxe5 Nd7
{ with threat of ...Nxe5 would have given Black a big advantage. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame & Endgame Themes"]
[Black "1-0 Kasparov, G (2795) - Anand, V (2725) New York 1995"]
[Result "*"]

{ Viswanathan Anand essayed the 3...Qa5 against Garry Kasparov in the 1995 PCA World Championship in New York. This game illustrates several important concepts such as the strength of the ...c5 break and play on the light squares. }
1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6
{ 5...Bf5  is my recommendation in the theory section. } 6. Ne5 Be6
{ is an interesting setup. Black blocks the e-pawn, but the dark-squared bishop will be developed on g7. }
7. Bd3 Nbd7 8. f4
{ Cements the knight on e5 at the cost of severely limiting the dark-squared bishop. }
8... g6 9. O-O Bg7 10. Kh1 Bf5 11. Bc4
{ is a very strange move. The bishop is hardly doing anything on c4.   11.Bxf5  gxf5  12.Qe2= }
11... e6
{ Stops any business on f7 and severely restricts White's light-squared bishop. }
12. Be2
{ Going back with the bishop is a clear admission that 11. Bc4 was a mistake. White is threatening to expand with g2-g4, a threat Anand easily parried with }
12... h5 13. Be3 Rd8 14. Bg1 O-O
{ The outcome of the opening was a huge success. Black is already substantially better due to White's numerous weaknesses on the light squares, not to mention his misplaced pieces. }
15. Bf3 Nd5
{ Black missed a fantastic shot here.   Far stronger was  15...c5!  which would have landed White in trouble along the d-file. This thematic break would have worked wonders here! }
16. Nxd5 exd5
{ Now we have a symmetrical position where Black is slightly for choice as White's position has a lot of light-square weaknesses and a passive bishop on g1.   Recapturing the knight with  16...cxd5  was more precise, giving Black access to the c-file. Moreover, after White plays the inevitable c3, Black can start a minority attack with ...b5-b4. }
17. Bf2 Qc7
{ 17...Qb4  was a more active square for the queen, where it pressures the b2 and d4 pawns. The pawn on f4 can also be attacked with ...Bh6. }
18. Rc1 f6
{ is a natural move, knocking back White's knight.   18...Nb6!  with the idea ...Na4 was more precise. After  19.g4  hxg4  20.Bxg4  Qc8  21.Bxf5  Qxf5  Black has the upper hand as White's light-squares are very vulnerable. }
19. Nd3 Rfe8 20. b3 Nb6 21. a4
{ Slowly but surely Kasparov is improving his position. Black, on the other hand, has been playing without a clear plan. }
21... Nc8 { Black's knight is headed to e4. } 22. c4 Qf7 23. a5 Bf8 24. cxd5
cxd5 25. Bh4 Nd6 26. a6
{ Fixes Black's pawn on a7, which can easily become a weakness later on. }
26... b6 27. Ne5 { is a wild move, putting Anand under pressure. } 27... Qe6
{ is a questionable decision, after which the position starts to become really dangerous for Black.   Black should have bitten the bullet and captured the knight with  27...fxe5  28.fxe5  Ne4  29.Bxd8  Rxd8  30.g4  leads to a draw following  30...hxg4  31.Bxg4  Bxg4  32.Qxg4  Nf2+  33.Rxf2  Qxf2  34.Qxg6+  Bg7  35.Rc7  Qf1+  36.Qg1  Qf3+  37.Qg2  Qd1+  38.Qg1  Qf3+  with a perpetual. }
28. g4
{ Kasparov adds wood to the fire, placing Black under serious pressure. } 28...
hxg4 29. Nxg4 Bg7 30. Rc7 Ne4
{ is a mistake. White's rook should not have been allowed to stay on c7.   Black should have challenged White's rook with  30...Rc8!  31.Rxa7  Ne4  The crucial difference compared to the text is that with the rook on c8, Black can now invade White's position with ...Rc3. }
31. Ne3 Bh3
{ With the clock ticking down, Anand panics and makes another mistake. The bishop was far better placed on f5.   31...Rc8  was much better, with the point that capturing the pawn on a7 with  32.Rxa7  now allows  32...Nc3 }
32. Rg1 g5 33. Bg4 Bxg4 34. Qxg4 Qxg4 35. Rxg4 Nd6
{ with a double-attack on the e3 and h4 minors, a threat that was easily parried with }
36. Bf2 Nb5 { Doesn't do much as Black cannot take on d4. } 37. Rb7 Re4
{ 37...Nxd4??  loses on the spot to  38.fxg5+- } 38. f5 Rxg4 39. Nxg4 Rc8 40.
Rd7
{ 40.h4  was even stronger, going after the f6 pawn with  40...gxh4  41.Bxh4± }
40... Rc2
{ Anand makes a fatal mistake on the last move of the time control.   He pushed the rook one square too far. Instead  40...Rc3  with the idea ...Rxb3 was much better. The difference is that after  41.Rxd5  the knight on b5 can be defended with  41...Rxb3 }
41. Rxd5
{ Once time control was reached, Anand soon realized that his last move blundered the game away and resigned. Black's knight is pushed away from b5, when he will lose the a7-pawn and with it the game.   For example  41...Nc7  42.Rd8+  Kf7  43.Rc8  White is now threatening to win the knight with Bg3.  43...Rc3  is the only way to continue, intending to meet Bg3 with ...Nb5. There's no saving Black's position though, as  44.Be1!  decides the game. After  44...Rc1  45.Kg2  Rxe1  46.Rxc7+  Re7  47.Rb7  Black is completely tied down, while White's king and d-pawn will decide the game.   Anand obtained a splendid position out of the opening with the Scandinavian but then failed to capitalize on his advantage and even ended up losing after a few mistakes.   1-0  (14)  Kasparov, G  (2795)  - Anand, Viswanathan  (2725)  PCA-World Championship New York 1995 }
*

