[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame & Endgame Themes"]
[Black "Model game: 0-1 Meier, V (2310)-Wahls, M (2525) Germany 1993"]
[Result "*"]

{ How to punish unambitious play  The following is a model game between FM Volker Meier and GM Matthias Wahls from the 1993 German Cup. It's an excellent example of Black's plans in the Capablanca structure and how to gradually outplay White from an equal position. }
1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 c6
{ 4...Nf6  5.Nf3  Bf5  is my recommendation in the theory section. } 5. Nf3 Nf6
6. Ne5 Bf5 7. Bd3
{ Exchanging off light-squared bishop is rather unambitious.   7.Bf4  ,  7.Nc4  or  7.h4  are all far more testing. }
7... Bxd3 8. Qxd3 Nbd7 9. Nxd7
{ White is content in exchanging minor pieces, probably content in drawing his higher-rated opponent. }
9... Nxd7 10. Bd2 e6 11. O-O-O O-O-O
{ We have a very typical Scandinavian middlegame where Black is absolutely fine. GM Wahls now gives a textbook example of how to play these positions. First order of business is completing development. }
12. Rhe1 Nf6
{ The knight stands much better on f6 than on d7, where it was obstructing the d8 rook. }
13. Qc4 { White naturally steps out of the x-ray of Black's rook. } 13... Bd6
{ Black has developed all his minor pieces. What should he do now? Target White's d4 pawn of course! He can do so by doubling on the d-file with ...Rd7 and ...Rhd8 as well as transferring the dark-squared bishop to b6. }
14. h3 Bc7 15. Kb1 Qf5
{ The queen wasn't doing much on a5. It's far more active on f5, from where it can target White's kingside pawns. }
16. f3 Rd7 17. Be3 Rhd8
{ Black successfully executed his plan and pressured the d4 pawn. One weakness is usually not enough so Black will now transfer his attention to the kingside, in particular the vulnerable g2 pawn. It's easier to target a weakness that's immobile and Black can fix it with ...h5-h4. }
18. Rd3 h5 19. Red1
{ White firmly defended the d4 pawn and decides to sit tight. It's a very unambitious strategy and one that usually does not pay off. Giving your opponent all the time in the world to gradually improve his position is not a good idea. }
19... h4 { The g2 pawn as well as the weak g3 and f4 squares are now fixed. }
20. a3 { Black's knight isn't doing much so it's time to improve it with }
20... Nd5 21. Nxd5
{ White continues his strategy of exchanging pieces. This exchange makes a lot of sense as Black's d5 knight was far stronger than White's knight on c3. }
21... exd5 22. Qc3
{ The pawn structure has changed prompting Black to reevaluate his setup. The e-file has now opened up, which Black can take over with ...Re7 followed by ...Rde8. }
22... Re8 23. Qe1 Rde7 24. Qg1
{ All of Black's pieces except his bishop are well placed. This piece is most actively placed on g3: }
24... Bg3 25. Ka2
{ Ok, now what? Black has full control of the e-file, but White is holding it up with the bishop on e3. Well, we can easily get rid of it by advancing the f-pawn all the way to f4! Step one in this plan is getting the queen out of the way. }
25... Re6 26. b3 Qf6 27. R1d2 Qd8 28. Rc3 f5
{ Here comes Freddy! White's bishop on e3 is about to be knocked back. } 29.
Rd1 Qe7 30. Bd2 Re2
{ The rook decisevely penetrates the 2nd rank. White won't be able to keep his position together now. }
31. Rd3 Qf6
{ The d4 pawn is now doomed. Once it drops, White's position will collapse. }
32. Kb2 Bf2 33. Qf1 Bxd4+ 34. Bc3 Bxc3+ 35. Rxc3 R8e3
{ With the rook on c3 about to drop, White resigned.  A textbook example of how to play with the Black pieces in the Capablanca structure and punish White's unambitious play. Black first targeted the d4 pawn by doubling on the d-file, then directed his attention to White's kingside and gained space on this side of the board by marching his h-pawn all the way to h4. The pawn structure was then transformed with the e-file opening up. Black immediately took it over and, once his rook reached the e2 square, White's position quickly collapsed.   0-1 @@StartBracket@@35@@EndBracket@@ Meier,V @@StartBracket@@2310@@EndBracket@@-Wahls,M @@StartBracket@@2525@@EndBracket@@ Germany 1993 }
*

