[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame & Endgame Themes"]
[Black "Model game: 0-1 Karpov, A (2705) - Larsen, B (2620) Montreal 1979"]
[Result "*"]

{ The following is one of the most famous games ever played in the Scandinavian.   The Danish legend Bent Larsen - dead last in the Montreal 1979 tournament - decided to unleash the 3...Qa5 Scandinavian against Anatoly Karpov, who was undefeated since becoming World-Champion earlier that year.   This game showcases several important Scandinavian themes: queenside expansion with ...b7-b5, the power of the d5 outpost, and playing on the light squares. As we're about to see, White overextended and was swiftly punished along this color complex. }
1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Bd2 Bg4 6. Be2 Bxe2 7. Ncxe2
{ is a surprising recapture, moving the queenside knight again. There is some sense to this move given that White's queenside knight often finds itself misplaced on c3. By retreating it to e2, the c-pawn is freed to advance and fight for the center. }
7... Qb6 8. Nf3 Nbd7
{ is too slow.   8...e6  followed by ...c5 is my recommendation in thetheory section. This approach doesn't give White any time to expand in the center with c2-c4. }
9. O-O e6 10. c4
{ Karpov takes full control over the center, taking advantage of the fact that Black is ill-positioned to break with ...c5. }
10... Be7
{ 10...Qxb2  Capturing the b2-pawn was possible, although White would have great compensation following  11.c5  Qa3  12.Rb1+=  when Black should give up the b7 pawn to complete development.   10...c5  can just be ignored with  11.Re1  the point being that  11...cxd4  is strongly met by  12.b4±  followed by c5 with a big space advantage. White has all the time in the world to recapture the d4 pawn. }
11. b4 O-O 12. a4
{ White has four pawns ready to march forward. Larsen was seemingly unfazed and justifiably so when you consider Black's position is very solid and without any weaknesses. }
12... c6
{ Black creates a square on c7 for the queen to drop back - a typical safe heaven for Black's queen in the Scandinavian.   Note that the b-pawn is untouchable as  12...Bxb4?  13.a5  Qd6  14.c5+-  wins a piece. }
13. Qc2 Qc7 14. Rfe1 b6
{ Provokes White to push forward with a5. Despite White's big space advantage on the queenside, the machines only offer him a slight edge. The reason is that Black is ultra solid and White's knight on e2 and bishop on d2 aren't particularly well placed.   14...e5?  would have been a premature pawn break. Opening up the position is in White's favor given that his minor pieces are more active.  15.Ng3  e4  16.Nxe4  Nxe4  17.Rxe4+-  would have left White a clean pawn up. }
15. a5
{ is very natural, seeking to open lines on the queenside. The downside of this rather committal decision is that it allows Black to counterattack on the queenside with ...b5 later on.   The preparatory  15.Rab1  was a better option. White can consider improving the position of his knight on e2 with Nc1-d3 next before starting active operations on the queenside. }
15... Rfb8
{ 15...Rab8  Placing this rook on b8 was slightly more precise. Black is ready for ...b5 next. }
16. a6
{ White gains even more space. The a6 pawn is both an asset, boxing in Black's pieces, and a weakness, as it requires constant protection. }
16... b5
{ is a thematic pawn break aimed at conquering the d5 square. An excellent example of thematic play on the light squares! }
17. c5
{ Exchanging off the 'bad' dark-squared bishop with  17.Bf4  doesn't yield much.  17...Bd6  18.Bxd6  Qxd6  19.c5  Qc7  20.Nc3  Rd8=  Black has no problems whatsoever and can look to transfer his d7 knight to g6. }
17... Nd5 18. Nc1 Re8
{ Black correctly reshuffles his rooks to the center of the board. } 19. Nd3
Rad8 20. g3 Bf6
{ Black has a very strong blockade on the light-squares fully offsetting White's space advantage. The game is level. }
21. Re4 Nf8 22. h4 Rd7 23. Kg2 Red8
{ is inaccurate on account of 24. g4.   23...Be7  was a better option. Black has little to worry about on the kingside. }
24. g4 { White is now clearly for choice with good play on the kingside. }
24... Re8 25. g5 Bd8 26. Nfe5 Rde7 27. Bf4
{ 27.Rg4  with the idea h5 was far more challenging. } 27... Qc8
{ Black naturally does not capture the bishop on f4 given how much stronger the d5 knight is. }
28. Bg3 f6
{ Larsen was done waiting around. Instead of waiting for White to slowly advance his kingside pawns, Black decides to knock back White's knight. }
29. Nf3 Rf7 30. Qd2 fxg5
{ Black gives up the e5 square in exchange for the f5 one.   Exchanging dark-squared bishops with  30...Bc7  was a good alternative. }
31. Nxg5
{ is a big positional mistake. White's knight on f3 was far better placed on e5.   31.hxg5  was the correct recapture. Following  31...Ng6  32.Nfe5  Nxe5  33.Nxe5  Rf5=  Black has a full blockade on the light-squares. }
31... Rf5
{ Black is clearly better here. He can gradually improve his position with moves like ...Ng6 and ...Ref8 while White has no active plan. }
32. Ra3 Ng6 33. Nf3
{ White's knight is headed to e5, a clear admission Nxg5 was a mistake. It's a little too late for this. }
33... Ref8 34. Nfe5 Nxe5 35. Rxe5
{ 35.Nxe5  Bc7!  with the big positional threat of capturing on e5. This would leave White defenseless on the light-squares. }
35... Rf3 36. Ra1
{ is a tactical blunder.   White had to cover the fourth rank with  36.Re4 }
36... Bxh4 { Karpov overlooked a rather simple combination. } 37. Qe2
{ The bishop is taboo as  37.Bxh4??  loses on the spot to  37...Rxd3!  38.Qxd3  Nf4+  winning the queen.   37.Rxd5??  is also no good because of  37...exd5!  38.Bxh4  Qh3+  39.Kg1  Qxh4-+  White's king will soon be mated. }
37... Bxg3 38. fxg3 Qd7
{ Black is ready to triple on the f-file with a dominating position. Karpov couldn't allow that and opted for }
39. Qxf3 { 39.Rxe6??  blunders a piece to  39...Rxd3  40.Qxd3  Qxe6-+ } 39...
Rxf3 40. Kxf3 Nxb4 { is a nice tactical blow. White's position now collapses. }
41. Rd1
{ 41.Nxb4  Qxd4  is a triple fork!  42.Rae1  Qxb4  43.Rxe6  h6  There's no saving the c5 or a6 pawns. Black's queenside pawns will easily decide the game. }
41... Qxd4 42. Re4 Qd5 43. Nf2 Qh5+ { 43...Qxc5  was even easier. } 44. Kg2 Nd5
45. Rxe6 h6 { Creates a square for the king on h7. } 46. Rd3 Kh7
{ Black improves the position of his king, taking advantage of the fact that the c6 pawn is untouchable. }
47. Rf3 { 47.Rxc6??  Nb4-+  forks White's rooks. } 47... b4
{ Black's b-pawn easily decided the game. } 48. g4
{ 48.Rxc6??  The pawn on c6 still cannot be taken, this time due to  48...Ne3+!  49.Rxe3  Qd5+  winning the rook on c6. }
48... Qg5 49. Kg3 Qc1 50. Nh3 { 50.Rxc6  Qg1+  51.Kh3  b3-+  is lights out. }
50... Qc4 51. g5 h5 52. Re8 h4+ 53. Kg2 b3 54. Rb8 Qe2+ 55. Nf2
{ 55.Rf2  is no improvement.  55...Qg4+  56.Kh2  Qg3+  57.Kh1  Qxh3+-+  White's king will soon be mated. }
55... Ne3+
{ The rook on f3 cannot be saved. White resigned.   A fantastic game by the Danish legend taking down an in-form Anatoly Karpov, who still went on to win the tournament.  0-1 @@StartBracket@@12@@EndBracket@@ Karpov, A @@StartBracket@@2705@@EndBracket@@ - Larsen, B @@StartBracket@@2620@@EndBracket@@ Montreal 1979. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame & Endgame Themes"]
[Black "c2+d3 Pawn Structure"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnb1kb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/q7/2B5/2NP4/PPP2PPP/R1BQK1NR b KQkq - 0 5"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Instead of occupying the center with d2-d4, White can opt for a more restrained and solid approach where he sets up the c2 + d3 pawn chain. This is aimed at restricting Black's light-squared bishop, which is typically developed to f5. }
5... a6
{ is connected to a very interesting plan in this structure. Black wants to expand on the queenside with ...b5 and fianchetto the light-squared bishop on b7. It'll be far more active on the long diagonal than on f5/g4. }
6. -- b5 7. Bb3 e6
{ White's bishop on b3 frequently ends up being misplaced as it's severely limited by our f7 + e6 pawn chain. }
8. -- Bb7
{ From this square, the bishop cuts across the long-diagonal and exerts significant pressure on White's kingside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame & Endgame Themes"]
[Black "Typical endgame #1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rn2kbnr/pp3ppp/2p1p3/8/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNB1KB1R w KQkq - 0 7"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This is a typical Scandinavian endgame. White has the two bishops while Black has no weaknesses. }
7. -- g6 8. -- h5
{ Black follows the Capablanca rule and places his pawns on the color opposite his bishop, i.e., on light-squares. This restricts White's light-squared bishop while maximizing the scope of Black's dark-squared bishop. }
9. -- Bh6
{ Another common rule when playing against the two bishops is to exchange off one of them. }
10. -- Ne7
{ Routing the g8 knight to f5 with ...Ne7-f5 is another maneuver worth remembering. }
11. -- Nf5
{ White's advanced d4 pawn is frequently a target in the endgame. It can be further undermined by doubling rooks on the d-file. }
