[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian defense, also known as the Center Counter Game, is one of Black's oldest openings, with the first recorded game dating back to 1475. Jumping forward 500+ years, Magnus Carlsen has essayed it with great success. He beat Fabiano Caruana in the 2014 Tromsø Chess Olympiad, drew him in the 2016 Baku Olympiad and defeated 5 time world champion Vishy Anand in the 2019 Kolkata Grand Chess tour. A whole host of other super-GMs such as Nakamura, Kramnik and Firouzja have this defense in their repertoire. }
2. Nc3
{ could have arisen from the Van Geet Opening via the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nc3  d5  2.e4  move order. It's known to be total nonsense but you'll find some troubled souls that like to play like this. }
2... d4
{ Gaining space in the center with tempo is the way to punish White's ridiculous opening.   2...dxe4  is too cooperative. Why activate White's knight for free? It's far better to knock it back with  2...d4! }
3. Nce2 e5
{ Takes firm control over the center. 3 moves in and Black's already better with a significant space advantage. }
4. Ng3 { 4.Nf3  f6  5.Ng3  transposes to the text. } 4... Be6
{ It's important to beat White to the diagonal. } 5. Nf3
{ is White's most popular move. } 5... f6
{ establishes an impressive pawn chain, which stretches all the way from g7 to d4. }
6. Bb5+ c6 7. Ba4
{ 7.Be2  is also possible. After natural moves like  7...Ne7  8.O-O  c5  9.h3  Nbc6  10.d3  Ng6  11.c3  Bd6=+  Black has the upper hand. }
7... Na6 { with the idea ...Nc5 basically forces White to play } 8. Bb3 Bxb3 9.
axb3 d3
{ is a very strong move and a theme worth remembering. Black completely kills White's bishop on c1 and enjoys a significant edge. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "2. d4 Blackmar-Diemer Gambit "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. d4 dxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. f3
{ is the bodacious Blackmar-Diemer Gambit @@StartBracket@@BDG for short@@EndBracket@@. In exchange for a pawn, White gains a tempo and the half-open f-file to operate with. Rapid development and active positioning of the minor pieces with Bc4 and Nf3-e5 is typically the name of the game in this gambit, hoping to start an attack against Black's king.  It might have enjoyed some success in the Romantic era, but today's engines believe it is very suspect. }
4... exf3
{ As the saying goes, the only way to refute a gambit is to accept it! } 5.
Nxf3 c6
{ is the continuation most in spirit with the Scandinavian. Black wants to develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain and then set up an impregnable Capablanca structure with ...e6, claiming he's basically a pawn up for nothing. }
6. Bc4 { Nothing else is really ever played. } 6... Bf5
{ is a good, active square for the bishop. It takes control over the e4 square and can fall back to g6 to cover the f7 pawn if needed.   Watch out! Do not fall for  6...Bg4??  when  7.Bxf7+  is one of the cheapos Blackmar-Diemer Gambiteers love to spring on their unsuspecting victims.  7...Kxf7  8.Ne5+  8...Kg8  9.Nxg4+-  White is winning. }
7. O-O e6 8. Ne5 Bg6
{ is a key move, stepping out of Rxf5 while neutralizing the Nxf7 threat.   And not  8...Nbd7?  which runs into  9.Rxf5  exf5  10.Nxf7+-  Black is busted.   8...Bxc2?  is too creative for Black's own good. If White were obliged to recapture the bishop, then ...Qxd4+ would be excellent. The problem is White has the intermezzo  9.Nxf7  with the upper hand. Clickhere for more details. }
9. Bg5
{ does absolutely nothing.   9.g4  is also harmless.  9...Bd6∓  followed by ...Bxe5 refutes White's 'attack'. }
9... Be7 10. Kh1 Nbd7
{ Black is rock-solid, a pawn up, and thus clearly better. } *

