1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian defense, also known as the Center Counter Game, is one of Black's oldest openings, with the first recorded game dating back to 1475. Jumping forward 500+ years, Magnus Carlsen has essayed it with great success. He beat Fabiano Caruana in the 2014 Tromsø Chess Olympiad, drew him in the 2016 Baku Olympiad and defeated 5 time world champion Vishy Anand in the 2019 Kolkata Grand Chess tour. A whole host of other super-GMs such as Nakamura, Kramnik and Firouzja have this defense in their repertoire. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 3. d4 Nc6
{ It's stronger to prepare the ...e5 break rather than play it straight away. }
4. Nf3 e5 { Black does best in striking in the center right away. } 5. Nc3 Bb4
6. Bd2 Bxc3 { Secures the queen's position in the center of the board. } 7.
Bxc3 e4 8. Ne5 { The only way is forward. } 8... Nxe5 9. dxe5 Ne7 10. Qe2
{ Stepping out of the d-file is White's best move with ideas of g3 followed by Bg2 to corral the e4 pawn as well as Rd1. }
10... Be6 11. g3 { 11.Rd1  can simply be met with  11...Qc6= } 11... e3
{ The e-pawn was a dead-man walking in the long run so we might as well sacrifice it to weaken White's structure. }
12. f3 O-O-O 13. Qxe3 Qc6
{ vacates the d5 square for the knight. White is a pawn up but far behind in development. Not only does Black have full compensation, but White also has to tread carefully to stay in the game.   A sample continuation is  14.Be2  Kb8  covering the a7 pawn.  15.Bd4  b6  improves over the correspondence game ½-½ Chitescu, I @@StartBracket@@2263@@EndBracket@@-Roques, P @@StartBracket@@2306@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2011.  16.O-O-O  Nf5  17.Qc3  Qa4  18.Bf2  Qxa2  gives Black excellent play.   And not  14.Qxa7?  which blunders the f3 pawn to  Qxf3!  15.Rg1   Worse is  15.Qa8+??  which practically loses by force to  Kd7  16.Qa7  Nc6  17.Qg1  Qe4+  18.Kd2  Kc8+  19.Kc1  Bd5-+  wins material.  15...Nc6  16.Qf2  Qe4+  17.Qe2  Qa4∓  Black is clearly better with threats of ...Nd4 and ...f6, blasting open the e-file. }
