[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "3. Nf3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian defense, also known as the Center Counter Game, is one of Black's oldest openings, with the first recorded game dating back to 1475. Jumping forward 500+ years, Magnus Carlsen has essayed it with great success. He beat Fabiano Caruana in the 2014 Tromsø Chess Olympiad, drew him in the 2016 Baku Olympiad and defeated 5 time world champion Vishy Anand in the 2019 Kolkata Grand Chess tour. A whole host of other super-GMs such as Nakamura, Kramnik and Firouzja have this defense in their repertoire. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nf3
{ is the best alternative to 3. Nc3. White doesn't immediately challenge Black's queen and leaves the c-pawn unobstructed. His main idea is to create an ideal center with c2-c4 and d2-d4 before developing the queen's knight to c3. }
3... Bg4
{ is very natural, pinning the knight and threatening to spoil White's structure with ...Bxf3. Black plans to prioritize queenside development with ...Nc6 and ...O-O-O to be ready to fight against White's aggressive  ideas of expanding in the center with c4 and d4. }
4. Be2
{ is the only serious option with the ambitious plan of expanding in the center with d4, c4 and Nc3. Needless to say, we're not going to allow any of this. }
4... Nc6 5. h3
{ I was surprised to see this insipid move recommended in a couple of sources. It's very unimpressive as after }
5... Bxf3 6. Bxf3 Qe6+
{ forces the queens off the board and Black is certainly not worse in the ensuing endgame. }
7. Qe2 Nd4
{ is the cleanest solution, forcing White to capture our queen.   7...Qxe2  is another reliable option, which is given as analternative recommendation up next. }
8. Qxe6 Nxf3+ { is an important in-between move, spoiling White's structure. }
9. gxf3 fxe6
{ Let's take stock. Both sides have doubled pawns on open files. If anything, Black's structure is slightly healthier as White's h-pawn is also weak.  A good development scheme is to fianchetto the dark-squared bishop with ...g6 and ...Bg7.   The g8 knight can head to h5 with ...Nf6-h5, from where it'll be able to jump to f4. Alternatively, it can come out to h6 and then head to h4 or d4 via f5 to target White's f3 pawn.   Black can either castle short or long depending on how White continues but either way a rook is certainly coming to f8 to attack the f3 pawn. }
10. d3
{ is White's most popular move.   Advancing the pawn one square further with  10.d4  is inferior as the pawn will simply become a target.  10...g6  11.Bf4  occurred in the online game 0-1 @@StartBracket@@37@@EndBracket@@ Shahinyan,D @@StartBracket@@2456@@EndBracket@@-Quesada Perez,Y @@StartBracket@@2598@@EndBracket@@ Lichess.org INT 2020. Now the novel  11...O-O-O!⩱  immediately targeting White's d-pawn would have given Black the upper hand. }
10... g6 11. Nc3 Nh6
{ Given that White did not fight for control over the d4 square, developing the knight to h6 aiming to jump into f5 makes a lot of sense. From f5 it can hop to d4 or h4 to attack the f3 pawn. }
12. h4 Nf5 13. Ne4 O-O-O
{ Black will complete development with ...Bg7 on the next turn and can then look to attack White's f3 pawn with the ROVER  (rook up and over!)  ...Rd5-f5, ...Nd4 and ...Rhf8.   The e6 pawn can easily be covered with ...Kd7 if necessary. I certainly like Black's chances. }
*

