1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian defense, also known as the Center Counter Game, is one of Black's oldest openings, with the first recorded game dating back to 1475. Jumping forward 500+ years, Magnus Carlsen has essayed it with great success. He beat Fabiano Caruana in the 2014 Tromsø Chess Olympiad, drew him in the 2016 Baku Olympiad and defeated 5 time world champion Vishy Anand in the 2019 Kolkata Grand Chess tour. A whole host of other super-GMs such as Nakamura, Kramnik and Firouzja have this defense in their repertoire. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nf3
{ is the best alternative to 3. Nc3. White doesn't immediately challenge Black's queen and leaves the c-pawn unobstructed. His main idea is to create an ideal center with c2-c4 and d2-d4 before developing the queen's knight to c3. }
3... Bg4
{ is very natural, pinning the knight and threatening to spoil White's structure with ...Bxf3. Black plans to prioritize queenside development with ...Nc6 and ...O-O-O to be ready to fight against White's aggressive  ideas of expanding in the center with c4 and d4. }
4. Be2
{ is the only serious option with the ambitious plan of expanding in the center with d4, c4 and Nc3. Needless to say, we're not going to allow any of this. }
4... Nc6 5. h3
{ I was surprised to see this insipid move recommended in a couple of sources. It's very unimpressive as after }
5... Bxf3 6. Bxf3 Qe6+
{ forces the queens off the board and Black is certainly not worse in the ensuing endgame. }
7. Qe2
{ is the only serious move.   7.Be2  Nd4=  followed by ...Qxe2 leads to a completely equal endgame. }
7... Qxe2+ 8. Bxe2 O-O-O
{ This natural move was, surprisingly, not considered by GM Avetik Grigoryan in his 3. Nf3 Anti-Scandinavian video series for chessmood.com. Black is ready to expand with ...e5 on the next turn. }
9. c3
{ White wants to get d4, which if would allow would give him some hopes for an edge. }
9... e5 { puts an end to all that. } 10. d3
{ 10.O-O  changes very little.  10...g6  was played in the game 0-1 Van den Doel,E @@StartBracket@@2577@@EndBracket@@-Broekmeulen,J @@StartBracket@@2388@@EndBracket@@ Netherlands 2017, which is analyzed in themodel games section. }
10... g6
{ With ...Bh6 and ...f5 coming next, Black is certainly not worse in this endgame. The extra space fully makes up for White's bishop pair.   A sample continuation is  11.Nd2  Bh6  12.Kd1  f5  13.Kc2  Nf6=  Black will centralize his pieces with ...Rhe8 and ...Nd5 next. He is doing very well. }
