[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian defense, also known as the Center Counter Game, is one of Black's oldest openings, with the first recorded game dating back to 1475. Jumping forward 500+ years, Magnus Carlsen has essayed it with great success. He beat Fabiano Caruana in the 2014 Tromsø Chess Olympiad, drew him in the 2016 Baku Olympiad and defeated 5 time world champion Vishy Anand in the 2019 Kolkata Grand Chess tour. A whole host of other super-GMs such as Nakamura, Kramnik and Firouzja have this defense in their repertoire. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5
{ This is the right place for the queen. Dropping it back with ...Qd6 or ...Qd8 is far more passive and totally uncalled for. }
4. b4
{ is the so-called Leonhardt Gambit, which Nakamura has essayed on occasion and is relatively popular with 500+ games played. This provocative move only works if Black is totally clueless. }
4... Qxb4 { Thanks for the free pawn! } 5. Rb1 Qd6
{ The queen is perfectly safe on d6. Sacrificing an entire pawn just to open the b-file and gain a tempo on the queen doesn't constitute sufficient compensation. }
6. Nf3
{ 6.d4  Firouzja played 6...Qd8 against Nakamura in a blitz game. Much better and far more natural is  6...Nf6  7.Nf3  g6  which transposes to the text.   Going after our queen with  6.Nb5?!  is a mistake. Simply  6...Qd8  retreats the queen to safety when the knight on b5 is completely misplaced and will be promptly kicked back after  7.Nf3  Nf6  8.d4  a6  9.Nc3  c5!∓  undermines White's center with a big advantage for Black. White is simply a pawn down. }
6... Nf6 7. d4 g6
{ With our queen on d6, fianchettoing the bishop makes perfect sense. It also means our king will be very safe.   Provided we keep the following guidelines in mind, we'll emerge with an advantage:  1. If White attacks our queen, we can safely drop it back to d8.  2. The c7 pawn can be covered with ...Na6 in case it's attacked.  3. Avoid creating pawn hooks with moves like ...c6 or ...e6. Only play these moves if strictly necessary.  4. Slow play by White allows us to simply develop with ...Bg7, and ...O-O when the extra pawn will count. }
8. Nb5 Qd8 9. Bf4 Na6
{ adequately covers the c7 pawn. Black will play ...Bg7 followed by ...O-O and the extra pawn will matter in the long run. I'm unsure where White's compensation is. }
*

