1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian defense, also known as the Center Counter Game, is one of Black's oldest openings, with the first recorded game dating back to 1475. Jumping forward 500+ years, Magnus Carlsen has essayed it with great success. He beat Fabiano Caruana in the 2014 Tromsø Chess Olympiad, drew him in the 2016 Baku Olympiad and defeated 5 time world champion Vishy Anand in the 2019 Kolkata Grand Chess tour. A whole host of other super-GMs such as Nakamura, Kramnik and Firouzja have this defense in their repertoire. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5
{ This is the right place for the queen. Dropping it back with ...Qd6 or ...Qd8 is far more passive and totally uncalled for. }
4. Bc4 Nf6 5. d3 a6
{ is my preferred approach here, which was not covered in the database Complete Repertoire against the Alekhine and Scandinavian by GM Zahar Efimenko nor in the book A Simple Chess Opening Repertoire by IM Sam Collins. The idea is to expand on the queenside with ...b5 and develop the light-squared bishop to b7. It'll exert great pressure on White's kingside from this square, and with already having played d3, he no longer has the option of dropping the bishop back to e2 to reinforce the f3 knight. }
6. Bd2 Qf5
{ is an obvious novelty, stepping out of any knight discoveries. Black is now ready to play ...b5. }
7. Nge2
{ is very similar to 7. Nf3 in that Black can execute his plan unfazed. } 7...
b5 8. Bb3 Nc6
{ The knight is more active on c6 than on d7 and we should reserve the latter square for our queen to drop back to in case of Ng3. }
9. Ng3 Qd7
{ Black will complete development with ...e6, ...Bd6 and ...Bb7. He's very comfortable. }
