1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian defense, also known as the Center Counter Game, is one of Black's oldest openings, with the first recorded game dating back to 1475. Jumping forward 500+ years, Magnus Carlsen has essayed it with great success. He beat Fabiano Caruana in the 2014 Tromsø Chess Olympiad, drew him in the 2016 Baku Olympiad and defeated 5 time world champion Vishy Anand in the 2019 Kolkata Grand Chess tour. A whole host of other super-GMs such as Nakamura, Kramnik and Firouzja have this defense in their repertoire. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5
{ This is the right place for the queen. Dropping it back with ...Qd6 or ...Qd8 is far more passive and totally uncalled for. }
4. d4 Nf6 5. Bc4
{ is White's 2nd most common move with over 1500 games played so far. } 5...
Bg4 6. Ne2
{ is White's strongest way of meeting ...Bg4. By developing the knight to e2 @@StartBracket@@as opposed to f3@@EndBracket@@, White has the option of playing f2-f3 at an opportune moment to break the pin. }
6... e6
{ Since White can break the pin at any moment with f3, we're unable to put sufficient pressure on the d4 pawn ...Nc6. As such, we instead opt for the ...e6, ...Nbd7, and ...c6 setup. }
7. O-O
{ NM Logozar stopped here in the Chessable course 1.e4: A Comprehensive White Repertoire and claimed a White advantage. Not only is this way too early to stop the analysis, but White also has no advantage whatsoever. }
7... Nbd7 8. Qe1
{ is both a novelty and White's best move. The queen walks out of the pin along the h5-d1 diagonal and White is ready to go after our light-squared bishop with h3 followed by Ng3. }
8... Bb4 { is an effective counter. } 9. a3
{ can just be ignored as the a1 rook is unprotected. } 9... O-O 10. Be3 Bxc3
11. Nxc3 c6
{ Black is in great shape and can target White's c2 pawn with ...Bf5 as well as expand on the queenside with ...b5 and ...Nb6. White's bishop pair is essentially meaningless here. }
