1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian defense, also known as the Center Counter Game, is one of Black's oldest openings, with the first recorded game dating back to 1475. Jumping forward 500+ years, Magnus Carlsen has essayed it with great success. He beat Fabiano Caruana in the 2014 Tromsø Chess Olympiad, drew him in the 2016 Baku Olympiad and defeated 5 time world champion Vishy Anand in the 2019 Kolkata Grand Chess tour. A whole host of other super-GMs such as Nakamura, Kramnik and Firouzja have this defense in their repertoire. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5
{ This is the right place for the queen. Dropping it back with ...Qd6 or ...Qd8 is far more passive and totally uncalled for. }
4. d4 Nf6 5. Bd2
{ connected with Bc4 is one of White's best approaches in the Scandinavian. The bishop is very well placed on d2, not only breaking the pin but also x-raying Black's queen. }
5... Bg4 6. f3 Bd7
{ The bishop is much better placed here than on  6...Bf5  where it is exposed to  7.g4  Bg6  8.f4!  when Black is in trouble. For example  8...e6  9.f5!  exf5  10.Qe2+±  gives White a big advantage }
7. Bc4
{ comes with a deadly threat of unleashing a discovered attack with Nd5. } 7...
Qb6
{ It's paramount to step out of any knight discoveries. The queen is well placed on b6, taking aim at the b2 and d4 pawns.   Watch out  7...e6??  loses on the spot to  8.Nd5!  Rule to remember: When White's bishops are on d2 and c4, Black's queen cannot stay on a5. }
8. Nge2 e6 9. O-O
{ is most common but not most challenging.   9.a4  a5  10.O-O  Be7  has no independent value. }
9... Be7 10. a4 a5
{ It's important to not let White gain more space on the queenside. } 11. Ne4
{ And now it's time for the typical Scandi central break } 11... e5
{ exploiting the pin along the b6-g1 diagonal. } *

