1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian defense, also known as the Center Counter Game, is one of Black's oldest openings, with the first recorded game dating back to 1475. Jumping forward 500+ years, Magnus Carlsen has essayed it with great success. He beat Fabiano Caruana in the 2014 Tromsø Chess Olympiad, drew him in the 2016 Baku Olympiad and defeated 5 time world champion Vishy Anand in the 2019 Kolkata Grand Chess tour. A whole host of other super-GMs such as Nakamura, Kramnik and Firouzja have this defense in their repertoire. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5
{ This is the right place for the queen. Dropping it back with ...Qd6 or ...Qd8 is far more passive and totally uncalled for. }
4. d4 Nf6 5. Bd2
{ connected with Bc4 is one of White's best approaches in the Scandinavian. The bishop is very well placed on d2, not only breaking the pin but also x-raying Black's queen. }
5... Bg4 6. f3 Bd7 7. f4
{ has yet to been played OTB and was recommended by GM Parimarjan Negi in the book GM Repertoire: 1. e4 vs Minor Defences. While his analysis should always be taken seriously, I don't think this particular recommendation poses Black any serious problems. }
7... Qb6
{ is an important move. While we're not threatening to take the b2 pawn due to Rb1xb7, the d4 pawn is certainly hanging. }
8. Nf3 a6
{ is a useful waiting move and the NNUE engines' top choice. Black's plan here is to target the d4 pawn with ...Nc6. Without ...a6 inserted, this would simply be refuted by Na4, trapping the queen. With ...a6 included, it can now find safe haven on a7.   Note we also delayed ...e6 to have the option of ...Bg4 in certain variations, further increasing the pressure on the d4 pawn.   Worse is  8...e6  as after  9.Bc4  Bb4  10.Qe2  O-O  11.O-O-O±  White's attack on the kingside will be much faster. Our queen is on the way of the b-pawn and we can't even get ...c5 in under good conditions. }
9. Bc4 Nc6 10. Na4
{ The pawn push  10.d5  yields very little after  10...Nd4  11.Nxd4  Qxd4  12.Bb3  Ne4= }
10... Qa7
{ This is the point behind ... a6. The queen can simply drop back to a7, where it's well placed keeping an eye on the d4 pawn. Not only is this pawn hanging, but ...b5 threatens to win material so White has to jump in with }
11. Nc5 Bf5
{ Black should preserve the light-squared bishop.   11...Bg4  isn't as good. After  12.c3  12...e6  13.Nd3+=  White's extra space and grip over the e5 square give him a small edge. }
12. Ne5 { with the idea Nxc6 is White's most ambitious attempt. } 12... e6 13.
Nxc6 bxc6 { The c5 knight is hanging and } 14. Qf3
{ with a counterattack on c6 is White's only chance for an advantage. } 14...
Qb6 { White's knight on c5 is once again in peril, forcing } 15. b4 a5
{ The c2 pawn is en prise and Black is fine here with ...Nd5 coming next. I'd even argue Black's position is easier to play due to White's overextended pawns.  Chessable note: further analysis can be found in themain section of the course. }
