1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian defense, also known as the Center Counter Game, is one of Black's oldest openings, with the first recorded game dating back to 1475. Jumping forward 500+ years, Magnus Carlsen has essayed it with great success. He beat Fabiano Caruana in the 2014 Tromsø Chess Olympiad, drew him in the 2016 Baku Olympiad and defeated 5 time world champion Vishy Anand in the 2019 Kolkata Grand Chess tour. A whole host of other super-GMs such as Nakamura, Kramnik and Firouzja have this defense in their repertoire. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5
{ This is the right place for the queen. Dropping it back with ...Qd6 or ...Qd8 is far more passive and totally uncalled for. }
4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 { is the mainline. } 5... Bf5 6. Bd2 e6 7. Ne5
{ White's idea is to go after our light-squared bishop with g2-g4. } 7... Qb6
{ targets the d4 pawn, effectively neutralizing White's g2-g4 threat . } 8. Qf3
{ White prevents ...Qxd4 due to Qxb7. } 8... c6
{ is simple and effective. The d4 pawn is now hanging.   And not  8...Qxb2??  because of  9.Rb1  Qa3  10.Qxb7+-   8...Bxc2?!  is not a pawn Black should grab. Following  9.Rc1  Bg6  10.h4→  White has a strong initiative.   8...Qxd4??  loses on the spot to  9.Qxb7+- }
9. O-O-O Nbd7
{ Prepares to eliminate White's strong knight on e5, which will solve all of Black's problems. }
10. Nc4 { is almost invariably played. } 10... Qd8
{ Yes, our queen was forced back but White's knight is also misplaced on c4. Black's immediate threat is a skewer with ... Bg4, which White should stop with }
11. h3 Nd5 12. g4 Bg6 13. Ne4 { 13.h4  can simply be blocked with  13...h5= }
13... Qc7
{ Develops the queen and stops a knight from landing on d6, improving over the game 1-0 @@StartBracket@@49@@EndBracket@@ Kovalev,A @@StartBracket@@2580@@EndBracket@@-Westerinen,H @@StartBracket@@2390@@EndBracket@@ Helsinki 1992 where Black played the inferior 13...N7f6. }
14. Bd3 Be7
{ Black can consider breaking with ...c5 and/or expanding on the queenside with ...b5. Black can look to the future with confidence. }
