1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian defense, also known as the Center Counter Game, is one of Black's oldest openings, with the first recorded game dating back to 1475. Jumping forward 500+ years, Magnus Carlsen has essayed it with great success. He beat Fabiano Caruana in the 2014 Tromsø Chess Olympiad, drew him in the 2016 Baku Olympiad and defeated 5 time world champion Vishy Anand in the 2019 Kolkata Grand Chess tour. A whole host of other super-GMs such as Nakamura, Kramnik and Firouzja have this defense in their repertoire. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5
{ This is the right place for the queen. Dropping it back with ...Qd6 or ...Qd8 is far more passive and totally uncalled for. }
4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 { is the mainline. } 5... Bf5 6. Ne5
{ is one of White's most challenging variations in the entire ...Qa5 Scandinavian complex. It's connected with a whole host of ideas, ranging from g4 and Bc4 to Nc4. }
6... c6 7. g4 { is aggressive but nothing to really worry about. } 7... Be6
{ 7...Bg6?  should be avoided due to  8.h4± } 8. Bc4
{ 8.Nc4  accomplishes very little. Simply  8...Qc7=  when White's knight on c4 is completely misplaced. }
8... Nbd7
{ is a very nice resource.   8...Nxg4  wins a pawn but White gets excellent compensation after  9.Bxe6  Nxe5  10.Bb3  Ng6  11.h4  with the idea h5 gives White a big initiative. Black is objectively fine after  11...e6  12.h5  Ne7  13.Bd2  Qc7  but this is something I'd rather avoid. White is the one having all the fun here. }
9. Bxe6 Nxe5
{ Chess is not checkers, and Black is under no obligation to recapture the e6 bishop. It's far better to take on e5! }
10. Qe2 { Attacking the knight is far better than 10. dxe5. } 10... Ng6 11. Bb3
e6
{ Black had a more than acceptable position in the game ½-½ @@StartBracket@@68@@EndBracket@@ Pikula,D @@StartBracket@@2476@@EndBracket@@-Zhukova,N  @@StartBracket@@2471@@EndBracket@@ Belgrade 2000. The bishop on b3 is restricted and White's g-pawn strikes me as nothing but a weakness.  Chessable note: more details can be found in themain section of the course. }
