[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian defense, also known as the Center Counter Game, is one of Black's oldest openings, with the first recorded game dating back to 1475. Jumping forward 500+ years, Magnus Carlsen has essayed it with great success. He beat Fabiano Caruana in the 2014 Tromsø Chess Olympiad, drew him in the 2016 Baku Olympiad and defeated 5 time world champion Vishy Anand in the 2019 Kolkata Grand Chess tour. A whole host of other super-GMs such as Nakamura, Kramnik and Firouzja have this defense in their repertoire. }
2. Nf3
{ The Tennison Gambit has a decent online following, particularly amongst lower-rated players. The idea is to meet ...dxe4 with Ng5.   The problem is White will have to spend a bunch of tempi recouping the pawn and, in the meantime, Black can just expand in the center. }
2... dxe4 3. Ng5 e5
{ Giving back the pawn while taking over the center is the simplest route towards a big advantage.   3...Bf5  is another good option, which was recommended in IndrekR's free Chessable course Taming the Tennison Gambit. }
4. Nxe4
{ 4.h4?!  only weakens White's position. After  4...h6  5.Nxe4  Be6  6.Bb5  c6  7.Be2  Qc7  8.Nbc3  f5∓  Black has full control over the center and a clear advantage.   4.d3?!  isn't much better. The simple  4...Be7  is easy enough.   I also see nothing wrong with the materialistic  4...exd3  as after  5.Bxd3  Nc6  6.O-O  Be7  7.Nf3  Bd6  Black is ready for ...Nge7 and ...Bf5 when White's compensation for the pawn is close to non-existent.  5.Nxe4  Nc6  6.Nbc3  f5∓  is clearly better for Black. }
4... f5
{ Takes over the center and forces White's knight to move for a third time. }
5. Nec3 { 5.Ng3  is no improvement.  5...Nc6∓  Black is clearly better. } 5...
Bc5
{ White's knight went from g1 to c3, where it's not even well placed as it's in the way of the b1 knight. In the meantime, Black has taken full control over the center and is already clearly better. }
