1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian defense, also known as the Center Counter Game, is one of Black's oldest openings, with the first recorded game dating back to 1475. Jumping forward 500+ years, Magnus Carlsen has essayed it with great success. He beat Fabiano Caruana in the 2014 Tromsø Chess Olympiad, drew him in the 2016 Baku Olympiad and defeated 5 time world champion Vishy Anand in the 2019 Kolkata Grand Chess tour. A whole host of other super-GMs such as Nakamura, Kramnik and Firouzja have this defense in their repertoire. }
2. e5 { is a move you'll encounter every now and then. } 2... c5 3. Bb5+
{ has been played in 100+ games. It makes no sense to me and the only reason I'm showing you this line is because of one remarkable plan we're about to see. }
3... Bd7 4. Bxd7+ Nxd7
{ White spent two tempi developing his light-squared bishop just to exchange it on d7 and develop our knight for us! }
5. Nf3
{ The pawn sacrifice  5.e6  can just be taken with  5...fxe6  6.Nf3  and now Black should play  6...e5!   And not  6...Ngf6  which runs into  7.Qe2  when White is able to recoup the pawn.  in order to be able to meet  7.Qe2  with  7...e4∓ }
5... e6 6. O-O g5
{ is the remarkable plan I teased a couple of moves ago. The idea is to undermine the f3 knight, which is the sole defender of the e5 pawn. }
7. d4
{ We all know that a counterattack in the center is the best response to a flank attack.   7.h3?  is a big mistake and creates a hook for Black's attack. After  7...h5  8.d4  g4−+  White is staring down a vicious attack. The engines are already giving Black a decisive advantage. }
7... g4 8. Ne1 cxd4 9. Qxg4
{ Capturing the other pawn with  9.Qxd4?!  is worse. After  9...h5∓  Black's g8 knight will quickly come to f5 when White will have a very hard time keeping the e5 pawn alive. }
9... Nxe5 10. Qxd4 Bg7
{ Black eliminated White's center and is already slightly better. The immediate threat is ...Nf3+ and ...Ne7-c6 is also coming. }
