1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian defense, also known as the Center Counter Game, is one of Black's oldest openings, with the first recorded game dating back to 1475. Jumping forward 500+ years, Magnus Carlsen has essayed it with great success. He beat Fabiano Caruana in the 2014 Tromsø Chess Olympiad, drew him in the 2016 Baku Olympiad and defeated 5 time world champion Vishy Anand in the 2019 Kolkata Grand Chess tour. A whole host of other super-GMs such as Nakamura, Kramnik and Firouzja have this defense in their repertoire. }
2. e5 { is a move you'll encounter every now and then. } 2... c5
{ Takes control over the d4 square. White's e5 pawn is merely a target here. }
3. c3
{ Preparing the d4 advance to reinforce the e5 pawn is White's best option.   The immediate  3.d4?!  is premature. After  3...cxd4  4.Qxd4  White's queen is a big target, which can be immediately attacked with  4...Nc6  5.Bb5  e6  6.Nf3  a6  7.Bxc6  bxc6∓  gives Black the bishop pair and a clear advantage. Next up is ...c6-c5 with excellent central control. }
3... Bf5
{ Black develops the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain before playing ...e6.   3...Nc6  and  3...d4  are good alternatives. }
4. d4 e6
{ On the board, we have a much-improved version of the Advance variation of the Caro-Kann where Black got in ...c5 in one go. You can also look at this as an Advance French on steroids with Black's light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain. }
5. Nf3 Nc6 6. Be2 cxd4
{ is a timely capture, leaving White with a weak, backward pawn on d4. } 7.
cxd4 Bb4+ 8. Nc3 Nge7 9. O-O O-O
{ Black is ready for ...Be4 and ...Nf5 next, with good play against White's d4 pawn. }
