1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian defense, also known as the Center Counter Game, is one of Black's oldest openings, with the first recorded game dating back to 1475. Jumping forward 500+ years, Magnus Carlsen has essayed it with great success. He beat Fabiano Caruana in the 2014 Tromsø Chess Olympiad, drew him in the 2016 Baku Olympiad and defeated 5 time world champion Vishy Anand in the 2019 Kolkata Grand Chess tour. A whole host of other super-GMs such as Nakamura, Kramnik and Firouzja have this defense in their repertoire. }
2. Nc3
{ could have arisen from the Van Geet Opening via the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nc3  d5  2.e4  move order. It's known to be total nonsense but you'll find some troubled souls that like to play like this. }
2... d4
{ Gaining space in the center with tempo is the way to punish White's ridiculous opening.   2...dxe4  is too cooperative. Why activate White's knight for free? It's far better to knock it back with  2...d4!   If the Caro-Kann, French, or Alekhine are part of your Black repertoire you can opt for  2...c6  ,  2...e6  or  2...Nf6  respectively. Nevertheless,  2...d4!  is the only way to punish White's dubious play. }
3. Nce2 e5
{ Takes firm control over the center. 3 moves in and Black's already better with a significant space advantage. }
4. f4
{ is a very premature break.   4.d3  isn't much of an improvement.  4...c5  5.g3  Now sending Harry down the board gives Black a big edge  5...h5  6.f4  h4∓ }
4... Nc6 5. d3 exf4 { resolves the central tension in Black's favor. } 6. Bxf4
Nge7 { The knight is headed to g6 to take over the e5 square. } 7. Nf3 Ng6 8.
Bg3 Bg4
{ is about as bad it looks for White. Black can continue with natural moves like ... Bd6, ...Qd7, and ...O-O-O. Marching the h-pawn down the board with ...h5-h4 is also worth considering later on. }
*

