{ This chapter is primarily dedicated to refuting the bodacious Blackmar-Diemer Gambit, which occurs after }
1. e4 d5 2. d4 dxe4 3. Nc3 { 3.f3  seen in 300+ games is premature. } 3... Nf6
{ Apart from } 4. f3
{ we're also going to examine  4.Bg5  played in 1000+ games.   and the rarer  4.Bc4  essayed 300+ times. }
4... exf3
{ As the saying goes, the only way to refute a gambit is to accept it! } 5.
Nxf3 c6
{ is the continuation most in spirit with the Scandinavian. Black wants to develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain and then set up an impregnable Capablanca structure with ...e6, claiming he's basically a pawn up for nothing.   5...g6  is Black's strongest continuation and was my recommendation in the course Beat 1.d4 systems. I wanted to recommend a different line here, particularly one that closer resembled Scandinavian structures and themes. Black can count on at least a clear advantage in all the lines after 5...c6 making it an excellent choice. }
