1. e4 d5 2. d4 dxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. f3
{ is the bodacious Blackmar-Diemer Gambit  (BDG for short)  . In exchange for a pawn, White gains a tempo and a half-open f-file. Rapid development and active positioning of the minor pieces with Bc4 and Nf3-e5 is typically the name of the game in this gambit, hoping to start an attack against Black's king.  It might have enjoyed some success in the Romantic era, but today's engines believe it is very suspect. }
4... exf3
{ As the saying goes, the only way to refute a gambit is to accept it! } 5.
Nxf3
{ 5.Qxf3?  blunders a pawn to  5...Qxd4  6.Be3  Qg4−+  with  6...Qd8−+  also being excellent. }
5... c6
{ is the continuation most in spirit with the Scandinavian. Black wants to develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain and then set up an impregnable Capablanca structure with ...e6, claiming he's basically a pawn up for nothing. }
6. Bd3
{ is inferior to  6.Bc4  as it doesn't put any pressure on the f7 pawn. } 6...
Bg4
{ While ...Bf5 is not possible, the bishop is perfectly well placed on g4. } 7.
O-O
{ 7.h3  drops the d4 pawn to  7...Bxf3  8.Qxf3  Qxd4  White's best is  9.Be3  Following  9...Qh4  10.g3  Qb4  11.O-O-O  Nbd7  12.g4  e6  13.g5  Ne5  14.Qe2  Nfd7⩱  Black will castle queenside next with the upper hand. }
7... e6
{ Black will complete development with ...Be7, ...O-O and ...Nbd7 next. White has insufficient compensation for the pawn deficit. }
*

