[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. 2.d4 | Blackmar-Diemer Gambit"]
[Black "7. Bg5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. d4 dxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. f3
{ is the bodacious Blackmar-Diemer Gambit  (BDG for short)  . In exchange for a pawn, White gains a tempo and a half-open f-file. Rapid development and active positioning of the minor pieces with Bc4 and Nf3-e5 is typically the name of the game in this gambit, hoping to start an attack against Black's king.  It might have enjoyed some success in the Romantic era, but today's engines believe it is very suspect. }
4... exf3
{ As the saying goes, the only way to refute a gambit is to accept it! } 5.
Nxf3 c6
{ is the continuation most in spirit with the Scandinavian. Black wants to develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain and then set up an impregnable Capablanca structure with ...e6, claiming he's basically a pawn up for nothing. }
6. Bc4 { Nothing else is really ever played. } 6... Bf5
{ is a good, active square for the bishop. It takes control over the e4 square and can fall back to g6 to cover the f7 pawn if needed. }
7. Bg5
{ is another option, usually connected with the idea of playing Qe2 and castling long. }
7... Nbd7
{ Black reinforces the f6 knight and will develop in standard fashion with ...e6 and ...Be7. }
8. Qe2
{ 8.Nh4?!  is well met by  8...Bg4  9.Qd3  Nb6  10.Bb3  e6∓  with the upper hand. A sample continuation is  11.h3  Bh5  12.g4  h6!  13.Bf4  Nfd5!∓  which highlights how misplaced the knight is on h4. }
8... e6 9. O-O-O Be7
{ This natural developing move was not considered in the book The Blackmar-Diemer Gambit: A Modern Guide to a Fascinating Chess Opening by IM Christoph Scheerer, who only examined  9...Bb4  The text is much stronger since it blocks the e-file and the x-ray White's queen was exerting on our king, neutralizing any ideas White had of getting in d4-d5. }
10. Bxf6
{ 10.Ne5  has also occurred in several games. After  10...Nxe5  11.dxe5  Nd5  12.Bxe7  Qxe7  13.Ne4  White is now threatening to jump into d6 but  13...Bxe4  is an easy enough solution.  14.Qxe4  a5∓  Black is clearly for choice. He's a pawn up and has ideas of ...b5 and Qb4. }
10... Nxf6 11. Ne5
{ White is now threatening to expand on the kingside with g2-g4.   11.Rhf1  is strongly met by  11...b5  expanding on the queenside with tempo. Following  12.Bb3  Bg4  13.h3  Bxf3  14.Qxf3  Rc8∓  Black will castle short next and will be the only one attacking with ...a5 on the agenda.   11.d5?  doesn't work due to  cxd5  12.Nxd5   12.Bb5+  Kf8-+  and White is now two pawns down.  12...exd5  13.Bxd5  Nxd5  14.Qb5+  Bd7  15.Qxd5  Qc7  16.Rhe1  Be6  blocks the e-file and after  17.Qb5+  Kf8-+  White is simply a piece down. }
11... h5 { Stops the immediate g4 and if White insists with } 12. h3 { then }
12... h4
{ stops g4 for good @@StartBracket@@technically White can still play it but we'll just capture en passant@@EndBracket@@. Next up is ...Qc7 with a clear advantage. We can cover the f7 pawn with ...g6 and ...Rh7, which will then enable us to castle long. }
