1. e4 d5 2. d4 dxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. f3
{ is the bodacious Blackmar-Diemer Gambit  (BDG for short)  . In exchange for a pawn, White gains a tempo and a half-open f-file. Rapid development and active positioning of the minor pieces with Bc4 and Nf3-e5 is typically the name of the game in this gambit, hoping to start an attack against Black's king.  It might have enjoyed some success in the Romantic era, but today's engines believe it is very suspect. }
4... exf3
{ As the saying goes, the only way to refute a gambit is to accept it! } 5.
Nxf3 c6
{ is the continuation most in spirit with the Scandinavian. Black wants to develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain and then set up an impregnable Capablanca structure with ...e6, claiming he's basically a pawn up for nothing. }
6. Bc4 { Nothing else is really ever played. } 6... Bf5
{ is a good, active square for the bishop. It takes control over the e4 square and can fall back to g6 to cover the f7 pawn if needed.   Watch out! Do not fall for  6...Bg4??  when  7.Bxf7+  is one of the cheapos Blackmar-Diemer Gambiteers love to spring on their unsuspecting victims.  7...Kxf7  8.Ne5+  8...Kg8  9.Nxg4+-  White is winning. }
7. O-O e6 8. Ne5 Bg6
{ is a key move, stepping out of Rxf5 while neutralizing the Nxf7 threat.   And not  8...Nbd7  which runs into  9.Rxf5  exf5  10.Nxf7+-  Black is busted.   8...Bxc2  is too creative for Black's own good. If White were obliged to recapture the bishop, then ...Qxd4+ would be excellent. The problem is White has the intermezzo  9.Nxf7  with the upper hand. }
9. Nxg6
{ 9.g4  is strongly met by  9...Bd6  intending to chop on e5.  10.Bf4  Bxe5  11.Bxe5  Nbd7  12.Bg3  O-O  is an obvious novelty. Now  13.h4  is easily answered with  13...h6∓  when White has no follow-up on the kingside. }
9... hxg6 10. h3 Nbd7
{ Black is ready to develop his bishop to d6, followed by ...Qc7 and ...O-O-O. }
11. Bf4 { prevents the immediate ...Bd6 but Black gets it in after } 11... Nb6
12. Bb3 Bd6
{ Black has scored 4/4 from this position against players rated between 2000 and 2450. Enough said. }
