[White "3. Various 3rd moves"]
[Black "3. c4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian defense, also known as the Center Counter Game, is one of Black's oldest openings, with the first recorded game dating back to 1475. Jumping forward 500+ years, Magnus Carlsen has essayed it with great success. He beat Fabiano Caruana in the 2014 Tromsø Chess Olympiad, drew him in the 2016 Baku Olympiad and defeated 5 time world champion Vishy Anand in the 2019 Kolkata Grand Chess tour. A whole host of other super-GMs such as Nakamura, Kramnik and Firouzja have this defense in their repertoire. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 3. c4
{ White attacks our queen and wants to establish a strong central pawn duo with d4 next. }
3... Qe4+
{ disrupts White's plan. He has no convenient way of blocking the check. } 4.
Qe2 Qxe2+ 5. Bxe2 Nc6
{ is an important move, taking control over the key d4 square. } 6. Nf3 e5
{ Stops d4 for good. Coming up are ...Bf5 and ...O-O-O with a big advantage. White has a backward pawn on a semi-open file plus very weak d3 and d4 squares. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Various 3rd moves"]
[Black "3. d3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian defense, also known as the Center Counter Game, is one of Black's oldest openings, with the first recorded game dating back to 1475. Jumping forward 500+ years, Magnus Carlsen has essayed it with great success. He beat Fabiano Caruana in the 2014 Tromsø Chess Olympiad, drew him in the 2016 Baku Olympiad and defeated 5 time world champion Vishy Anand in the 2019 Kolkata Grand Chess tour. A whole host of other super-GMs such as Nakamura, Kramnik and Firouzja have this defense in their repertoire. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 3. d3
{ was recommended by FM Kamil Plitcha in the Chessable course Reign Supreme: The King's Indian Attack. I have a hard time believing this move is any good and the neural network engines are also not a fan. Just ask the bishop on f1 what it feels about d2-d3. }
3... Bf5
{ is my preferred option and was not considered in the aforementioned Chessable course. Kamil only looked at 3...Nf6 but the text is far stronger.   The point is to be able to meet 4. Nc3 with 4...Qd7 without obstructing the light-squared bishop. Since White is likely to fianchetto the bishop on g2, the queen will be ideally placed to support a future ...Bh3. }
4. Nc3 Qd7
{ The queen is perfectly well placed on d7, controlling the d4 square, supporting a future ...Bh3 and away from any discovered attacks @@StartBracket@@had it instead gone to a5, then Black would have to watch out for knight discoveries after Bd2@@EndBracket@@. White already needs to be careful not to end up significantly worse. }
5. Nf3 Nc6 6. g3
{ Going for the King's Indian attack fianchetto setup doesn't work well due to }
6... e5
{ taking over the center. 6 moves in and Black is already better thanks to the extra space and superior central control. }
7. Bg2 O-O-O 8. Be3 f6
{ Reinforces the e5 pawn and gives Black a sizeable advantage with ideas of ...Nge7, ...Bh3, and even ...h4-h5. White has less space and little control over the center. Two sample continuations are:   9.Qe2  clearing the way for O-O-O is strongly met by  9...Nd4!  10.Bxd4  exd4  11.Ne4  Bb4+  12.Nfd2  Bg4∓  when White has big issues.   9.O-O  Castling kingside walks straight into an attack after  Bh3  10.Bxh3  Qxh3∓  White is in big trouble with ...h5-h4 and ...Ne7-f5 coming next. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Various 3rd moves"]
[Black "3. d4 4. Be3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian defense, also known as the Center Counter Game, is one of Black's oldest openings, with the first recorded game dating back to 1475. Jumping forward 500+ years, Magnus Carlsen has essayed it with great success. He beat Fabiano Caruana in the 2014 Tromsø Chess Olympiad, drew him in the 2016 Baku Olympiad and defeated 5 time world champion Vishy Anand in the 2019 Kolkata Grand Chess tour. A whole host of other super-GMs such as Nakamura, Kramnik and Firouzja have this defense in their repertoire. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 3. d4
{ is a logical move. The d4 pawn is however more of a target than an asset. }
3... Nc6
{ It's stronger to prepare the ...e5 break rather than play it straight away.   3...e5  4.Nc3  Qxd4   4...Bb4  5.Nge2  exd4  6.Qxd4  5.Qxd4  exd4  6.Nb5  are endgames I'd rather avoid. Black's winning chances are very limited. }
4. Be3 { is far less common than 4. Nf3. } 4... e5 5. Nc3
{ 5.Nf3  has also been tried.  5...exd4  6.Nxd4  Bb4+  7.c3  Bd6=  is very comfortable.   5.c4  Qa5  6.Bd2  Bb4  7.d5  Nd4=  is completely fine. }
5... Bb4
{ The d4 pawn is under fire and Black is threatening to spoil White's structure with ...Bxc3. }
6. Ne2
{ 6.a3  allows  6...Bxc3+  7.bxc3  Qa5=+  Black was already much better, going on to win in 0-1 @@StartBracket@@35@@EndBracket@@ Shianovsky,V @@StartBracket@@2299@@EndBracket@@-Gordenko,D @@StartBracket@@2352@@EndBracket@@ Kiev 2002. }
6... exd4 7. Nxd4 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Nge7
{ is an obvious novelty with the engine bar already dipping below zero. White has the two bishops but his queenside pawn structure is in shambles. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
