1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian defense, also known as the Center Counter Game, is one of Black's oldest openings, with the first recorded game dating back to 1475. Jumping forward 500+ years, Magnus Carlsen has essayed it with great success. He beat Fabiano Caruana in the 2014 Tromsø Chess Olympiad, drew him in the 2016 Baku Olympiad and defeated 5 time world champion Vishy Anand in the 2019 Kolkata Grand Chess tour. A whole host of other super-GMs such as Nakamura, Kramnik and Firouzja have this defense in their repertoire. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 3. d4 Nc6
{ It's stronger to prepare the ...e5 break rather than play it straight away.   3...e5  4.Nc3  Qxd4   4...Bb4  5.Nge2  exd4  6.Qxd4  5.Qxd4  exd4  6.Nb5  are endgames I'd rather avoid. Black's winning chances are very limited. }
4. Nf3 e5 { Now's the time to strike in the center! } 5. dxe5
{ cannot be recommended. } 5... Qxd1+ 6. Kxd1 Bg4
{ White has lost castling rights and will not be able to hold onto the e5 pawn. }
7. Bf4
{ 7.Be3  is what White should go for when  7...Nxe5=  is at least equal. I'd certainly take Black. }
7... Bc5
{ Targets the f2 pawn, forcing White's dark-squared bishop to move yet again. }
8. Bg3 O-O-O+
{ improves over the game ½-½ @@StartBracket@@88@@EndBracket@@ Rocha,S @@StartBracket@@2427@@EndBracket@@-Silva,A @@StartBracket@@2224@@EndBracket@@ Lisbon 1999, where Black played 8...Bd4. Immediately bringing the rook into the game sets White a lot more problems. }
9. Nd2 Nge7
{ The e5 pawn will eventually drop with ...Nf5 and ...Rhe8 to follow. White's king is stuck in the center of the board and he's already at least slightly worse. }
