[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian defense, also known as the Center Counter Game, is one of Black's oldest openings, with the first recorded game dating back to 1475. Jumping forward 500+ years, Magnus Carlsen has essayed it with great success. He beat Fabiano Caruana in the 2014 Tromsø Chess Olympiad, drew him in the 2016 Baku Olympiad and defeated 5 time world champion Vishy Anand in the 2019 Kolkata Grand Chess tour. A whole host of other super-GMs such as Nakamura, Kramnik and Firouzja have this defense in their repertoire. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nf3
{ is the best alternative to 3. Nc3. White doesn't immediately challenge Black's queen and leaves the c-pawn unobstructed. His main idea is to create an ideal center with c2-c4 and d2-d4 before developing the queen's knight to c3. }
3... Bg4
{ is very natural, pinning the knight and threatening to spoil White's structure with ...Bxf3. Black plans to prioritize queenside development with ...Nc6 and ...O-O-O to be ready to fight against White's aggressive  ideas of expanding in the center with c4 and d4. }
4. Be2
{ is the only serious option with the ambitious plan of expanding in the center with d4, c4 and Nc3. Needless to say, we're not going to allow any of this. }
4... Nc6 5. O-O { is too slow. } 5... O-O-O
{ With our rook on d8, White will never get d4 in meaning he can never be any better.   Black can easily equalize and oftentimes even gain the upper hand provided he keeps the following guidelines in mind:  1. Black's standard plan is to expand in the center with ...e5  2. Nc3 to attack our queen should be met with ...Qd7  3. If White puts the question to our bishop with h2-h3, we should only play ...Bxf3 if we can follow up with ...Nd4. Otherwise, we should retreat the bishop with ...Bh5  4. h2-h3 is the perfect hook for us to launch a strong attack against White's king with ...g5-g4  5. b4-b5 hitting our c6 knight is usually strongly met by the in-between move ...Bxf3! followed by ...Nd4  White has several different move orders  (play h3 immediately and only then d3, play d3 first and then h3, forego h3 entirely, start with Nc3, etc)  . There are many possible transpositions but you don't need to worry about this. Sticking to the guidelines above will allow you to easily navigate these positions.   Watch out! Do not play  5...e5?  because of  6.h3  when  6...Bh5  7.Nc3  Qd7  is refuted by  8.Nxe5!  It's important to be aware of this tactical trick and get our king to safety right away with 5...O-O-O. }
6. h3
{ 6.Nc3  Qd7  7.h3  Bh5  has no independent value. White has other options apart from 7. h3 but there's no need to cover anything else as they're completely harmless.   6.d3  is subpar as it lets Black expand in the center with  6...e5  uncontested. Check out the game 0-1 Braun, G @@StartBracket@@2385@@EndBracket@@-Wahls, M @@StartBracket@@2570@@EndBracket@@ Germany 1992 in themodel games chapter for more details. }
6... Bh5
{ Guidelines #3 says we should only take on f3 if we can follow up with ...Nd4.   Here  6...Bxf3?!  is met by  7.Bxf3  with a tempo on our queen. Obviously,  7...Nd4??  is not possible and we should thus retreat the bishop to  h5  . }
7. Nc3 { As per guidelines #2, Nc3 should be met with } 7... Qd7 8. b4
{ This caveman-style attack is White's most popular continuation. With the kings castled on opposite wings, it makes perfect sense to start a pawn assault. }
8... Nf6
{ Black should continue development unfazed by White's aggressive intentions. }
9. Rb1 g5
{ is a mirror reaction to White's b-pawn advance. The key difference is White has already played h3, meaning Black will burst open the g-file, and his attack will be faster.   Note that  10.Nxg5  is strongly met by  10...Rg8!  11.d3  Bxe2  12.Nxe2  h6!  13.Nf3  Qxh3⭢  with a big attack. }
