1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nf3 Bg4 4. Be2 Nc6 5. O-O O-O-O 6. h3 Bh5 7. Nc3 Qd7
8. b4 Nf6 9. d3
{ was recommended by GM Simon Williams and Richard Palliser in the Chessable course Grandmaster Gambits: 1.e4 Part 2. I found this recommendation very surprising since White @@StartBracket@@yes, you read that right!@@EndBracket@@ has to be very precise not to end up in massive trouble.   The simplest and most practical option is  9...Rg8  instead, which is mymain recommendation.   Advanced players might prefer the more ambitious and theoretically demanding  9...Nxb4  - a direct attempt at refuting White's 'attack'. This is given as analternative recommendation. Simon and Richard failed to Black's most ambitious approachhere, which requires White to be precise to stay in the game. }
