1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian defense, also known as the Center Counter Game, is one of Black's oldest openings, with the first recorded game dating back to 1475. Jumping forward 500+ years, Magnus Carlsen has essayed it with great success. He beat Fabiano Caruana in the 2014 Tromsø Chess Olympiad, drew him in the 2016 Baku Olympiad and defeated 5 time world champion Vishy Anand in the 2019 Kolkata Grand Chess tour. A whole host of other super-GMs such as Nakamura, Kramnik and Firouzja have this defense in their repertoire. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nf3
{ is the best alternative to 3. Nc3. White doesn't immediately challenge Black's queen and leaves the c-pawn unobstructed. His main idea is to create an ideal center with c2-c4 and d2-d4 before developing the queen's knight to c3. }
3... Bg4
{ is very natural, pinning the knight and threatening to spoil White's structure with ...Bxf3. Black plans to prioritize queenside development with ...Nc6 and ...O-O-O to be ready to fight against White's aggressive  ideas of expanding in the center with c4 and d4. }
4. Be2
{ is the only serious option with the ambitious plan of expanding in the center with d4, c4 and Nc3. Needless to say, we're not going to allow any of this. }
4... Nc6 5. d4
{ is at least twice as popular as the alternatives. If White is allowed to play c4 undisturbed, he'll roll Black over in the center. }
5... O-O-O
{ is an important move. The pressure on the d4 pawn prevents White from comfortably establishing a pawn duo with c4 and d4. Anything but c4 will now be met with ...e5. }
6. Be3
{ is the second most popular move. White reinforces the d4 pawn in anticipation of ...e5. White wants to play Nd2 next, which would unpin the d-pawn and stabilize White's center. }
6... e5
{ Rule to remember: When White plays Be3 with the idea Nd2, Black should immediately strike in the center.  The pressure on the d4 pawn forces White to either play Nc3 or c4, thus preventing Nbd2. }
7. c4 { 7.c3  Nge7  is covered via the6. c3 7. Be3 move order. } 7... Qa5+ 8.
Bd2 Qa6
{ is Black's best move, despite being 3 times less common than 8...Bb4. The threat of ...exd4 forces White to advance one of his central pawns. }
9. d5 Bxf3 10. Bxf3 Nd4 11. Be2
{ 11.b3?!  is strongly met by  11...f5  12.O-O  e4  13.Bh5  Nf6  14.Nc3  Nxh5  15.Qxh5  Qg6  16.Qxg6  hxg6=+  Black has the upper hand in this endgame. He can look to reroute his knight with ...Nc2-b4-d3. }
11... c6
{ Breaks down White's center and gives Black an excellent game. The knight on d4 is a beast.   A sample continuation is  12.Nc3  Kb8  13.dxc6  Qxc6  14.O-O  Nf6  15.Re1  Bd6  16.Bf1  This was all recommended in the Chessable course Smash the Scandinavian Defense by Zac Attack. He only considered  16...Rhe8  but  16...e4!  Opening up the d6 bishop's gaze towards White's king is far stronger and gives Black the upper hand with ...Ng4 coming next.  17.Qc1  Ng4  18.h3  h5!  is very strong. White has to be very careful to not lose outright. }
*

