2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nf3
{ is the best alternative to 3. Nc3. White doesn't immediately challenge Black's queen and leaves the c-pawn unobstructed. His main idea is to create an ideal center with c2-c4 and d2-d4 before developing the queen's knight to c3. }
3... Bg4
{ is very natural, pinning the knight and threatening to spoil White's structure with ...Bxf3. Black plans to prioritize queenside development with ...Nc6 and ...O-O-O to be ready to fight against White's aggressive  ideas of expanding in the center with c4 and d4. }
4. Be2
{ is the only serious option with the ambitious plan of expanding in the center with d4, c4 and Nc3. Needless to say, we're not going to allow any of this. }
4... Nc6 5. d4
{ is at least twice as popular as the alternatives. If White is allowed to play c4 undisturbed, he'll roll Black over in the center. }
5... O-O-O
{ is an important move. The pressure on the d4 pawn prevents White from comfortably establishing a pawn duo with c4 and d4. Anything but c4 will now be met with ...e5. }
6. Be3
{ is the second most popular move. White reinforces the d4 pawn in anticipation of ...e5. }
6... e5
{ Rule to remember: When White plays Be3 with the idea Nd2, Black should immediately strike in the center.  The pressure on the d4 pawn forces White to either play Nc3 or c4, thus preventing Nbd2. }
7. c4 Qa5+ 8. Bd2 Qa6
{ is Black's best move, despite being 3 times less common than 8...Bb4. The threat of ...exd4 forces White to advance one of his central pawns. }
9. c5 { tries to trap our queen but fails short due to } 9... Bxf3 10. gxf3
{ No, our queen isn't trapped as we have } 10... b5 11. d5
{ is a rare option that has only been played a couple of times. It was recommended by GM Gawain Jones in the book Coffeehouse Repertoire 1.e4: Volume 1 for Quality Chess. As we're about to see, Black has nothing to worry about. }
11... Nd4 { The knight should naturally jump into the center of the board. }
12. d6 { is White's idea, intending to open up the queenside. } 12... cxd6 13.
Nc3
{ 13.Na3  has no independent value transposing to the text after  13...dxc5  14.Nxb5 }
13... dxc5 14. Nxb5 Nxe2 15. Qxe2
{ Gawain Jones stopped here assessing this position as unclear. He wrote A murky position has arisen. Black is currently a pawn up but with a wide-open king. Our next couple of moves will be b2-b4 and Rc1, when there's still a lot of pressure on Black's position.  Unclear assessments in a White repertoire book are typically a red flag and code for Black is fine, I just don't want to admit it. Let's bring some clarity to this position by continuing for a few more moves. }
15... Nf6
{ The pawn on e5 is untouchable since the b5 knight requires protection. } 16.
b4
{ Yes, our king on c8 is not the safest but it turns out White's king on e1 is just as exposed. Let's blast open the e-file with the powerful break }
16... e4
{ I suspect GM Gawain Jones underestimated this resource which flips the tables on his assessment. White's the one that needs to be careful in this line. }
17. fxe4 Nxe4
{ White's pieces are very awkwardly placed. The knight on b5 is pinned and White's queen can't step out of the e-file since it's tied to the defense of White's knight. }
18. Be3
{ Removes the bishop from danger.   18.Nxa7+  is also possible. After  18...Qxa7  19.Qxe4  Bd6  20.O-O  Rhe8  21.Qg4+  Qd7  22.Qg2  Re6↑  the only side attacking here is Black with the threat of ...Rg6.   There's no time for  18.bxc5  as after  18...Bxc5-+  White's king on  e1  is toast. }
18... Nd6
{ Undermining the pinned piece. This forces an endgame where Black is up a pawn but White should hold with precise play: }
19. Nxd6+ Rxd6 20. Rc1 Re6 21. Qxa6+ Rxa6 22. O-O
{ 22.Rc2  is well met by  22...Kb7  23.bxc5  Be7  24.Rg1  Bf6  25.Rg4  Kc6=  with a level endgame where Black is the only side that can push. }
22... Rxa2
{ Black is currently two pawns up. The c5 pawn will soon drop and White should hold the resulting pawn down endgame. All in all, Black is in great shape in this line and if anything it's White that needs to tread carefully. }
