{ is very natural, pinning the knight and threatening to spoil White's structure with ...Bxf3. Black plans to prioritize queenside development with ...Nc6 and ...O-O-O to be ready to fight against White's aggressive  ideas of expanding in the center with c4 and d4. }
4. Be2
{ is the only serious option with the ambitious plan of expanding in the center with d4, c4 and Nc3. Needless to say, we're not going to allow any of this. }
4... Nc6 5. d4
{ is at least twice as popular as the alternatives. If White is allowed to play c4 undisturbed, he'll roll Black over in the center. }
5... O-O-O
{ is an important move. The pressure on the d4 pawn prevents White from comfortably establishing a pawn duo with c4 and d4. Anything but c4 will now be met with ...e5. }
6. c4
{ is White's most common move. The first player erects a strong central pawn duo and intends to quickly reinforce it with Be3 and Nbd2. Black cannot allow this to happen.   6.Nc3  Qa5  7.Be3  e5  transposes to the text. }
6... Qf5 7. Be3
{ White is once again 'threatening' to unpin the d-pawn and stabilize the center with Nbd2. Black can use the following tactical combination to prevent this: }
7... Bxf3 { This exchange would not have much point if not for } 8. Bxf3 Nxd4
{ The point is Black is ready to meet Bg4 with ...Nc2+. Case in point: } 9. Bg4
Nc2+ 10. Qxc2 Qxg4 11. O-O e5 { Note that } 12. Bxa7
{ doesn't bother us at all. White is the one that should be worried after }
12... Ne7
{ as ...Ng6/f5-h4 is coming very fast. The first player needs to be very careful to keep his head above water. }
