1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian defense, also known as the Center Counter Game, is one of Black's oldest openings, with the first recorded game dating back to 1475. Jumping forward 500+ years, Magnus Carlsen has essayed it with great success. He beat Fabiano Caruana in the 2014 Tromsø Chess Olympiad, drew him in the 2016 Baku Olympiad and defeated 5 time world champion Vishy Anand in the 2019 Kolkata Grand Chess tour. A whole host of other super-GMs such as Nakamura, Kramnik and Firouzja have this defense in their repertoire. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5
{ This is the right place for the queen. Dropping it back with ...Qd6 or ...Qd8 is far more passive and totally uncalled for. }
4. b4
{ is the so-called Leonhardt Gambit, which Nakamura has essayed on occasion and is relatively popular with 500+ games played. This provocative move only works if Black is totally clueless. }
4... Qxb4 { Thanks for the free pawn! } 5. Rb1
{ is the move you'll face almost every time.   5.a4?!  with the idea Ba3 makes little sense. After  5...a6  6.Ba3  Black's queen finds a good home on a5  6...Qa5  making it impossible for White to expand with d4 as the c3 knight would then hang.  7.Nf3  Nc6  8.Bc4  Nf6∓  White has next to no compensation for the pawn deficit. }
5... Qd6
{ The queen is perfectly safe on d6. Sacrificing an entire pawn just to open the b-file and gain a tempo on the queen doesn't constitute sufficient compensation. }
6. Nf3
{ 6.d4  For unknown reasons, Firouzja played ...Qd8 against Nakamura here in a blitz game. Much better and far more natural is  6...Nf6  7.Nf3  g6  which transposes to the text.   Going after our queen with  6.Nb5?!  is a mistake. Simply  6...Qd8  retreats the queen to safety when the knight on b5 is completely misplaced and will be promptly kicked back after  7.Nf3  Nf6  8.d4  a6  9.Nc3  c5!∓  which undermines White's center with a big advantage for Black. White is simply a pawn down. }
6... Nf6 7. d4 g6
{ With our queen on d6, fianchettoing the bishop makes perfect sense. It also means our king will be very safe.   Provided we keep the following guidelines in mind, we'll emerge with an advantage:  1. If White attacks our queen, we can safely drop back to d8.  2. The c7 pawn can be covered with ...Na6 in case it's attacked.  3. Avoid creating pawn hooks with moves like ...c6 or ...e6. Only play these moves if strictly necessary.  4. Slow play by White allows Black to simply develop with ...Bg7, and ...O-O when the extra pawn will count. }
8. g3
{ Fianchettoing the light-squared bishop with hopes to put pressure on our queenside is a common setup. }
8... Bg7 9. Bg2
{ 9.Bf4  is natural but doesn't trouble Black as it only encourages the queen to retreat to a safe square, which Black was likely going to end up playing anyhow.  9...Qd8  Note that  10.Nb5  is strongly met by  10...Nd5!  covering the  c7  pawn with tempo. White's pieces will now be forced back:  10.Bd2  a6  knocks back the knight with a big advantage. }
9... O-O 10. O-O
{ Our kingside is developed and now we need to get our queenside pieces out. The bishop on b7 is tied down to the defense of the b7 pawn so we should bring our knight out first with }
10... Nc6
{ We no longer need the knight to go to a6 as   11.Nb5  Qd8  12.Bf4  can now be met with  12...Nd5! }
11. Re1 Qd8
{ is a strong prophylactic move, getting the queen out of danger. Black is now ready to fight for an advantage with ...Na5 and remember that we're already a pawn up! }
12. d5 Na5
{ The knight is superbly placed on a5, keeping an eye on the b7 pawn and the vulnerable c4 square. White's b2-b4 advance left the first player with a hole on c4 and a backward pawn on c2, which Black is more than happy to exploit! }
13. Ba3
{ 13.Ne5  is strongly met by  13...Nd7  immediately challenging White's central knight. A sample continuation is  14.Bf4  Nxe5  15.Bxe5  Bxe5  16.Rxe5  Nc4  Black is in great shape and will follow up with ...Re8 and ...Nd6 next. }
13... Re8 14. Qe2
{ White is homing in on the e7 pawn but we can simply push it forward with }
14... e6 { with the upper hand. White doesn't have enough for the pawn. } *

