[White "5. 3.Nc3 | Sidelines"]
[Black "4. b4 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian defense, also known as the Center Counter Game, is one of Black's oldest openings, with the first recorded game dating back to 1475. Jumping forward 500+ years, Magnus Carlsen has essayed it with great success. He beat Fabiano Caruana in the 2014 Tromsø Chess Olympiad, drew him in the 2016 Baku Olympiad and defeated 5 time world champion Vishy Anand in the 2019 Kolkata Grand Chess tour. A whole host of other super-GMs such as Nakamura, Kramnik and Firouzja have this defense in their repertoire. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5
{ This is the right place for the queen. Dropping it back with ...Qd6 or ...Qd8 is far more passive and totally uncalled for. }
4. b4
{ is the so-called Leonhardt Gambit, which Nakamura has essayed on occasion and is relatively popular with 500+ games played. This provocative move only works if Black is totally clueless. }
4... Qxb4 { Thanks for the free pawn! } 5. Rb1
{ 5.a4?!  with the idea Ba3 makes little sense. After  5...a6  6.Ba3  Black's queen finds a good home on a5  6...Qa5  making it impossible for White to expand with d4 as the c3 knight would then hang.  7.Nf3  Nc6  8.Bc4  Nf6∓  White has next to no compensation for the pawn deficit. }
5... Qd6
{ The queen is perfectly safe on d6. Sacrificing an entire pawn just to open the b-file and gain a tempo on the queen doesn't constitute sufficient compensation. }
6. Nf3
{ 6.d4  For unknown reasons, Firouzja played ...Qd8 against Nakamura here in a blitz game. Much better and far more natural is  6...Nf6  7.Nf3  g6  which transposes to the text.   Going after our queen with  6.Nb5?!  is a mistake. Simply  6...Qd8  retreats the queen to safety when the knight on b5 is completely misplaced and will be promptly kicked back after  7.Nf3  Nf6  8.d4  a6  9.Nc3  c5!∓  which undermines White's center with a big advantage for Black. White is simply a pawn down. }
6... Nf6 7. Bc4 { is strongly met by } 7... a6
{ Black is ready to expand on the queenside with ...b5. } 8. d4 b5 9. Bb3
{ 9.Bd3  has yet to be played. Black gets a clear advantage with  9...Bb7  10.O-O  e6  11.a4  b4  12.Na2  a5∓ }
9... c5
{ is both novel and strong, improving over the game 1-0  (65)  Nakamura,H  (2651)  -Har Zvi,R  (2515)  ICC INT 2007 where Black played the inferior 9...Bb7. }
10. Ne5
{ 10.dxc5  runs into  10...Qxd1  11.Nxd1  e6  12.Be3  Ne4∓  with a clear advantage for Black. }
10... e6
{ The tempting  10...c4  allows  11.Bxc4  bxc4  12.Qf3  Ra7  13.Bf4  when White has excellent compensation. }
11. Qf3
{ 11.Bf4  might look strong but is entirely harmless. Black can simply retreat with  11...Qc7  12.Ng6  Qa5  13.Nxh8  Qxc3  14.Bd2  Qxd4−+  White's knight on h8 will eventually drop. Black's two minor pieces will then be much stronger than White's rook. }
11... Qc7
{ is a stunning resource! Black is threatening both ...Qb7 and ...cxd4 so White has no good option but to go ahead and capture the rook on a8 with }
12. Qxa8 { 12.Bf4  Bb7−+  is lights out. } 12... cxd4
{ Apart from both of White's knights being en prise, we're also threatening to win White's queen with ...Bb7 followed by ...Bc5. }
13. Bf4
{ 13.Ne2  loses on the spot to  13...Bb7  14.Qa7  Bc5  Trapping White's queen!   13.Qf3  is strongly met by  13...Bb7  14.Qg3  dxc3  15.Nf3  Qxg3  16.hxg3  Be7∓  Black is clearly for choice in this endgame with two pawns and a knight for White's rook. Importantly, White's bishop on b3 is severely restricted. }
13... Qxc3+ 14. Kf1 Bd6 15. Nxf7
{ Retreating with  15.Qf3  doesn't help much. After  15...Qc7  16.Nd3  O-O∓  Black has a big advantage with 2 pawns and a knight for White's rook, not to mention White's king on f1. }
15... Bxf4 16. Nxh8 d3
{ White's exposed king combined with the threat of ...dxc2 are decisive. Her majesty on a8 is sorely missed in the defense.   Scooting it over with  17.Qf3  is a little too late. After  17...dxc2  18.Qxc3  cxb1=Q  19.Qe1  Qxe1  20.Kxe1  Kf8−+  White's knight on h8 will soon drop. Black has a decisive material advantage. }
