[Black "4. Rb1 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian defense, also known as the Center Counter Game, is one of Black's oldest openings, with the first recorded game dating back to 1475. Jumping forward 500+ years, Magnus Carlsen has essayed it with great success. He beat Fabiano Caruana in the 2014 Tromsø Chess Olympiad, drew him in the 2016 Baku Olympiad and defeated 5 time world champion Vishy Anand in the 2019 Kolkata Grand Chess tour. A whole host of other super-GMs such as Nakamura, Kramnik and Firouzja have this defense in their repertoire. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5
{ This is the right place for the queen. Dropping it back with ...Qd6 or ...Qd8 is far more passive and totally uncalled for. }
4. Rb1
{ Not subtle at all! White wants to expand with b2-b4 without sacrificing a pawn. }
4... c6 { Allows us to drop back our queen to safety. } 5. b4 Qd8
{ The queen is better placed on d8 than on c7. On the latter square, it would be subject to a tempo with g3 and Bf4. }
6. g3 Nf6
{ Similar to the Leonhardt Gambit, we are going to develop our kingside with ...g6 and ...Bg7. }
7. Bg2
{ is White's best setup. The plan is to complete development and then increase the scope of his bishop with b4-b5, placing our queenside under pressure. }
7... g6 8. Nge2 Bg7 9. O-O O-O 10. b5
{ White gets his break in but we're well prepared to meet it. } 10... cxb5 11.
Rxb5 Nc6
{ blocks White's light-squared bishop. The plan is to knock back White's rook with ...a6 and then post the knight on a5. }
12. d4
{ This position was reached in the game 0-1  (48)  Berchtenbreiter,M  (2405)  -Nisipeanu,L  (2674)  Bad Wiessee 2013.   Black played  12...Ne8  with the idea ...Nd6.  The novel }
12... a6 { immediately getting rid of Black's rook is even stronger. } 13. Rb1
Na5
{ Yes, the knight is on the rim but it's far from dim! It's excellently placed on a5, covering the b7 pawn and taking control over the weak c4 square. }
14. Na4 { is White's best move, heading into b6. } 14... Be6
{ Active counterplay! Black goes after the a2 pawn and couldn't care less about sacrificing an exchange after }
15. Nb6 Bxa2 16. Rb2 { is strongly met by } 16... Nc4 17. Rxa2 Qxb6
{ Black will bring a rook to c8 and is already slightly for choice. White's c and d-pawns are nothing but targets. Moreover, Black has the outside a passed pawn meaning any endgames will likely be in his favor.  Black is very close to consolidating by bringing the rooks to the central files. White's only hope is to oust our knight from the c4 square and play c2-c4. The only thing Black should know to deal with this is that c2-c4 should be met with ...b7-b5, undermining White's center. Therefore, retreating with ...Qc7 freeing up the b-pawn is also on Black's agenda.   A sample continuation illustrating this is  18.Qd3  Rac8  19.Ra4  Qc7  20.Bf4  Nd6  21.c4  Qd7  22.Rfa1  b5  with an excellent game. }
