1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian defense, also known as the Center Counter Game, is one of Black's oldest openings, with the first recorded game dating back to 1475. Jumping forward 500+ years, Magnus Carlsen has essayed it with great success. He beat Fabiano Caruana in the 2014 Tromsø Chess Olympiad, drew him in the 2016 Baku Olympiad and defeated 5 time world champion Vishy Anand in the 2019 Kolkata Grand Chess tour. A whole host of other super-GMs such as Nakamura, Kramnik and Firouzja have this defense in their repertoire. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5
{ This is the right place for the queen. Dropping it back with ...Qd6 or ...Qd8 is far more passive and totally uncalled for. }
4. Bc4 Nf6 5. d3 a6
{ is my preferred approach here, which was not covered in the database Complete Repertoire against the Alekhine and Scandinavian by GM Zahar Efimenko nor in the book A Simple Chess Opening Repertoire by IM Sam Collins. This rare move was first played by the creative Spanish GM David Larino.  The idea is to expand on the queenside with ...b5 and develop the light-squared bishop to b7. It'll exert great pressure on White's kingside from this square, and with already having played d3, he no longer has the option of dropping the bishop back to e2 to reinforce the f3 knight. }
6. Bd2 Qf5
{ is an obvious novelty, stepping out of any knight discoveries. Black is now ready to play ...b5. }
7. Nf3 { allows Black to execute his plan: } 7... b5 8. Bb3 Bb7 9. O-O e6
{ Coming up are ...Bd6 and ...O-O. While Black isn't better yet, he can easily take over in the upcoming middlegame given how misplaced White's light-squared bishop is. Our bishops on b7 and d6 will exert great pressure on White's kingside. }
*

