16. a4
{ is White's best move. It prevents ...axb4 due to a5.   16.Na4  yields nothing after  16...Qb7= }
16... Nd5
{ Do not fall for  16...axb4??  as it runs into  17.a5!  Qb8  18.Qxc6++-  winning. }
17. g4
{ This aggressive approach needs to be checked. It seems a bit too optimistic to me. }
17... Bxc2 { I see nothing wrong with grabbing the c2 pawn. } 18. Bxd5 cxd5 19.
Rc1 Bxa4
{ is forced. Black already has two pawns for the minor piece and both b4 and d4 will drop in the next couple of moves. }
20. Nxa4 Qxd4 21. Nc5 axb4
{ Black has 4 pawns for the piece, the knight on c5 has to retreat and White's king is very exposed. I don't care how many zeros Stockfish spits at me, White's position is very hard to handle.   For example  21...axb4  22.Nb3  Qb2  23.Rxc7  Bd6  24.Rc6  Ra3→  gives Black a great initiative. White has to play like an engine to hold this, the correct way to do so being  25.Bc1  Qb1  26.O-O  Rxb3  27.Qe2  Ke7  28.Rxd6  Kxd6  29.Qa6+=  and White barely escapes with a perpetual. }
