{ In for a penny, in for a pound! The tactics work out well for Black. } 15.
Bxa5 dxc4 16. Qxc4 Nxa5 17. Re3+ Be6
{ Three pieces for the queen are usually more than sufficient, with this position being no exception. Stockfish is shooting an endless string of zeros at me and I won't argue with it.   Two sample continuations are  18.Rxe6  fxe6  19.Qxe6  Be7  20.Ng3  Rf8  21.O-O   21.Nf5?!  is a good illustration of how easily White can go wrong. After  21...Rf7  22.O-O  Kf8  23.Re1?  Re8−+  White is in big trouble along the e-file with ...Bb4 being a huge threat.  21...Rd8  22.c3  Rd7=  Black will slowly but surely untangle with ...Nd5 planned next. White has to be accurate to maintain the balance. }
