10. O-O Be7
{ 10...Qxb2  Here this doesn't work because of  11.a4±  with the deadly threat of Bb3 followed by Ra2 trapping and winning our queen. }
11. Ne4 O-O
{ Black can look to complete development with ...Nc6-a5, ...Rd8 and ...Bb5.  I covered all of this in my White course Crush the Alekhine and Scandinavian, where I claimed White had a slight advantage here @@StartBracket@@do note that I still believe that this is one of White's strongest options in the entire Scandinavian complex@@EndBracket@@.  I no longer believe White is objectively better here. The latest version of Leela now assesses the position as equal. Stockfish initially gives White a slight plus, but the longer it thinks the closer it gravitates towards equality. Having spent a number of hours with various cloud engines analyzing this position, my conclusion is that Black is fine with precise play.   Here's one of the machine's top lines at high depth:  12.a4  Nc6!  13.c3  Na5  14.Nxf6  Bxf6  15.Bd3  e5  16.b4  Nc6  17.a5  Qa7  18.Bf2  exd4  19.Qc2  g6  20.Be4  Rad8  21.Bxc6  Bxc6  22.Nxd4  GM Justin Tan stopped here claiming White was slightly better in the book 1.e4! The Chess Bible. This evaluation is incorrect and Black is completely fine after the simple  22...Qb8  23.Nxc6  bxc6  24.Bc5  Rfe8=  The doubled pawns are irrelevant here since they cannot be attacked. Black will post his queen on b5 and there's no reason for White to be any better @@StartBracket@@for reference both Leela and Stockfish assess this as 0.00@@EndBracket@@.  Higher-rated/ambitious players that want to train this clickable variation can do so in the nextalternative line. }
