1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian defense, also known as the Center Counter Game, is one of Black's oldest openings, with the first recorded game dating back to 1475. Jumping forward 500+ years, Magnus Carlsen has essayed it with great success. He beat Fabiano Caruana in the 2014 Tromsø Chess Olympiad, drew him in the 2016 Baku Olympiad and defeated 5 time world champion Vishy Anand in the 2019 Kolkata Grand Chess tour. A whole host of other super-GMs such as Nakamura, Kramnik and Firouzja have this defense in their repertoire. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5
{ This is the right place for the queen. Dropping it back with ...Qd6 or ...Qd8 is far more passive and totally uncalled for. }
4. d4 Nf6 5. Bc4
{ is White's 2nd most common move with over 1500 games played so far. } 5...
Bg4 6. Nf3
{ is third most common. White doesn't mind the pin and develops the knight to its most natural square. }
6... Nc6
{ We follow suit, developing our c6 knight to its most active post, and are ready to attack the d-pawn with ...O-O-O next.   We are under no obligation to play  6...e6  Instead, it's far stronger to immediately pressure White's d4 pawn, taking advantage of the fact that the knight on f3 is pinned. }
7. d5
{ immediately walks into trouble along the d-file.   7.Be3  O-O-O  8.h3  e5!  is a very strong intermezzo. Black ignores the attack on the bishop and instead strikes in the center. Following  9.hxg4  exd4  10.Nxd4  Bc5  Black recoups the piece with a big advantage. }
7... O-O-O 8. Bd2 Nd4
{ There's no stopping ...Nxf3, which will ruin White's pawn structure. Black has a big advantage. }
