1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian defense, also known as the Center Counter Game, is one of Black's oldest openings, with the first recorded game dating back to 1475. Jumping forward 500+ years, Magnus Carlsen has essayed it with great success. He beat Fabiano Caruana in the 2014 Tromsø Chess Olympiad, drew him in the 2016 Baku Olympiad and defeated 5 time world champion Vishy Anand in the 2019 Kolkata Grand Chess tour. A whole host of other super-GMs such as Nakamura, Kramnik and Firouzja have this defense in their repertoire. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5
{ This is the right place for the queen. Dropping it back with ...Qd6 or ...Qd8 is far more passive and totally uncalled for. }
4. d4 Nf6 5. Bc4
{ is White's 2nd most common move with over 1500 games played so far. } 5...
Bg4 6. Ne2
{ Having examined 6. f3 and 6. Nf3, it's now turn to examine White's final and strongest option of dealing with ...Bg4. }
6... e6
{ Since White can break the pin at any moment with f2-f3, we're unable to put sufficient pressure on the d4 pawn ...Nc6. As such, we instead opt for the ...e6, ...Nbd7, and ...c6 setup. }
7. f3
{ With ...e6 already on the board, f2-f3 is stronger as Black can no longer retreat the bishop to d7. }
7... Bf5 8. g4 Bg6 9. h4 h6
{ is a necessary move, creating a square for the bishop on h7. At first sight, it may look like White is doing very well with lots of space. However, it's yet to be determined whether the advanced pawns are an asset or a liability. }
10. Bd2
{ White's bishops are on d2 and c4, which signals that our queen cannot stay on a5. }
10... Qb6 { This is one of the rare instances when Nd5 is a threat. } 11. a4 a6
12. Nf4 Bh7
{ Now the only way for White to pose any problems is to push ahead with } 13.
d5 { which we should just bypass with } 13... e5 14. a5
{ A nice in-between move, luring our queen to c5 so as to later hit it with Nd3. }
14... Qc5 15. Qe2 { White covers the bishop on c4 while pinning the e-pawn. }
15... Nbd7
{ Black will castle long on the next turn with a level game. White's bishop on c4 and knight on f4 will have to retreat, a good indication there's not much for Black to worry about.   Note that  16.g5  fails to  16...hxg5  17.hxg5  Bd3!-+  A bolt from the blue that gives Black a decisive advantage! }
