1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian defense, also known as the Center Counter Game, is one of Black's oldest openings, with the first recorded game dating back to 1475. Jumping forward 500+ years, Magnus Carlsen has essayed it with great success. He beat Fabiano Caruana in the 2014 Tromsø Chess Olympiad, drew him in the 2016 Baku Olympiad and defeated 5 time world champion Vishy Anand in the 2019 Kolkata Grand Chess tour. A whole host of other super-GMs such as Nakamura, Kramnik and Firouzja have this defense in their repertoire. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5
{ This is the right place for the queen. Dropping it back with ...Qd6 or ...Qd8 is far more passive and totally uncalled for. }
4. d4 Nf6 { We're finally ready to deal with White's main move: } 5. Nf3
{ There's nothing more natural than developing both knights to their most active posts. }
5... Bf5
{ is my preferred choice.   Despite not being as popular  5...c6  Black scores better with this move @@StartBracket@@and in fact has a 50% score against 2700+ opposition@@EndBracket@@, and the NNUE engines also rate it significantly higher. Strategically, it's a more flexible move giving Black the options of going ...c5 in one go or developing the b8 knight to c6. }
6. Bd3
{ is a common move at the club level but entirely harmless. Exchanges only help Black who has less space. }
6... e6
{ Rather than improve the position of White's queen with  6...Bxd3  Black instead invites White to capture on f5. }
7. O-O
{ 7.Bxf5  only improved the position of Black's queen in the game  7...Qxf5=  0-1 @@StartBracket@@40@@EndBracket@@ Barle,J @@StartBracket@@2420@@EndBracket@@-Larsen,B @@StartBracket@@2620@@EndBracket@@ Bled/ Portoroz 1979 }
7... Bxd3 8. Qxd3 Be7 9. Bf4 c6
{ Black had an excellent position in 0-1 @@StartBracket@@21@@EndBracket@@ Nurbekoglu, M-Lentrodt,T @@StartBracket@@2260@@EndBracket@@ Passau 1995.   A sample continuation is  10.Ne4  Nxe4  11.Qxe4  Nd7  12.Rfe1  O-O  13.c4  Rfd8  14.Qc2  Nf8  followed by ...Ng6, ...Bf6 and ...Qb6 homing in on White's d4 pawn. }
*

