1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian defense, also known as the Center Counter Game, is one of Black's oldest openings, with the first recorded game dating back to 1475. Jumping forward 500+ years, Magnus Carlsen has essayed it with great success. He beat Fabiano Caruana in the 2014 Tromsø Chess Olympiad, drew him in the 2016 Baku Olympiad and defeated 5 time world champion Vishy Anand in the 2019 Kolkata Grand Chess tour. A whole host of other super-GMs such as Nakamura, Kramnik and Firouzja have this defense in their repertoire. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5
{ This is the right place for the queen. Dropping it back with ...Qd6 or ...Qd8 is far more passive and totally uncalled for. }
4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 { is the mainline. } 5... Bf5 6. Ne5
{ is one of White's most challenging variations in the entire ...Qa5 Scandinavian complex. It's connected with a whole host of ideas, ranging from g4 and Bc4 to Nc4. }
6... c6 7. Bf4
{ has occurred in a few top-level games. White adopts a central strategy and is planning to follow up with Nc4 with the idea Nd6+ to trade Black's dark-squared bishop when he eventually plays ...e6. }
7... Nbd7 { Challenging White's knight. } 8. Nc4
{ White has more space and so he logically avoids trading pieces. } 8... Qd8 9.
Qe2
{ with the rather obvious checkmating threat of Nd6+ is easily neutralized with }
9... e6 10. Nd6+
{ White's knight managed to jump into d6 but fails to achieve anything of value. }
10... Bxd6 11. Bxd6 Nb6
{ Depending on which diagonal White chooses to drop his bishop back to, Black will complete development with either 12...Qc7 followed by 13...O-O-O or 12...O-O without a worry in the world. }
