1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian defense, also known as the Center Counter Game, is one of Black's oldest openings, with the first recorded game dating back to 1475. Jumping forward 500+ years, Magnus Carlsen has essayed it with great success. He beat Fabiano Caruana in the 2014 Tromsø Chess Olympiad, drew him in the 2016 Baku Olympiad and defeated 5 time world champion Vishy Anand in the 2019 Kolkata Grand Chess tour. A whole host of other super-GMs such as Nakamura, Kramnik and Firouzja have this defense in their repertoire. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5
{ This is the right place for the queen. Dropping it back with ...Qd6 or ...Qd8 is far more passive and totally uncalled for. }
4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 { is the mainline. } 5... Bf5 6. Ne5
{ is one of White's most challenging variations in the entire ...Qa5 Scandinavian complex. It's connected with a whole host of ideas, ranging from g4 and Bc4 to Nc4. }
6... c6 7. Bf4
{ has occurred in a few top-level games. White adopts a central strategy and is planning to follow up with Nc4 with the idea Nd6+ to trade Black's dark-squared bishop when he eventually plays ...e6. }
7... Nbd7 { Challenging White's knight. } 8. Nc4
{ White has more space and so he logically avoids trading pieces. } 8... Qd8 9.
Ne3
{ is White's only way of fighting for an edge. Correspondence games have shown Black can effectively neutralize White's initiative with precise play. }
9... Be6
{ is the correct retreat. The plan is to fianchetto the dark-squared bishop with ...g6. The bishop on e6 is very well placed, limiting White's knight on e3.   9...Bg6  10.h4→  is unpleasant to face. }
10. a4
{ with the idea a5 is both novel and very interesting. White's gains space while restricting our d7 knight and plans to route the light-squared bishop to f3 to pressure our queenside. }
10... g6 11. a5
{ 11.Be2  is not congruent with White's last move. Here I like  11...Qa5!  stopping White's pawn dead in its tracks and securing the b6 square for the d7 knight. After  12.Bc4  Bxc4  13.Nxc4  the queen finds a safe square with  13...Qf5= }
11... Nh5
{ Black needs to get this in right away before White plays Be2. The point behind this move is to force White's bishop off of the b8-h2 diagonal. }
12. Bg5 Bg7 13. Be2
{ Now  13...Ndf6  fails to completely equalize but Black has the very precise }
13... h6 { knocking back White's bishop with the point that after } 14. Bh4 Bf6
{ effectively forces the bishops off the board. It might look strange to exchange off the fianchetto bishop but once White captures it, ...Nd7xf6 will cover the h5 knight. More importantly, the f4 square will then be very weak and a great outpost for this knight. }
15. Bxf6
{ 15.Bg3  hands over the bishop pair to  15...Nxg3=  when Black's chances are preferable. }
15... Ndxf6 16. Bf3 Rc8 17. O-O O-O
{ Black is doing very well. He'll complete development by placing the queen on d6/c7 and bring the f8 rook to d8 to target White's vulnerable d4 pawn. The knight on h5 is temporarily on the rim but can jump into the weak f4 square  (or alternatively reroute itself with ...Ng7-f5)  . }
