1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian defense, also known as the Center Counter Game, is one of Black's oldest openings, with the first recorded game dating back to 1475. Jumping forward 500+ years, Magnus Carlsen has essayed it with great success. He beat Fabiano Caruana in the 2014 Tromsø Chess Olympiad, drew him in the 2016 Baku Olympiad and defeated 5 time world champion Vishy Anand in the 2019 Kolkata Grand Chess tour. A whole host of other super-GMs such as Nakamura, Kramnik and Firouzja have this defense in their repertoire. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5
{ This is the right place for the queen. Dropping it back with ...Qd6 or ...Qd8 is far more passive and totally uncalled for. }
4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 { is the mainline. } 5... Bf5 6. Ne5
{ is one of White's most challenging variations in the entire ...Qa5 Scandinavian complex. It's connected with a whole host of ideas, ranging from g4 and Bc4 to Nc4. }
6... c6 7. Bf4
{ has occurred in a few top-level games. White adopts a central strategy and is planning to follow up with Nc4 with the idea Nd6+ to trade Black's dark-squared bishop when he eventually plays ...e6. }
7... Nbd7 { Challenging White's knight. } 8. Nc4
{ White has more space and so he logically avoids trading pieces. } 8... Qd8 9.
d5
{ is White's most enterprising option. White wants to open up the position to try and exploit his slightly lead in development. }
9... cxd5 10. Ne3
{ 10.Nxd5  allows Black to liberate his position with  10...e5!  A nice point is that  11.Nde3  is strongly met by the tactical shot  11...Bxc2!  12.Nxc2  exf4  13.Qe2  Be7  14.Nd6  Kf8∓  Black continued with ...g6 and had the upper hand in the game ½-½ @@StartBracket@@42@@EndBracket@@ Morawietz,D @@StartBracket@@2438@@EndBracket@@-Coenen,N @@StartBracket@@2379@@EndBracket@@ Germany 2007. }
10... Be4 { Black is ready to liberate his position with the ...e5 break. } 11.
f3 { We get in } 11... e5 { anyhow. } 12. Bg5
{ Removing the bishop from danger is the move White should go for. } 12... a6
{ is a strong prophylactic move, preventing Bb5. } 13. Qe2
{ Turns out Black doesn't need to care about the e4 bishop at all. We can simply push ahead with }
13... d4 { forking White's knights. } 14. Nxe4 Qa5+
{ This precise check solves all of Black's problems. } 15. Qd2 Qxd2+ 16. Nxd2
h6
{ is a strong intermezzo. Two of White's pieces are now hanging, effectively forcing }
17. Bxf6 dxe3 { And here comes the second intermezzo! } 18. Bh4 exd2+ 19. Kxd2
Be7
{ Black is in great shape in this endgame. Despite falling outside the scope of an opening course, this is a very interesting endgame, so I decided to analyze it in the subsequent clickables. When learning a new opening, it's important to not just learn the theory but to also explore the ensuing middlegames and endgames. This way you develop other parts of your game in the process.   20.Bxe7  is rather compliant, relinquishing the bishop pair advantage and developing our king for us  20...Kxe7  21.Re1  Kf6  22.c3  Rhd8  23.Kc2  b5=  gives Black excellent play on the queenside with ...Rac8, ...Nb6 and possibly even ...b4 on the agenda. The second player can also look to mobilize his kingside pawn majority with ...Ke6 and ...f5 later on.   Alternatively  20.Bf2  is well met by  20...Bc5  insisting on the bishop exchange to neutralize White's bishop pair.  21.Bg3  keeping the two bishops is White's most ambitious try.   21.Bxc5  is once again too cooperative.  21...Nxc5  22.Re1  O-O-O+  23.Kc3  f6=  is also great. Black has ideas of ...b5 and ...Na4+ as well as the simple ...Ne6 followed by doubling on the d-file with ...Rd6 and ....Rhd8.  21...O-O-O  22.Bd3  h5=  with the idea ...h4 to knock back White's bishop. Our knight can then be activated with ...Nf8-e6. Note that  23.h4  is well answered by  23...Rhe8  preparing to break with ...e4. I already prefer Black's position. }
