1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian defense, also known as the Center Counter Game, is one of Black's oldest openings, with the first recorded game dating back to 1475. Jumping forward 500+ years, Magnus Carlsen has essayed it with great success. He beat Fabiano Caruana in the 2014 Tromsø Chess Olympiad, drew him in the 2016 Baku Olympiad and defeated 5 time world champion Vishy Anand in the 2019 Kolkata Grand Chess tour. A whole host of other super-GMs such as Nakamura, Kramnik and Firouzja have this defense in their repertoire. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5
{ This is the right place for the queen. Dropping it back with ...Qd6 or ...Qd8 is far more passive and totally uncalled for. }
4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 { is the mainline. } 5... Bf5 6. Ne5
{ is one of White's most challenging variations in the entire ...Qa5 Scandinavian complex. It's connected with a whole host of ideas, ranging from g4 and Bc4 to Nc4. }
6... c6 7. g4
{ is aggressive but nothing to really worry about. White is the side that needs to be careful as this bold advance can easily backfire. }
7... Be6
{ is the correct square for the bishop. The bishop on e6 controls the c4 square  (giving Black the option of meeting Nc4 with ...Bxc4)  and, more importantly, is far less vulnerable to being chased down than if it were placed on g6.   This retreating move was not considered in the book Chess Openings for White, Explained by GMs Lev Alburt,  Roman Dzindzichashvil, and  Eugene Perelshteyn.   7...Bg6?  should be avoided due to  8.h4± }
8. Bc4
{ 8.Nc4  accomplishes very little. Simply  8...Qc7=  when White's knight on c4 is completely misplaced.   8.Bg2  is a worse square for the bishop. Following  8...Nbd7  9.Nxd7  Bxd7  10.g5  Nd5  11.O-O  Nxc3  12.bxc3  And now the novel  12...e5!  solves all of Black's issues. For example  13.Re1  Bd6  14.Bf4  O-O-O  15.Bxe5  Bxe5  16.Rxe5  Qxc3  17.Rc5  Qa3=  with a level game. }
8... Nbd7
{ is a very nice resource. Recall that Black should almost always seek to exchange off White's e5 knight at the earliest opportunity.   8...Nxg4  wins a pawn but White gets excellent compensation after  9.Bxe6  Nxe5  10.Bb3  Ng6  11.h4  with the idea h5 gives White a big initiative. Black is objectively fine after  11...e6  12.h5  Ne7  13.Bd2  Qc7  but this is something I'd rather avoid. White is the one having all the fun here. }
9. Bxe6 Nxe5
{ Chess is not checkers, and Black is under no obligation to recapture the e6 bishop. It's far better to take on e5! }
10. dxe5 { is a mistake because of } 10... Qxe5+ 11. Qe2 Qxe6 12. Qxe6 fxe6
{ Black has an extra pawn. Sure, they're doubled but White is still worse here. }
