1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian defense, also known as the Center Counter Game, is one of Black's oldest openings, with the first recorded game dating back to 1475. Jumping forward 500+ years, Magnus Carlsen has essayed it with great success. He beat Fabiano Caruana in the 2014 Tromsø Chess Olympiad, drew him in the 2016 Baku Olympiad and defeated 5 time world champion Vishy Anand in the 2019 Kolkata Grand Chess tour. A whole host of other super-GMs such as Nakamura, Kramnik and Firouzja have this defense in their repertoire. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5
{ This is the right place for the queen. Dropping it back with ...Qd6 or ...Qd8 is far more passive and totally uncalled for. }
4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 { is the mainline. } 5... Bf5 6. Ne5
{ is one of White's most challenging variations in the entire ...Qa5 Scandinavian complex. It's connected with a whole host of ideas, ranging from g4 and Bc4 to Nc4. }
6... c6 7. Bc4 e6 8. g4
{ This aggressive idea is the main point behind the Ne5 and Bc4 setup. White is going after our bishop with g4 and h4. }
8... Bg6
{ And not  8...Be4?!  when  9.O-O  Bd5  10.Bd3  Nbd7  11.f4±  is problematic. }
9. h4
{ White is not actually threatening to trap our bishop because we still have the e4 square. As such, we should continue development with }
9... Nbd7 10. Nxd7 Nxd7 11. h5 Be4 12. Rh3
{ was played in the famous attacking game 1-0 @@StartBracket@@25@@EndBracket@@ Anand,V @@StartBracket@@2765@@EndBracket@@-Lautier,J @@StartBracket@@2660  Biel 1997. Modern theory regards it as inferior to 12. O-O. }
12... Bg2 { lures the rook to a worse square } 13. Re3 Bd5
{ Mission accomplished. White's rook on e3 is misplaced, blocking in the c1 bishop.  The text is stronger than Lautier's 13...Nb6. }
14. Be2
{ 14.Bxd5  is inferior. After  14...cxd5  15.Bd2  Be7  16.Ne2  Qc7⩱  gave Black a slight edge in ½-½ Garlant, C-Glauser, P Switzerland 1998. White's kingside pawns are overextended. }
14... O-O-O 15. Bd2 Qc7 16. Nxd5 exd5
{ Black has very good play with ...Bd6-f4 and potentially ...g6 on the cards. }
