1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bf5 6. Ne5 c6 7. Bc4 e6 8. g4
Bg6 9. h4 Nbd7 10. Nxd7 Nxd7 11. h5 Be4
{ The next set of lines are devoted to } 12. O-O
{ The bishop is hanging so we have to retreat it with } 12... Bd5 13. Nxd5 cxd5
14. Bd3 Bd6
{ is the critical position in the 6. Ne5 complex.  Let's take stock. White has the bishop pair and more space on the kingside. This can create problems for Black and White admittedly has an advantage here, but several correspondence and high-level OTB games have proven it can be neutralized with precise play.   After a huge amount of analytical work, I've come up with several improvements and novel plans and will show you exactly how to neutralize White's play.  Stockfish tends to overestimate White's position at low depth while Leela's evaluations are generally more accurate. At high depth, Stockfish's evaluations go down significantly and very often tend towards Leela's, which are typically between equality and a very slight White advantage.  Finally, White's position is also not without danger. As we'll see, just one careless move and he can often find himself overextended on the kingside with his king particularly vulnerable to an attack.   In the following trainable lines, we'll consider White's five main approaches:  15.f4  ,  15.Kg2  ,  15.a4  ,  15.c3  , and  15.Bd2  .  Note: if you're a beginner or a casual player, there's no need to remember or review the following set of lines @@StartBracket@@after all, we're already on move 14!@@EndBracket@@. Playing over them once to get the general ideas is sufficient. }
*

