1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bf5 6. Ne5 c6 7. Bc4 e6 8. g4
Bg6 9. h4 Nbd7 10. Nxd7 Nxd7 11. h5 Be4 12. O-O Bd5 13. Nxd5
{ 13.Bd3  is both rare and completely harmless. After  13...O-O-O  14.Re1  g6  15.h6  Bb4=  Black is very comfortable and can look to break with ...e5. }
13... cxd5 14. Bd3 Bd6 15. f4
{ Let's start with White's most aggressive approach. } 15... O-O-O 16. a4
{ White is expanding on both sides of the board and can roll Black over if he does nothing. However }
16... f5
{ is a very nice resource, giving Black excellent counterplay on the kingside. }
17. gxf5
{ 17.g5  is strongly met by  17...h6  forcing White's pawn to move forward with  18.g6  This clears the f6 square, enabling  18...Nf6=  Black has good prospects with ...Ne4 coming next. }
17... exf5 18. Bxf5 g6
{ The machine screams equal here but White has to be very careful not to end up in massive trouble. I certainly wouldn't want to be in White's shoes with such an exposed king. }
