15. f4 { Let's start with White's most aggressive approach. } 15... O-O-O 16.
a4
{ White is expanding on both sides of the board and can roll Black over if he does nothing. However }
16... f5
{ is a very nice resource, giving Black excellent counterplay on the kingside. }
17. Bd2 { Maintaing the tension is a better option but hardly worrisome. }
17... Qb6
{ Black has an extremely straightforward plan of anchoring a knight on e4 and there's little White can do about it. The machines initially give White a slight plus here, but the longer they think, the more they gravitate towards equality.   A sample continuation is  17...Qb6  18.c3  Nf6  19.a5  Qc6  20.a6  b6  21.g5  Ne4  22.Rc1  Kb8  23.Be3  h6  24.g6  Rc8=  Black will play ...Qd7 and then double on the c-file with ...Rc7 and ...Rhc8. White has no way of making progress. }
