1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bf5 6. Ne5 c6 7. Bc4 e6 8. g4
Bg6 9. h4 Nbd7 10. Nxd7 Nxd7 11. h5 Be4 12. O-O Bd5 13. Nxd5 cxd5 14. Bd3 Bd6
15. f4 { Let's start with White's most aggressive approach. } 15... O-O-O 16.
Qe2 Nf6
{ is very thematic in this structure. Black's knight is heading to e4, which will cost us a pawn but exchange off White's best minor piece. This will leave the first player with a multitude of light square weaknesses and overextended pawns. }
17. a4
{ 17.Bd2  is well met by the simple  17...Qa4  hitting the d4 pawn.  18.c3  Kb8  19.b3  Qa3= }
17... Ne4 18. Bxe4 dxe4 19. Bd2
{ Bringing the bishop out with tempo is more precise than the immediate  19.Qxe4  which is strongly answered by  19...g6  20.h6  f5!=  with an improved version of the text. }
19... Qc7 20. Qxe4 g6
{ And this is the point. White is a pawn up but his kingside pawns are overextended and nothing but targets. Black has full compensation for the pawn deficit. }
21. h6 f5
{ White's exposed king and weak pawns give Black excellent play and full compensation for the material deficit. The following sample continuations are a good illustration.   22.Qxe6  picks up a pawn with check but after  22...Kb8  both the c2 and g4 pawns are hanging. After  23.Qb3  fxg4  24.Rae1  Rhf8=  Black is in the driver's seat. White is the one that needs to be careful not to end up in trouble.   Alternatively  22.Qe2  fxg4  23.Qxe6  Kb8  24.c3  g3  25.Rae1  Qa5=  hits the a4 pawn and threatens to swing the queen over to h5. Black is in great shape.   Finally  22.Qg2  Qc4  targets the d4 pawn, yet another weakness in White's camp.  23.c3  fxg4  24.Rae1  Rhf8  25.Qxg4  Rf6  26.Re4  Rf5=  is dynamically balanced. The e6 pawn will likely be exchanged for the a4 pawn. }
