Bg6 9. h4 Nbd7 10. Nxd7 Nxd7 11. h5 Be4 12. O-O Bd5 13. Nxd5 cxd5 14. Bd3 Bd6
15. Kg2
{ This useful waiting move was recommended in the 2nd edition of the book A Startling Chess Repertoire for White by IM Chris Baker and FM Graham Burgess. Their intention was to meet }
15... g6 { with } 16. Rh1 O-O-O
{ was not considered in the aforementioned book. Black scoots his king over to the queenside and will try to prove White's king is the one in danger. }
17. Bg5 Rde8
{ gives Black good play with ideas of ...gxh5 followed by ...Rhg8 as well as breaking in the center with ...e5. While Stockfish initially gives White a slight advantage, its evaluation quickly goes down towards equality.   Black has good practical chances as the following sample continuation illustrates:  18.a4  gxh5  19.Rxh5  Rhg8  20.Kf1  h6  21.Bxh6  Nf6  The knight is headed to e4 with excellent counterplay. }
