15. a4
{ is very logical, expanding on the queenside and dissuading Black from castling on this side of the board. }
15... O-O 16. f4
{ has never been played but should be mentioned.   Also novel is  16.g5  when  16...e5  17.Qg4  Qc7  18.Bf5  Rad8  gives Black good chances. Best play by both sides follows  19.c3  g6  20.hxg6  fxg6  21.Be6  Kh8  22.Bxd5  exd4  23.Qxd4  Be5  24.Qc4  Qxc4  25.Bxc4  Bf4  26.Rd1  Bxc1  27.Raxc1  Ne5  28.Rxd8  Rxd8  White's bishop is hanging and with ...Rd2 coming, Black is fine. }
16... Nf6 { The knight is headed to e4. } 17. Qf3 Rae8 18. g5 Ne4
{ sacrifices a pawn to get White's light-squared bishops off the board. } 19.
Bxe4 dxe4 20. Qxe4 Qd5 21. Qxd5 exd5
{ Black is currently a pawn down but has full compensation since White is underdeveloped and his pawns are overextended. Black's rook is heading to e2/e4 and White's kingside is about to be undermined with ...f6. }
