{ 21...Qb6  is another option that led to a draw in the correspondence game ½-½ @@StartBracket@@42@@EndBracket@@ Burgos Garbin, F @@StartBracket@@2335@@EndBracket@@-Lundberg,C @@StartBracket@@2297@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2017. I prefer the text. }
22. Bxe4 dxe4 23. Qxe4 f5
{ I certainly wouldn't want to be White here. His king is very exposed.   A sample continuation is  24.gxf5  Rxf5  25.Qxf5  White is well advised to take this chance to simplify the game. Otherwise, Black will invite everyone to the party as Yasser Seirawan likes to say with ...Qf7 and ...Rf8, swiftly hunting down White's king.  25...exf5  26.Rxe8  Kh7  27.Rae1  Qa5  28.R8e6  Qd5  29.f3  f4=  with good play. Despite the material disadvantage, Black is the one pressing here due to White's weak king. The first player has to be very careful to not lose both the h5 and f3 pawns. }
