[White "10. 3.Nc3 | 5.Nf3 6.Ne5"]
[Black "15. a4 [16...a6 Alternative #4]"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bf5 6. Ne5 c6 7. Bc4 e6 8. g4
Bg6 9. h4 Nbd7 10. Nxd7 Nxd7 11. h5 Be4 12. O-O Bd5 13. Nxd5 cxd5 14. Bd3 Bd6
15. a4
{ is very logical, expanding on the queenside and dissuading Black from castling on this side of the board. }
15... O-O 16. Qf3 a6
{ is an interesting continuation. The idea is to be able to meet  17.h6  with  17...g6  without having to worry about Bb5 followed by Qf6.   Note that  16...f5  is mymain recommendation. }
17. c3 Rae8 { Black is getting ready to liberate his position with ...e5. } 18.
Kg2 Qc7 19. Re1 h6
{ Puts a stop to White's active plan of expanding on the kingside with ...g5. }
20. Bd2 Nf6
{ The knight is headed to e4 and there's little White can do about it. } 21.
Bxh6
{ Flashy but I'm not bothered.   Alternatively  21.g5  hxg5  22.Bxg5  Nh7  23.Be3  f5  followed by ...Nf6-g4/e4 gives Black good prospects. }
21... Ne4 { White's bishop is now hanging. } 22. Bc1
{ is the best square to retreat to. Having to go all the way back home is a big indication White has no real advantage. Indeed, following   22.Be3  f5⭡  gives Black a big initiative down the f-file. }
22... f5 23. g5 Qe7
{ The g5 pawn is hanging and if it moves forward then ...e5 will come. White has overextended himself. }
