1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bf5 6. Ne5 c6 7. Bc4 e6 8. g4
Bg6 9. h4 Nbd7 10. Nxd7 Nxd7 11. h5 Be4 12. O-O Bd5 13. Nxd5 cxd5 14. Bd3 Bd6
15. Bd2 { Sielecki missed Black's best move } 15... Qb6
{ This is the best square for the queen, where it keeps an eye on the b2 and d4 pawns. While the former is taboo since Rb1xb7 would then follow, the latter is certainly hanging. }
16. c3 Bc7
{ with the idea ...Qd6 to go after White's exposed king. All those pawn moves on the kingside are coming back to bite White.   This clever ...Qb6 + ...Bc7 regrouping solves all of Black's problems! Sethuraman missed it in the Chessable course Lifetime Repertoires: Sethuraman's 1.e4 Part 1. }
17. f4
{ White clamps down on the e5 square and nullifies the threat of ...Qd6.   17.a4  O-O  18.f4  doesn't change much.  18...Nf6  19.Qe2  Ne4  20.Bxe4  dxe4  21.Qxe4  Qxb2  leads to similar play as the text. }
17... Nf6
{ is a key novelty. The knight is headed to e4 and there's little White can do to stop it.   This is even stronger than  17...g6  played in the correspondence game ½-½ @@StartBracket@@57@@EndBracket@@ Fuzishawa, R @@StartBracket@@2400@@EndBracket@@-Salvador Marques, C @@StartBracket@@2400@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2018. }
18. Qe2
{ 18.Qa4  is well met by  18...Ke7  Yes, our king is in the center but White has no way of targeting it. For example  19.f5  e5!  20.Rae1  e4=  keeps the e-file closed. Black is ok. }
18... Ne4 { And we jump in anyhow. The point is that after } 19. Bxe4 dxe4 20.
Qxe4 Qxb2
{ Black collects the b2 pawn with a critical tempo on the d2 bishop such that White has no time for Rb1. }
21. Rfd1 O-O
{ Black has a sound position and can look to target the backward c3 pawn with ...Rac8 and ...Ba5.   The king on g8 is safe. White doesn't have enough minors nor are his existing pieces well placed to mount any semblance of a kingside attack. }
