1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian defense, also known as the Center Counter Game, is one of Black's oldest openings, with the first recorded game dating back to 1475. Jumping forward 500+ years, Magnus Carlsen has essayed it with great success. He beat Fabiano Caruana in 2014 Tromsø Chess Olympiad, drew him in the 2016 Baku Olympiad and defeated 5 time world champion Vishy Anand in the 2019 Kolkata Grand Chess tour. A whole host of other super-GMs such as Nakamura, Kramnik and Firouzja have this defense in their repertoire. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5
{ This is the right place for the queen. Dropping it back with ...Qd6 or ...Qd8 is far more passive and totally uncalled for. }
4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 { is the mainline. } 5... Bf5 6. Bc4 e6 7. O-O
{ is a natural developing move but it fails to put any pressure on Black's position. }
7... Nbd7 8. Bd2 c6 { Black should not fear the knight discovery with } 9. Nd5
Qd8 { The queen has come back home and White's knight must now move again. }
10. Ne3
{ 10.Nxf6+  Nxf6=  followed by ...Bd6 and ...O-O fully equalized with Black going on to win in 0-1 @@StartBracket@@46@@EndBracket@@ Garic,R @@StartBracket@@2246@@EndBracket@@-Savic,M @@StartBracket@@2537@@EndBracket@@ Obrenovac 2013. }
10... Bg6
{ Next up are ...Bd6 and ...O-O with a comfortable game. White's knight on e3 is poorly placed, blocking the dark-squared bishop and obstructing the e-file. }
