[White "11. 3.Nc3 | 5.Nf3 6.Bc4"]
[Black "7. Bd2 8. Ne5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian defense, also known as the Center Counter Game, is one of Black's oldest openings, with the first recorded game dating back to 1475. Jumping forward 500+ years, Magnus Carlsen has essayed it with great success. He beat Fabiano Caruana in 2014 Tromsø Chess Olympiad, drew him in the 2016 Baku Olympiad and defeated 5 time world champion Vishy Anand in the 2019 Kolkata Grand Chess tour. A whole host of other super-GMs such as Nakamura, Kramnik and Firouzja have this defense in their repertoire. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5
{ This is the right place for the queen. Dropping it back with ...Qd6 or ...Qd8 is far more passive and totally uncalled for. }
4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 { is the mainline. } 5... Bf5 6. Bc4 e6 7. Bd2
{ is White's only challenging option. The first player breaks the pin and threatens a deadly discovery with Nd5. }
7... Bb4
{ is known as the Laznicka variation, named after the Czech grandmaster Victor Laznicka who played it consistently against the world's best players for a number of years. Other notable Scandinavian experts that have employed this variation are four-time Greek Champion GM Ioannis Papaioannou and French GM Eric Prie.  At first sight, this move may look anti-positional as we'll be forced to part with our bishop pair after a3. However, after the exchange on c3, White's dark-squared bishop will find itself misplaced and ineffective on c3.   7...c6  is inferior to the text due to  8.Nd5  Qd8  9.Nxf6   9...gxf6  is Black's most common choice. I was unable to find a way for Black to equalize in this line, with the compromised pawn structure being a big handicap.  9...Qxf6  While this might not look dramatic, Black's queen is actually very misplaced on f6 and would much rather be on a5.  10.Qe2  Bg4  11.d5!±  gives White a big advantage.  By forgoing ...c6, Black retains the option of developing the b8 knight to this square to target the d4 pawn. The pressure on this pawn can be further increased by bringing a rook to d8 and undermining White's knight on f3 with ...Bg4 or ...Be4. }
8. Ne5 { As usual, early knight jumps can be neutralized with } 8... Nbd7 9.
Nxd7 Nxd7 10. a3 Bxc3 11. Bxc3 Qb6
{ Black is now threatening a double-attack with ...Qc6 and if } 12. d5
{ 12.O-O  is well met by  12...Nf6  when  13.d5  is nothing to worry about. Simply  13...Nxd5  14.Bxd5  O-O-O= }
12... O-O-O
{ is excellent for Black. Coming up is ...Nf6 with good play down the d-file.   Note that  13.Bd4?!  is strongly met by  13...c5!  14.dxc6  Qxc6∓  White is in big trouble. The g2 pawn is hanging and White placed himself under a terrible pin along the d-file, which Black is ready to exploit with ...Nb6. }
