1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bf5 6. Bc4 e6 7. Bd2 Bb4 8.
a3 Bxc3 9. Bxc3 Qb6 10. d5
{ was Wesley So's recommendation in his Lifetime Repertoire. This is a line where White is playing for two results but with precise play, Black can make a draw fairly easily. }
10... exd5 { 10...Nbd7  is mymain recommendation. } 11. Bxd5
{ I'm going to start by explaining why I've decided not to recommend } 11...
O-O
{ This is natural but the resulting endgame that arises pretty much by force is not as dead drawn as I'd like.   11...Be6  is a good alternative to my main recommendation with 10...Nbd7. It is analyzed set of alternative lines startinghere. }
12. Bxf6 Re8+ 13. Be5 Nd7 14. Bxf7+
{ is a strong resource.   14.O-O  is obviously harmless  14...Nxe5  15.Nxe5  Rxe5= }
14... Kxf7 15. Qd5+ Be6 16. Qd4
{ is White's best move.   16.Ng5+  fails to give White anything after  16...Kf8  17.Nxe6+  Rxe6  18.Qxd7  Rxe5+  19.Kf1  Qxb2= }
16... Qxd4 17. Bxd4 Bd5+ 18. Be3 Bxf3 19. gxf3 Ne5 20. Ke2 b6 21. Rad1 Rad8
{ I'm fairly confident Black should be able to draw this with accurate play, but 10...Nbd7 or 10...exd5 11...Be6 lead to even easier endgames to hold. }
