1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian defense, also known as the Center Counter Game, is one of Black's oldest openings, with the first recorded game dating back to 1475. Jumping forward 500+ years, Magnus Carlsen has essayed it with great success. He beat Fabiano Caruana in 2014 Tromsø Chess Olympiad, drew him in the 2016 Baku Olympiad and defeated 5 time world champion Vishy Anand in the 2019 Kolkata Grand Chess tour. A whole host of other super-GMs such as Nakamura, Kramnik and Firouzja have this defense in their repertoire. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bf5 6. Bc4 e6 7. Bd2 Bb4 8. a3 Bxc3 9.
Bxc3 Qb6 10. d5
{ was Wesley So's recommendation in his Lifetime Repertoire. This is a line where White is playing for two results but, with precise play, Black can make a draw fairly easily. }
10... Nbd7
{ is my preferred move.   10...exd5  11.Bxd5  Be6  is another good option, which is covered in a set of alternative lines startinghere. }
11. Nd4
{ Going after our bishop on f5 is more challenging than 11. dxe6.   11.Bd4  can be blocked with  11...c5  12.dxc6  Qxc6=  with a perfectly fine position. }
11... O-O-O
{ Not only brings the king to safety, but puts immediate pressure on White's center. }
12. Nxf5
{ 12.dxe6?  runs into  12...Ne5∓  Note that  13.e7  doesn't help as  13...Rd6!  14.Bb3?!  Bg4  15.Qd2  Nc6−+  will pick up White's knight on d4.   Alternatively  12.O-O  allows  12...Be4=+ }
12... exf5 13. O-O Rhe8
{ gives Black a good game. White's bishop pair, particularly the bishop on c4, are awkwardly placed, preventing White from pushing his queenside pawns. Our knights will find good squares in the center of the board.   For example  14.Ba2  gives us enough time to centralize his knight with  14...Ne5  and with ...Ne4 and possibly ...g7-g5 to follow, Black in great shape.   Note that  14.d6  is well met by  14...Ne5  covering the f7 pawn and hitting White's bishop. After  15.Bd3  g6  16.Bxe5  Rxe5  17.dxc7  Qxc7=  Black is doing very well. We're fully centralized and can double on the d-file with ...Red5 followed by ...Nd7-e5 to exploit the pin or, alternatively, go after White's queenside pawns with ...Rb5 next. }
