[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian defense, also known as the Center Counter Game, is one of Black's oldest openings, with the first recorded game dating back to 1475. Jumping forward 500+ years, Magnus Carlsen has essayed it with great success. He beat Fabiano Caruana in 2014 Tromsø Chess Olympiad, drew him in the 2016 Baku Olympiad and defeated 5 time world champion Vishy Anand in the 2019 Kolkata Grand Chess tour. A whole host of other super-GMs such as Nakamura, Kramnik and Firouzja have this defense in their repertoire. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5
{ This is the right place for the queen. Dropping it back with ...Qd6 or ...Qd8 is far more passive and totally uncalled for. }
4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 { is the mainline. } 5... Bf5 6. Bc4 e6 7. Bd2
{ is White's only challenging option. The first player breaks the pin and threatens a deadly discovery with Nd5. }
7... Bb4
{ is known as the Laznicka variation, named after the Czech grandmaster Victor Laznicka who played it consistently against the world's best players. Other notable Scandinavian experts that have employed this variation are four-time Greek Champion GM Ioannis Papaioannou and French GM Eric Prie.  At first sight, this move may look anti-positional as we'll be forced to part with our bishop pair after a3  (and, if you have gone through my past courses, you know how dear the bishop pair is to me!)  . However, after the exchange on c3, White's dark-squared bishop will find itself misplaced and ineffective on c3.   7...c6  is inferior to the text due to  8.Nd5  Qd8  9.Nxf6   9...gxf6  is Black's most common choice. I was unable to find a way for Black to equalize in this line, with the compromised pawn structure being a big handicap.  9...Qxf6  While this might not look dramatic, Black's queen is actually very misplaced on f6 and would much rather be on a5.  10.Qe2  Bg4  11.d5!±  gives White a big advantage.  By foregoing ...c6, Black can retains the option of developing the b8 knight to this square to target the d4 pawn. The pressure on this pawn can be further increased by bringing a rook to d8 and undermining White's knight on f3 with ...Bg4 or ...Be4. }
8. a3
{ is considered a critical variation in the ...Qa5 Scandinavian. White picks up the bishop pair, but I'm about to prove he is fine. }
8... Bxc3 9. Bxc3 Qb6 10. d5
{ was Wesley So's recommendation in his Lifetime Repertoire. This is a line where White is playing for two results but, with precise play, Black can make a draw fairly easily. }
10... Nbd7
{ is my preferred move.   10...exd5  11.Bxd5  Be6  is another good option, which is covered in a set of alternative lines startinghere. }
11. O-O O-O { Black follows suit and gets his king to safety. } 12. dxe6
{ 12.Bd4  is once again easily blocked with  12...c5 } 12... Bxe6 13. Bxe6 Qxe6
{ White's bishop pair has been neutralized. While White's remaining bishop gives the first player something to play with, Black has no weaknesses and thus little to worry about. }
14. Re1 Qf5 15. Nh4
{ 15.Nd4  is innocuous. After  15...Qd5  16.Qf3  Qxf3  17.Nxf3  Rfe8=  the game soon ended in a drawn in ½-½  (21)  Magem Badals,J  (2545)  -Cornette,M  (2545)  Catalunya 2012. }
15... Qd5
{ Prepares to get the queens off the board, edging ever closer to a draw. White's dark-squared bishop is unable to pose Black any problems because the pawn structure is symmetric. }
16. Qxd5 Nxd5 17. Rad1 { White brings the rook into the game with tempo. }
17... N7b6 { is easy enough, reinforcing the powerful d5 knight. } 18. Ba5
{ 18.Bd4  changes very little. After  18...Rfe8  19.Rxe8+  Rxe8  20.Nf5  f6=  Black has no problems with ...Kf7 and ...g6 coming next. }
18... Rfe8
{ It's now time to exchange a pair of rooks. The more pieces get off the board, the closer Black gets to a draw. }
19. Rxe8+
{ 19.b3  is no improvement. The only game to reach this position continued  19.b3  Ne7  20.Kf1  Nc6  21.Bxb6  axb6  22.Rxe8  Rxe8  23.Nf5  Rd8  24.Rxd8  and a draw was agreed in ½-½  (24)  Packroff,H  (2229)  -Wedel,L  (2110)  ICCF email 2014. }
19... Rxe8 20. b3 f6
{ Black creates a square for his king on f7 while placing another pawn on dark squares, which limits the scope of White's bishop. }
21. Nf5
{ This was all recommended in the Chessable course Lifetime Repertoires: Wesley So's 1.e4. Wesley prematurely ended his analysis here, claiming White was slightly better. However, he failed to consider the precise }
21... Re5
{ after which White has next to nothing. White's pieces on the 5th rank will have to retreat.   The following sample continuations are a good illustration:  22.g4  h5  23.Bxb6  Nxb6  24.h3  Kf7  25.Ne3  hxg4  26.hxg4  Re7=  is dead even.   22.Ng3  Nf4  23.Rd8+  Kf7  24.Bd2  Ne6  25.Rb8  Rd5  26.Nf1  Nd8=  Next up is ...Rd7 without a worry in the world. White's rook can then be expelled with ...c5 and ...Nc6.   22.Bxb6  axb6  23.c4  Nc3  24.Rd8+  Kf7  25.Ne3  Re8=  Kicks back White's rook with full equality. }
