{ is White's only challenging option. The first player breaks the pin and threatens a deadly discovery with Nd5. }
7... Bb4
{ is known as the Laznicka variation, named after the Czech grandmaster Victor Laznicka who played it consistently against the world's best players. Other notable Scandinavian experts that have employed this variation are four-time Greek Champion GM Ioannis Papaioannou and French GM Eric Prie.  At first sight, this move may look anti-positional as we'll be forced to part with our bishop pair after a3  (and, if you have gone through my past courses, you know how dear the bishop pair is to me!)  . However, after the exchange on c3, White's dark-squared bishop will find itself misplaced and ineffective on c3.   7...c6  is inferior to the text due to  8.Nd5  Qd8  9.Nxf6   9...gxf6  is Black's most common choice. I was unable to find a way for Black to equalize in this line, with the compromised pawn structure being a big handicap.  9...Qxf6  While this might not look dramatic, Black's queen is actually very misplaced on f6 and would much rather be on a5.  10.Qe2  Bg4  11.d5!±  gives White a big advantage.  By foregoing ...c6, Black can retains the option of developing the b8 knight to this square to target the d4 pawn. The pressure on this pawn can be further increased by bringing a rook to d8 and undermining White's knight on f3 with ...Bg4 or ...Be4. }
8. a3
{ is considered a critical variation in the ...Qa5 Scandinavian. White picks up the bishop pair, but I'm about to prove he is fine. }
8... Bxc3 9. Bxc3 Qb6 10. d5
{ was Wesley So's recommendation in his Lifetime Repertoire. This is a line where White is playing for two results but with precise play, Black can make a draw fairly easily. }
10... exd5 11. Bxd5 Be6
{ It's important to get the light-squared bishops off the board here. This move was not considered in the book Kaufman's Repertoire for White and Black by GM Larry Kaufman. }
