11. b4
{ Gaining space on the queenside makes a lot of sense. It is connected with the ambitious plan of dropping both the bishops back and pushing c2-c4, when White would then be threatening to run Black over on the queenside.   It's not without its drawbacks as White's b4 pawn can be undermined with ...a5 in the future. }
11... O-O 12. Bb2 a5
{ improves over the game ½-½ @@StartBracket@@60@@EndBracket@@ Huschenbeth, N @@StartBracket@@2609@@EndBracket@@ -Bartholomew, J @@StartBracket@@2446@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com INT 2020, where Black played  12...Rad8  The text is much more incisive.  By putting immediate pressure on White's queenside, we don't give the first player any time to execute his plan of dropping back the light-squared bishop and expanding with c2-c4. }
13. c3 axb4 14. axb4 Ne7
{ Black is ready to play ...c6 and transfer the knight to d5. White cannot be at all better with such a passive bishop on b2. }
