1. e4 d5
{ The Scandinavian defense, also known as the Center Counter Game, is one of Black's oldest openings, with the first recorded game dating back to 1475. Jumping forward 500+ years, Magnus Carlsen has essayed it with great success. He beat Fabiano Caruana in 2014 Tromsø Chess Olympiad, drew him in the 2016 Baku Olympiad and defeated 5 time world champion Vishy Anand in the 2019 Kolkata Grand Chess tour. A whole host of other super-GMs such as Nakamura, Kramnik and Firouzja have this defense in their repertoire. }
2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5
{ This is the right place for the queen. Dropping it back with ...Qd6 or ...Qd8 is far more passive and totally uncalled for. }
4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 { is the mainline. } 5... Bf5 6. Bc4 e6 7. Bd2
{ is White's only challenging option. The first player breaks the pin and threatens a deadly discovery with Nd5. }
7... Bb4
{ is known as the Laznicka variation, named after the Czech grandmaster Victor Laznicka who played it consistently against the world's best players. Other notable Scandinavian experts that have employed this variation are four-time Greek Champion GM Ioannis Papaioannou and French GM Eric Prie.  At first sight, this move may look anti-positional as we'll be forced to part with our bishop pair after a3. However, after the exchange on c3, White's dark-squared bishop will find itself misplaced and ineffective on c3.   7...c6  is inferior to the text due to  8.Nd5  Qd8  9.Nxf6   9...gxf6  is Black's most common choice. I was unable to find a way for Black to equalize in this line, with the compromised pawn structure being a big handicap.  9...Qxf6  While this might not look dramatic, Black's queen is actually very misplaced on f6 and would much rather be on a5.  10.Qe2  Bg4  11.d5!±  gives White a big advantage.  By forgoing ...c6, Black retains the option of developing the b8 knight to this square to target the d4 pawn. The pressure on this pawn can be further increased by bringing a rook to d8 and undermining White's knight on f3 with ...Bg4 or ...Be4. }
8. a3
{ is considered a critical variation in the ...Qa5 Scandinavian. White picks up the bishop pair, but I'm about to prove he is fine. }
8... Bxc3 9. Bxc3 Qb6 10. O-O { is White's most common move. } 10... Nc6
{ White has tried many moves at this juncture but only  11.b4  and  11.a4  are really worth reviewing.  We are going to go over all of White's main tries for completeness's sake and, while it's good to see them once as I will be pointing out several important middlegame themes, feel free to pause most of them afterward. }
11. b4
{ Gaining space on the queenside makes a lot of sense. It is connected with the ambitious plan of dropping both the bishops back and pushing c2-c4, when White would then be threatening to run Black over on the queenside.   It's not without its drawbacks as White's b4 pawn can be undermined with ...a5 in the future. }
11... O-O 12. b5 { is more incisive than Huschenbeth's  12.Bb2 } 12... Nb8
{ White is welcome to do his worse and push his queenside pawns with } 13. a4
c6 { Creates a safe square for the queen on c7. } 14. a5 Qc7 15. b6
{ White got in all the moves he wanted and accomplished absolutely nothing! Black's position is rock solid and if anything White's advanced pawns left several weak squares behind. }
15... Qd8 16. bxa7 Rxa7
{ Black will develop the knight to d7, the queen will go to c7 and he can then look to gang up on the a5 pawn with ...Rfa8. Black is rock solid and has no worries whatsoever. }
