8... Bxc3 9. Bxc3 Qb6 10. O-O { is White's most common move. } 10... Nc6
{ White has tried many moves at this juncture but only  11.b4  and  11.a4  are really worth reviewing.  We are going to go over all of White's main tries for completeness's sake and, while it's good to see them once as I will be pointing out several important middlegame themes, feel free to pause most of them afterward. }
11. a4
{ is White's most common move. The threat is obvious: White wants to trap our queen with a5. }
11... a5 12. Bb5
{ is much more popular than the alternatives.   12.Qe2  is harmless.  12...O-O  13.b3  Nb4=  targeting the c2 pawn is very comfortable. }
12... O-O
{ Black has completed development and is ready to target the weak c2 pawn with ...Nb4 next. }
13. Nd2
{ The point behind Bb5 is now clear. White's knight is heading to e3 via c4.   13.Qe2  is completely harmless.  13...Nb4  14.Rfc1  c6  15.Bc4  Rad8=  was more than acceptable in the game 1-0 Petkov, M @@StartBracket@@2358@@EndBracket@@-Tristan, L @@StartBracket@@2535@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020 }
13... Nb4 14. Nc4 Qa7
{ White achieved very little as the queen is perfectly fine on a7, where it still eyes the d4 pawn. The pressure on the c2 pawn even forces White to go back with }
15. Ne3
{ White's knight is well placed here, protecting the c2 pawn and supporting the d4-d5 break. Unfortunately for White, he's never going to get it in. }
15... Bg6
