{ This chapter contains over a dozen annotated model games, hand-picked based on their instructional value and theoretical relevance. Their aesthetic qualities also played a role.  In this chapter, you can   (1)  see typical tactical resources as well as thematic middlegame and endgame plans in action.   (2)  learn from 3...Qa5 Scandinavian heroes GMs Viktor Laznicka, Eric Prie, and Matthias Wahls.   (3)  have fun playing through 3 fantastic miniatures where strong GMs were crushed with the Scandinavian defense in 20 moves or less! }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model games"]
[Black "0-1 Mamonovas,V (2483)-Marti Pericot,J (2465) ICCF 2009"]
[Result "*"]

{ The following is a correspondence game where White, rated 2483, essayed the dubious Blackmar-Diemer Gambit.   The game started out with }
1. d4 { but soon transposed to lines we covered. } 1... d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. e4
dxe4 4. f3
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d5  2.d4  dxe4  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.f3  is the way to reach this position via the Scandinavian move order. }
4... exf3 { Accepting the gambit is the way to refute it! } 5. Nxf3 c6
{ Black's plan is to develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain and then set up an impregnable Capablanca structure with pawns on ...e6 and ...c6. }
6. Bc4 Bf5 7. O-O e6 8. Ne5
{ White is threatening a cheapo with Rxf5, which Black easily avoided with }
8... Bg6 9. Bg5 Be7
{ This was all covered in the theory section, namely in the8.Ne5 #1 variation in chapter 2. As remarked there, Black is rock-solid and all his pieces are coming to good squares. White's compensation for the pawn deficit is non-existent. }
10. Nxg6 hxg6 11. Qd3 Nbd7 12. Rae1 Qc7
{ Targets the h2 pawn and clears the way for queenside castling. Black's rook is perfectly well placed on h8 so it makes little sense to castle short. }
13. h3 O-O-O
{ The rook is well placed on d8, directly opposite White's queen. } 14. a4
{ White has nothing to show for the pawn deficit. His only chance is to try and stir up an attack on the queenside. }
14... a6
{ is solid but wasn't strictly necessary. Other moves like ...Rh5 or ... Kb8 were also good enough. }
15. Qe3 Nb6 16. Bb3 c5
{ is the usual Scandinavian break, which works wonders in this position. Black prepares to exchange off White's only central pawn leaving the second player with a central majority. }
17. a5 Nbd7 18. Bf4 Qxa5
{ There goes a second pawn. White was banking on drumming something up with }
19. d5 e5
{ is a nice solution. Black gives back one of the pawns and completely denies White any counterplay. One extra pawn is more than sufficient to win the game. }
20. Bxe5 Nxe5 21. Qxe5 Bd6 22. Qe2 Rhe8
{ The rook wasn't doing anything on h8 and joins the action with tempo. } 23.
Qd3 Rxe1 24. Rxe1 b5
{ is very strong. Black is threatening both ...c4 and ... b4, winning material. }
25. Kf1 c4 26. Bxc4 bxc4
{ Black won a piece prompting White to resign.  This one-sided game is a good illustration of the solidity of Black's setup with ...c6 and ...e6 and how easy it is to neutralize White's aggressive intentions in the Blackmar-Diemer Gambit, after which the extra pawn makes its presence felt.  0-1 Mamonovas,V  (2483)  -Marti Pericot,J  (2465)  ICCF 2009 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model games"]
[Black "0-1 Braun,G (2385)-Wahls,M (2570) Germany 1992"]
[Result "*"]

{ The following is a model game between German GMs Gottfried Braun and Matthias Wahls from the 1992 German Cup. GM Walhs is a Scandinavian expert, having defeated many titled players with our beloved defense. This game features the 3. Nf3 variation and showcases how Black should go about attacking White's king in opposite castled king scenarios. }
1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nf3 Bg4 4. Be2 Nc6 5. O-O O-O-O 6. d3
{ is subpar and lets Black expand in the center with 6...e5.   6.h3  is the only testing move, which was examined in thetheory section. }
6... e5 7. Nc3 Qd7 8. Re1
{ 8.h3  should be met with  8...Be6   Watch out  8...Bh5  blunders a pawn to  9.Nxe5!  Bxe2  10.Qxe2  Nxe5  11.Qxe5±  9.a3  Nge7  followed by ...f6, ...h5 and ...g5-g4, starting a vicious pawn assault on White's king. The hook on h3 ensures we'll be able to blast open some files on the kingside. }
8... f6 9. Be3
{ This seemingly natural developing move is too slow. With kings castled on opposite sides of the board, White should have wasted no time in starting play on the queenside.  Better was   9.h3  Be6  10.Ne4  g5  11.c3  when both sides will throw their pawns at the opposing king. Black is ready for h5 and g4 while White will push ahead with b2-b4. }
9... Nge7 { The immediate  9...h5  followed by ...g5 was even stronger. } 10.
Nd2
{ White is playing without a plan, simply shuffling his piece around. The first player should have started active operations on the queenside asap and will now come under a vicious attack on the kingside. }
10... h5 11. Nb3
{ White's knight is headed to the c5 square.   11.h3  Bxe2  12.Qxe2  Nf5  Black is ready to jump into the stronghold on d4 and blast open the kingside with ...g5-g4. White has no counterplay on the queenside and is in big trouble. }
11... Kb8
{ is a very cool response. Black vacates the c8 square for the queen in the case of Nc5. }
12. Bf3
{ is a terrible position for the bishop. It might look more active on f3 than on e2 but this is not the case as it's now a target to ideas like ...Nf5 followed by ...Nd4. }
12... Qf5 { 12...g5  was another good option. } 13. Nd2
{ White's knight is forced back to defend the f3 bishop. Spending two tempi with Nd2-b3 back to d2 is something White cannot afford in opposite castled positions. It's only move 13 and White's already close to lost. }
13... Qg6
{ is a logical move, vacating the f5 square for the e7 knight.   13...g5!  was even stronger. The idea is to capture on f3 and follow up with g4. }
14. Kf1 { Black immediately moved in with } 14... Nf5 15. h3 Nxe3+
{ is simple and effective. Black doesn't need to do anything fancy to close the game out. By taking on e3, Black clears the way for his f-pawn to move forward.   The flashy  15...Ncd4!  was an excellent alternative. }
16. fxe3 Bd7
{ Simple chess once again, which is more than good enough.   There was no need to retreat and Black could have instead pushed ahead with  16...f5  17.hxg4  hxg4  18.Bd5  Bc5-+  is dead winning. White's king is simply far too exposed. }
17. Nb3
{ The knight is once again back on b3. It's obvious White has been playing without a plan basically since the beginning of the game. }
17... f5 18. Nd5 Qf7
{ Black once again opts for a simple and logical move. The queen steps out of the g-file, clearing the way for ...g5-g4.   18...e4!  would have decided the game pretty much immediately.  19.Nf4  Qh7-+  followed by ...g5 is lights out. }
19. c4 g5 20. Qd2 g4 21. Bd1 Ne7
{ Eliminates White's only active piece.   21...gxh3  ripping open the kingside was also decisive. It's hard to play a move that doesn't win with Black at this point. }
22. Nxe7 Bxe7 23. Qf2 Rdg8
{ The d8 rooks joins the action. Black didn't forget to invite everyone to the party! }
24. Ke2
{ Desperation. White tries to run away but he won't be going very far.   24.h4  fails to close down the kingside. After  24...g3  25.Qc2  e4  The h4 pawn is about to drop. White is busted. }
24... f4 25. Rh1 gxh3 26. gxh3 Rg3
{ The rook invades with decisive effect. The end is in sight. } 27. exf4 exf4
28. Kd2 Qg7
{ Powerless against the devastating threats of ...Qxb2+ and ...Rg2, White resigned.   0-1 @@StartBracket@@28@@EndBracket@@ Braun,G @@StartBracket@@2385@@EndBracket@@-Wahls,M @@StartBracket@@2570@@EndBracket@@ Germany 1992 }
