{ The following is a model game in the 3. Nf3 variation between Dutch GM Eric Van den Doel and IM Jasper Broekmeulen. }
1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nf3 Bg4 4. Be2 Nc6 5. h3 Bxf3 6. Bxf3 Qe5+ 7. Qe2
Qxe2+ 8. Bxe2 O-O-O 9. d3 e5 10. O-O g6
{ This was all covered in the theoretical section of the course, specifically the5. h3 #3 variation in chapter 4. My assessment was that Black had good chances in this endgame. }
11. Re1 Bh6
{ Black starts by exchanging the dark-squared bishops, neutralizing White's bishop pair advantage. }
12. Bxh6 { Only helps Black develop.   12.Nd2  was a better move. } 12... Nxh6
13. Na3 f6 14. c3
{ White takes control over the d4 square at the cost of weakening the d3 pawn. }
14... Rd7
{ Black prepares to double rooks on the d-file, aiming at this weak pawn. } 15.
Nc2 { 15.Nc4  was a much better square for the knight. } 15... Nf5 16. Rad1
Rhd8 17. Rf1 Nce7 { Black's knight is headed to f4. } 18. Kh2 Nd5 19. g3
{ White cannot allow Black's knight to land on f4. This comes at the cost of weakening his kingside. }
19... c5 { prevents White from liberating his position with d3-d4. } 20. Rb1
Nb6 21. Ne3 Ng7 { Black has more space and thus correctly avoids exchanges. }
22. Ng4 Rd6 23. Nh6 Re8 24. b4
{ White was tired of waiting around and decided to break on the queenside. While it looks active, it leaves behind a weak pawn on c3.   24.Kg2  was much better when White is still very much in the game. }
24... Ne6 25. Ng4 Rf8 26. f4
{ Another active looking move that further deteriorates White's position. After exchanging on f4, this pawn will be a target.   26.Kg2  was once again a better option. }
26... exf4 27. gxf4 cxb4 28. Rxb4 Nd5 29. Rc4+ Kd8 30. Rb1 Ndxf4
{ wins a pawn with a tempo on the bishop, meaning White has no time for Rxb7. }
31. Bf1 Rf7
{ Black was a clean pawn up and with a 3 vs 1 on the kingside, he didn't have any trouble converting his advantage. }
32. d4 Nd5 33. Bg2 h5 34. Nf2 Ne3 35. Ra4 Nxg2 36. Kxg2 b6 37. Ne4 Rd5 38. Kf2
f5 39. Nd2 Rc7 40. Ra3 g5 41. Nf3 g4 42. Ne5 Ke7 43. hxg4 hxg4 44. Rh1 Kd6 45.
Nd3 Ra5 46. Rb3 Rxa2+ 47. Ke3 g3 48. Nb2 f4+ 49. Kf3 Ng5+ 50. Kxf4 g2 51. Rh6+
Ke7
{ There's no way to prevent Black from queening. White resigned.   0-1 @@StartBracket@@51@@EndBracket@@ Van den Doel,E @@StartBracket@@2577@@EndBracket@@-Broekmeulen,J @@StartBracket@@2388@@EndBracket@@ Netherlands 2017 }
