{ The following is a model game between IM Jan Vykouk and Scandinavian 'hero' GM Viktor Laznicka from the 2020 Pardubice Rapid Open. }
1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Bd2 Bg4 6. f3 Bd7 7. Bd3
{ is a pretty dumb square for the bishop. It's far better placed on c4. } 7...
Qb6
{ Even stronger was  7...Nc6!  immediately targeting the d4 pawn and supporting the ...e5 pawn break. After  8.Nge2  e5=+  Black is already for choice. }
8. Nge2 e6 9. O-O
{ The machine likes the very enterprising and hard to find  9.b4!  gaining space on the queenside. The b4 pawn is taboo as after  9...Bxb4?  10.Rb1±  is a very awkward pin. Black's bishop will drop after a3. }
9... c5
{ Black executes the most standard Scandinavian pawn break, undermining White's center. }
10. Be3 cxd4 11. Bxd4 Bc5
{ Black successfully broke down White's center and has excellent prospects. }
12. Bxc5 Qxc5+ 13. Kh1 Nc6 14. Ng3 O-O-O
{ is very logical, lining up the d8 rook against White's queen. White's pieces are very poorly placed, especially the bishop on d3 which doesn't allow the first player to easily contest the d-file.   14...O-O  was another good option. Following  15.Qe2  Ne5  16.Nge4  Nxe4  17.Nxe4  Qe7  18.Bb5  Bxb5  19.Qxb5  Qc7=+  Black has the upper hand. White's queenside pawns are big targets with ...Qxc2 and ...Nc4 on the cards. }
15. Nge4 Qe7 16. Bb5
{ 16.Qe1  stepping out of the d-file was a better option. } 16... a6 17. Ba4
Be8
{ Uncovers the rook. Black is now ready to jump into the center of the board with ...Nd4 next.   17...Nxe4  18.Nxe4  f5  was another good option. }
18. Qe1 Nd4 19. Bb3
{ is a mistake as the bishop isn't doing anything on b3.  It was far better to swap off the light-squared bishops with   19.Bxe8  Rhxe8  20.Rd1  when White is still very much in the game. It's important to note that the c2 pawn is untouchable since  20...Nxc2??  21.Rxd8+  Qxd8  22.Qc1  Nd4  23.Nd6+!  23...Qxd6  24.Nb5++-  wins the house. }
19... Bc6 20. Rd1 Nxe4 21. Nxe4 f5
{ Black starts mobilizing his f and e-pawn phalanx while knocking back White's knight.   21...Nxb3  was also great. Following  22.cxb3  Rxd1  23.Qxd1  Rd8  Black is clearly in the driver's seat with ...f5 and .. .Qc7 on the cards. }
22. Nd2 e5 23. Nc4 Nxb3
{ Black eliminates White's light-squared bishop, leaving him with an unoposed monster on c6. There's little White can do to stop Black from creating a passed pawn with ... e4 next. }
24. Rxd8+ Rxd8 25. cxb3 e4 26. Qg3 Qc7 27. f4
{ is big strategic mistake. Black now has a protected passed pawn on e4 not to mention full control over the d-file. }
27... b5
{ is a natural move but there was an even better option.  Far stronger was   27...Bb5!  28.Rc1  Kb8-+  Black rook will now penetrate to d2/d3 with decisive effect. The second player is even threatening the sneaky  29.--  Bxc4  30.bxc4  Qxc4  31.Rxc4  Rd1+  32.Qe1  Rxe1 }
28. Ne5 Bb7 29. Qe3 Kb8
{ Steps out of the c-file, neutralizing White's obvious threat of winning the queen with Rc1. }
30. Rc1 Qd6 31. h3 Qd2 32. Qg1
{ cost White the game.  The first player could have actually forced a draw with the remarkable   32.Nc6+!  Bxc6  33.Qb6+  Bb7  34.Rc7  Qd5  35.Rxb7+  35...Qxb7  36.Qxd8+  Qc8  37.Qb6+  with a perpetual. }
32... e3 { Now there's no stopping Black's e-pawn from deciding the game. } 33.
Nc6+ Bxc6 34. Rxc6 Re8 35. Rc1 Re6 36. Re1 Kb7
{ 36...e2!  37.Qf2  Qxb2-+  was lights out. } 37. Qf1 Re4 38. Re2 Qd4 39. Qf3
Kb6 40. g3 g6 41. Kg2 h6 42. h4 h5 43. Qf1 Qd3 44. Qf3 Re6 45. Qf1 Qd5+
{ 45...Rc6!  followed by ...Rc2/... Rc1 would have won immediately. } 46. Qf3
Kc5 47. Rc2+ Kd4 48. Qxd5+ Kxd5 49. Kf1 Ke4 50. Ke2 Rd6 51. a4 Rd4 52. a5 Rd6
53. b4 Rd3 54. Rc3
{ White resigned as the b2 pawn was about to drop after ... Rd2+.   An instructive game where Black's typical ...c5 pawn break successfully undermined White's center. Once the d4 pawn was exchanged, Black's pieces found very good squares and White found himself on the back foot. A couple of mistakes then cost the first player the game.   0-1 @@StartBracket@@54@@EndBracket@@ Vykouk,J @@StartBracket@@2444@@EndBracket@@-Laznicka,V @@StartBracket@@2658@@EndBracket@@ Pardubice 2020 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model games"]
[Black "0-1 Nayhebaver,M (2482)-Gazik,V (2502) Drienica 2020"]
[Result "*"]

{ The following is a model game between IM Martin Nayhebaver and GM Viktor Gazik in the 5. Bc4 6. f3 variation. }
1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Bc4 Bg4 6. f3 Bd7 7. Bd2 Qb6 8.
Nge2 e6 9. O-O Be7 10. a4
{ It's important to not let White roll Black over on the queenside. The a-pawn should be stopped with }
10... a5 11. Be3 O-O
{ This was all covered in the theoretical section of the course, specifically the9. O-O #2 variation in chapter 7.   Starting with  11...Na6  is another good option and was my recommendation in the theory section. }
12. Bf2
{ Black's plan in this type of position is to engineer the ...c5 break. He can prepare it with ...Rd8 and ...Na6. }
12... Rd8
{ Lining up the rook against White's queen makes a lot of sense and increases the effectiveness of the upcoming ...c5 break.   Black could have also started with the immediate  12...Na6  13.Ne4  c5  14.c3  Rfd8=  with a perfectly fine position. }
13. Ne4 Na6 14. Bb3
{ is inaccurate.   14.c3  was a better option when  14...c5=  equalizes on the spot. }
14... Be8
{ makes some sense, uncovering the d8 rook, but Black had an even better option at his disposal.   I see no reason to delay  14...c5!  which would have given Black the upper hand. }
15. N2c3 { Now } 15... c5 { gives Black a serious advantage. Following } 16.
Nxc5 Nxc5 17. dxc5 Bxc5 18. Qe2 Bc6
{ 18...Rd6  preparing to double on the d-file was another good option. A sample line goes  19.Rad1  Rad8  20.Rxd6  Rxd6  21.Rd1  Bxf2+  22.Qxf2  Rxd1+  23.Nxd1  Qb4  with a clearly better endgame for Black. White's bishop on b3 is completely misplaced and the a4 pawn is a target. }
19. Rfd1 h5
{ This wasn't really called for although Black can afford to play on both sides of the board. }
20. Bxc5 Qxc5+ 21. Qf2 Qb4
{ is a natural square for the queen.   21...Qg5  The queen was better placed here. }
22. Ne2 e5 { gives White unnecessary counterplay.   22...Bd5!  was stronger. }
23. Nc3
{ White immediately clears the e-file, getting ready for Re1 to target the e5 pawn. }
23... h4 24. Re1 Re8
{ 24...h3!?  would have been in line with Black's last moves. } 25. Ne4 Bxe4
{ Black eliminates White's active piece. He now has a knight vs bishop, with White's bishop on b3 being far from ideally placed. }
26. fxe4 h3 { Forces White to compromise his kingside. } 27. g4
{ Simply waiting with  27.Re2  is the machine's suggestion. } 27... Re7 28. Qf3
Rd8
{ Remember to invite everyone to the party! Black brings his last piece into the fray. }
29. g5 Nh7 30. g6
{ blunders a pawn to   30.Qg4  was far better when White is still very much in the game. }
30... Qb6+
{ The double-attack nets Black a pawn, which he converted without too many difficulties. The rest of the game is not relevant for us: }
31. Kh1 Qxg6 32. Qxh3 Rd2 33. Re3 Ng5 34. Qg3 Qh6 35. Rg1 Ne6 36. Rd3 Rxd3 37.
Qxd3 Qh4 38. Bd5 Nf4 39. Qg3 Qf6 40. Qg4 b6
{ 40...g6  41.Qg5  Qd6-+  was lights out. } 41. c4 g6 42. Qg5 Qd6 43. h4
{ Dramatically weakens White's king. He quickly collapsed after } 43... Kg7 44.
Qf5 Qc5 45. Qg4 Qf2 46. Qg3 Qxb2 47. Qg4 Re8 48. Qd7 Rf8 49. Qe7 Qc3
{ White was about to get mated so he resigned.   This game is another good illustration of the power of Black's typical ...c5 break. Once White's center was broken down, Black's pieces sprung into life and he won a nice game after a few inaccuracies by the first player.  0-1  (49)  Nayhebaver,M  (2482)  -Gazik,V  (2502)  Drienica 2020 }
