{ The following is a model game from the 2019 World Rapid Championship between GMs Shamsiddin Vokhidov and GM Viktor Laznicka, the latter being one of the foremost experts on the Scandinavian defense. }
1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Bc4 Bg4 6. Be2
{ is completely harmless. Spending a full tempo retreating the bishop is as unambitious as it gets! }
6... Bxe2 7. Qxe2
{ White's d4 pawn now lacks protection, which Black immediately attacked with }
7... Nc6 8. Nf3 O-O-O
{ 8 moves into the game and White is already in big trouble as there's no good way of covering the d4 pawn. }
9. Be3
{ Better was  9.O-O  when White at least gets something for the pawn following  9...Nxd4  10.Nxd4  Rxd4  11.Be3  Rb4  is the best square for the rook.  Worse is   11...Rd7  12.Nb5  a6  13.a4!  gives White full compensation for the pawn deficit.  12.a4=+  While not enough for a pawn, here White at least has some play with ideas of Nb5. }
9... e5
{ Black undermines White's center, opening up his dark-squared bishop with a deadly threat in mind. }
10. dxe5 { 10.Rd1  runs into  10...Ba3∓ } 10... Ba3
{ is a fantastic move! The bishop is untouchable as the c3 knight followed by the rook on a1 would drop with check. }
11. O-O { 11.bxa3??  loses on the spot to  11...Qxc3+  12.Bd2  Qxa1+-+ } 11...
Bxb2 12. Rab1 Bxc3 13. exf6 Bxf6
{ White has nothing to show for the missing pawn. Any ideas of a queenside attack are nothing but a pipe dream. }
14. Nd2 Nd4 15. Bxd4
{ is practically forced.   15.Qc4  runs into  15...Qd5  16.Qxd5  Rxd5-+ } 15...
Bxd4
{ Let's take stock. Black has an extra pawn, the better minor piece and the superior pawn structure. This tallies up to a decisive advantage Laznicka had little trouble converting. }
16. Nb3 Qf5 17. Nxd4 Rxd4 18. c3 Re4 19. Qb2 b6 20. Qc2 Rhe8
{ Black brings his last piece into the game and is fully centralized, with every single one of his pieces being superior to White's counterpart. }
21. Rb4 g6 22. Qd3 Kb7 23. Rxe4 Rxe4 24. g3 Qe6 25. Qf3 f5
{ Anchors the rook on the powerful e4 square. Notice how Laznicka gradually improves his position before going in for the kill. }
26. Re1 a5 27. h4 a4 28. a3 Qc6 29. Re3 Rc4 30. Qxc6+ Kxc6 31. Kf1
{ There's no stopping Black's king from collecting White's queenside pawns. }
31... Kb5 32. Rd3 Rc6 33. Ke2 Kc4 34. Kd2 Rd6 35. Rxd6 cxd6 36. Kc2 d5
{ White resigned since the pawn endgame is dead lost.   This time it was Black's ...break that gave him an edge, with the beautiful ...Ba3 shot netting him a pawn. White never recovered.  0-1 @@StartBracket@@36@@EndBracket@@ Vokhidov,S @@StartBracket@@2526@@EndBracket@@-Laznicka,V @@StartBracket@@2648@@EndBracket@@ Moscow 2019 }
