{ The following is a model game between Czech GMs Petr Haba and Viktor Laznicka, one of the foremost experts on the Scandinavian. He's one of those players whose games in the Scandinavian you'll do well not to miss. }
1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bf5 6. Ne5 c6 7. Bc4 e6 8. g4
Bg6 9. h4 Nbd7 10. Nxd7 Nxd7 11. h5 Be4 12. O-O Bd5 13. Nxd5 cxd5 14. Bd3 Bd6
15. a4 Qd8
{ Threatens to invade with ...Qh4, but it can be easily neutralized.   15...O-O  was my recommendation in thetheory section. }
16. Kg2 { is a great response. White is now ready to meet ...Qh4 with Rh1. }
16... Qe7
{ I'm not a big believer in this move. The queen isn't particularly well placed on e7.   16...O-O  is preferable. }
17. a5
{ 17.Rh1  would have given White a big edge after  17...O-O  18.Qf3  White can slowly build up on the kingside while it's not clear what Black should do in the meantime. }
17... a6 { Stops White's a-pawn from moving any further. } 18. c3 g6 19. h6
{ is a mistake, which allows Black to break with 19...f5.   19.Rh1  Keeping the tension and threatening to win material with hxg6 was a better option. }
19... f5
{ Threatens to rip open White's kingside and severely limits White's light-squared bishop. White's king is suddenly very uncomfortable. }
20. f4
{ White limits his own dark-squared bishop and allows Black to rip open the f-file with 20...fxg4.   20.g5  Keeping the position closed was a better try. }
20... fxg4 21. Qxg4 Nf6 22. Qg5 Rf8
{ The f4 pawn is a big target, which is about to be attacked with ...Nh5. } 23.
Bd2 Nh5 24. Rae1
{ is natural, bringing the last piece into the game but it's tactically flawed. Here's why:   24.Qg4  Keeping an eye on the e6 pawn was much better. }
24... Nxf4+ 25. Bxf4 Rxf4 26. Qxe7+
{ White has no time for   26.Rxf4  as his queen is hanging.  26...Qxg5+-+  Oops. }
26... Kxe7 27. Rxf4 Bxf4
{ is an opposite-colored bishop endgame Laznicka converted with good technique. Black is currently a pawn up and the h6 one isn't long for this world. }
28. c4 Kf6 29. Rf1 Kg5 30. Re1 dxc4 31. Bxc4 Rd8 32. Rxe6 Rxd4 33. b3 Rd7 34.
Kf3 Bd6 35. Re4 Kxh6 36. Rd4 Kg5 37. b4 h5 38. b5 axb5 39. Bxb5 Rf7+ 40. Kg2
Bc7 41. a6 bxa6 42. Bxa6 Rf6 43. Bc8 Bf4 44. Bd7 Rb6 45. Re4 Rd6 46. Bc8 Rd2+
47. Kf1 Rd8 48. Rc4 Rf8 49. Kg2 Kh4 50. Rc3 Rd8 51. Rh3+ Kg5 52. Rc3 Be5 53.
Rc6 Kf4 54. Rc4+ Ke3 55. Rc2 g5 56. Be6 g4 57. Ra2 Rd4 58. Ra5 Kf4 59. Rc5 Rd2+
60. Kf1 h4 61. Ke1 Rd6 62. Bxg4 Bd4
{ White's rook and bishop are both hanging so he'll end up down a piece. With the h-pawn on the board, White had no chances and resigned.    0-1 @@StartBracket@@62@@EndBracket@@ Haba,P @@StartBracket@@2432@@EndBracket@@-Laznicka,V  @@StartBracket@@2669@@EndBracket@@ Pardubice 2017. }
