[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model games"]
[Black "½-½ Harikrishna,P (2730)-Hera,I (2611) Brest 2019"]
[Result "*"]

{ The following is a model game between super-GM Pentala Harikrishna and Hungarian GM Imre Hera from the 2019 French Team Championship. It features one of the most theoretical and critical variations in the 3...Qa5 Scandinavian. }
1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6 6. Bc4 Bf5 7. Ne5 e6 8. g4
Bg6 9. h4 Nbd7 10. Nxd7 Nxd7 11. h5 Be4 12. O-O Bd5 13. Nxd5 cxd5 14. Bd3 Bd6
15. c3 O-O-O 16. Qf3 Rdf8
{ This was all covered in the theoretical section of the course, specifically in the15. c3 #1 variation in chapter 10.   16...Rde8  is stronger than the text and was my recommendation. By protecting the e6 pawn, Black neutralizes the threat of Qxf7. }
17. Be3
{ is a harmless setup. The bishop is not well placed on e3, where it obstructs the e-file and doesn't put any pressure on Black's position.   17.Kg2  was preferable, with the plan of fixing Black's kingside with  17...Kb8  18.h6  g6  19.Re1  Keeps an eye on the e6 pawn, preventing Black from breaking with ...f5. White can now try to make something happen on the queenside. }
17... Kb8 18. Rfc1
{ White has made a bunch of seemingly natural but aimless, disconnected moves. In the meantime, Black has coordinate himself to execute the following timely pawn break: }
18... f5
{ gives Black excellent counterplay on the kingside. White is ill-prepared to meet this. }
19. gxf5
{ Trying to keep the kingside closed with  19.g5?  allows Black to break in the center with  19...e5!  when White is in big trouble.  20.Qh3  is relatively best   Alternatively  20.b4?!  is strongly met by  20...Qc7  21.Qxd5  when there's no stopping Black's pawns after  21...e4  22.Be2  Nb6  23.Qe6  f4  24.Bd2  e3!  is a fantastic clearance sacrifice.  25.fxe3  f3−+  And Black's f-pawn is just too strong. White is busted.  20...e4  21.Be2  g6  22.h6  Qd8  Targets the g5 pawn when  23.f4  fails to keep it alive after  23...exf3  24.Bxf3  f4  25.Bf2  Qxg5∓ }
19... exf5
{ Black can now look to transfer his knight to the e4 outpost.   19...g5!?  was very interesting albeit hard to spot. A possible line is  20.Kh1  Rhg8  21.Rg1  h6  22.Qh3  exf5↑  with excellent attacking chances. }
20. Bg5 Nf6 21. c4
{ is the point behind 18. Rfc1. However, it fails to bring White anything of value. }
21... dxc4 22. Rxc4 Qd5
{ is solid, seeking to exchange the queens and transfer the game into an equal endgame.   Black could have played more ambitiously with  22...g6  23.h6  Ne4  24.Bf4  Ka8  The game continues and you'd probably be a bit more nervous as White. }
23. Qxf5
{ is inaccurate.   23.Qxd5  Nxd5=  with a level endgame. It's unclear to me why White didn't go for this as it's essentially an improved version of the text. }
23... Qxf5 24. Bxf5 Nxh5
{ Black restores material equality with an advantageous position. The knight is about to land on f4 when Black's kingside pawns can start marching down the board. Conversely, White's d4 pawn is firmly under Black's control. }
25. Bg4 Nf4 26. Re1 h5 27. Bxf4
{ Harikrishna slams on the breaks at just the right moment before his position deteriorates any further, transferring the game into a holdable opposite-colored bishops endgame. }
27... Bxf4 28. Bh3 Rf7
{ 28...g5  was possible. It allows White to invade the 7th with  29.Re7  when  29...Re8  30.Rf7  would have likely resulted in a draw. }
29. d5 g5 30. Be6
{ Black is certainly a bit better and could have played on. He was probably content with a draw with Black, especially given that this was a team event.   This game showcases that the struggle after 14...Bd6 is not one-sided. A super-GM with the White pieces struggled to find an active plan. Black coordinated perfectly and executed a timely pawn break when White had to play precisely to keep afloat. Another reason for #TeamScandi to smile!  ½-½  (30)  Harikrishna,P  (2730)  -Hera,I  (2611)  Brest 2019 }
