{ The following is a blitz game between GMs Ian Nepomniatchi and Igor Kovalenko from the 2018 World Blitz Championship that took place in St. Petersburg. }
1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bf5 6. Bd2 e6 7. Bc4 Bb4 8.
a3 Bxc3 9. Bxc3
{ As remarked in the theory section, White has just won the bishop pair. However, the dark-squared bishop on c3 is unremarkable and confined to the passive role of protecting the d4 and b2 pawns. }
9... Qb6 10. b3
{ is not only uncritical, but actually dubious.   10.Qe2  or  10.d5  - both extensively analyzed inchapter 11 - are far better options. }
10... Nbd7
{ is not the right way to punish White's approach.   10...Nc6!  is a much more active post for the knight, which leaves the d-file unobstructed.  11.O-O  O-O-O⭢  followed by ...Bg4 puts the d4 pawn under a lot of pressure. }
11. O-O O-O 12. h3
{ looks like a very standard Scandinavian position where neither side is doing much. Appearances are however deceptive. }
12... Be4 13. Re1
{ is inaccurate. The next series of moves demonstrates the dynamic potential in Black's position.   Better was  13.Bd3  Qc6  14.Bxe4  Nxe4  15.Bb2  with a level game. }
13... Qc6
{ Suddenly, after a single imprecise move, White is under pressure. Black is threatening ...Bxf3 and White cannot play the Be2 since the c3 bishop would then hang. }
14. Ne5 { is thus forced.   14.Be2??  blunders a piece to  14...Qxc3−+ } 14...
Nxe5 15. dxe5 Nd5
{ Removes the knight from danger with a counterattack on White's c3 bishop. }
16. Bd2 { 16.Rxe4??  blunders the rook to  16...Nxc3−+ } 16... Nb6
{ is a strong retreating move, forcing White's bishop away from c4 when the c2 pawn will drop. }
17. Bb5 { is flashy but can just be ignored. } 17... Qxc2
{ 17...Qxb5  18.Rxe4  is White's point. } 18. Qxc2 Bxc2 19. Rec1 Bxb3 20. Rxc7
Bd5
{ Black was up a pawn and outplayed White right down to a winning pawn ending. He faltered at the very last moment and Nepo miraculously escaped with a draw - a not so infrequent outcome in blitz games when both players get down to seconds. }
21. Be3 Rfc8 22. Rac1 Bc6 23. Rxc8+ Rxc8 24. Bxb6 axb6 25. Rb1 Be4 26. Rb4 Bd5
27. f3 Rc3 28. a4 Re3 29. Kf2 Rxe5 30. Bd3 Bc6 31. Rxb6 Ra5 32. Bb5 Bd5 33. Rd6
Ra8 34. Rd7 Rc8 35. h4 g6 36. Kg3 h6 37. Kf2 Kg7 38. Ke3 Rc2 39. g3 Rc3+ 40.
Bd3 Ra3 41. Rc7 Rxa4 42. f4 Ra3 43. Ke2 Bc6 44. Bc4 Kf6 45. Bd3 Ra2+ 46. Kf1
Rd2 47. Be2 Rb2 48. Bd3 Bd5 49. Be2 b5 50. h5 b4 51. hxg6 Kxg6 52. Bd3+ Kf6 53.
Bh7 Kg7 54. Bd3 b3 55. Rc8 Rd2 56. Be2 Rc2 57. Rb8 b2 58. Bd3 Rc3 59. Ke2 Rb3
60. Rxb3 Bxb3 61. Bb1 Bd5 62. Kd2 f5 63. Kc3 Be4 64. Bxe4 fxe4 65. Kxb2 Kf6
{ blunders the win.   65...Kg6  would have easily won. The difference to the game is that  66.g4  can now be met with  66...h5−+ }
66. g4 e5 67. f5 h5 68. gxh5 Kxf5 69. Kc3 Kg5 70. Kd2 Kxh5 71. Ke3
{ And a draw was agreed.  ½-½  (71)  Nepomniachtchi,I  (2763)  -Kovalenko,I  (2657)  St Petersburg 2018 }
