{ The following is a rapid game between Dutch GMs Jorden Van Foreest and Roeland Pruijssers from the 2019 Rapid Dutch Championship. }
1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bf5 6. d4 e6 7. Bd2 Bb4 8.
a3 Bxc3 9. Bxc3 Qb6 10. O-O Nc6 11. a4 a5
{ This was all covered in the theory section of the course, specifically in the11. a4 #1 variation in chapter 11. }
12. b3
{ is an option we didn't examine there. The reason is that it's not at all a good move, allowing Black to immediately take over the initiative with }
12... O-O-O 13. Bb2 Bg4
{ The d4 pawn is coming under heavy fire. Black is already quite a bit better. }
14. c3
{ is a big mistake.   14.h3  was certainly better. I still doubt White has anywhere close to enough compensation for the pawn after  14...Bxf3  15.Qxf3  Nxd4=+ }
14... Ne5
{ is very strong, exploiting the pin along the d-file. White's in massive trouble. }
15. Qe2 Nxc4 16. bxc4 Bxf3
{ 16...Qa6∓  It was far more precise to start with this move. } 17. gxf3
{ White returns the favor.   17.Qxf3!  remarkably draws. The point is that after  17...Qxb2  18.Rfb1  Qc2  19.Qxb7+  Kd7  Black cannot escape perpetual check. For example  20.Qb5+  Ke7  Black should of course avoid   20...c6?  when  21.Qb7+  Ke8  22.Qxc6+  Kf8  23.Qc7  Re8  24.Rb7+-  is decisive.  21.Qc5+  Ke8  22.Qxc7  Qxc3  23.d5  Nxd5  24.Qc6+=  is just barely enough for a draw. That would have been a Houdini-like escape! }
17... Qa6
{ 17...e5!  was also very strong.  18.dxe5  Nd7∓  being the point. Black is essentially playing with an extra minor piece as White's bishop on b2 is terrible. }
18. Rab1 Nd5
{ Black takes advantage of yet another pin. The knight is headed to b6 to attack White's weak pawns. }
19. Rfe1 Nb6 20. c5 Qxe2 21. Rxe2 Nc4 22. Bc1 Rd5
{ Black is dominating in this endgame. The knight on c4 is a monster and White's position is riddled with weaknesses. I'll refrain from commenting on the rest of the game as Black was winning throughout its entirety but let White escape at the very end. }
23. Bf4 Rf5 24. Bg3 Rxf3 25. d5 Re8 26. Rc1 Rf5 27. Rd1 c6 28. dxc6 bxc6 29.
Rb1 e5 30. Rbe1 Rd8 31. Bxe5 Nd2 32. Bd6 Nf3+ 33. Kg2 Nxe1+ 34. Rxe1 Rxd6 35.
cxd6 Kd7 36. Re7+ Kxd6 37. Ra7 g5 38. Kf1 g4 39. Ke2 h5 40. Ke3 Rf3+ 41. Ke2
Rxc3 42. Rxa5 Rh3 43. Rf5 Rxh2 44. Kf1 Rh1+ 45. Ke2 Ra1
{ Black could have won immediately with  45...Ke6!  46.Rc5  h4  47.Rxc6+  Kf5-+   or  45...h4!  46.Rxf7  h3  47.Rh7  h2-+ }
46. Rxf7 Rxa4 47. Rf6+ Kc7 48. Rh6 Ra5 49. Ke3 Rf5 50. Ke4 Rxf2 51. Rxh5 g3 52.
Rg5 g2 53. Kd4 Kb6 54. Kc4 Re2 { 54...Kc7!  55.Rg6  Kd7-+  was winning. } 55.
Kd3 { 55.Rg7=  holds. } 55... Ra2 56. Kc4 Rb2
{ 56...Kc7-+  would have led to a win. } 57. Rg7 Rd2 58. Kc3 Rf2 59. Kc4 Rf4+
60. Kc3 Rf3+ 61. Kc4 Rf2 62. Kb4 Re2 63. Kc4 Ka6 64. Kb4 Rf2 65. Kc4 Ka5 66.
Ra7+ Kb6 67. Rg7 Ra2 68. Kb3 Re2 69. Kc4 Ka6 70. Kb4 Rf2 71. Kc4 Kb6 72. Kb4
