[Black "½-½ Karjakin,S (2750) -Mamedyarov,S (2764) Saint Louis 2019"]
[Result "*"]

{ The following is a high-profile game in the 5. Nf3 mainline of the Scandinavian between super-GMs Sergey Karjakin with the White pieces and Shakriyar Mamedyarov playing Black from 2019 Sinquefield Cup. }
1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bf5 6. Bd2 e6 7. Bc4 Bb4 8.
a3 Bxc3 9. Bxc3 Qb6 10. d5 { leads to a two results endgame after } 10... exd5
{ 10...Nbd7!  was mymain recommendation in the theory section. } 11. Bxd5 Be6
{ As mentioned in thetheory section, immediately exchanging the light-squared bishops is most precise. }
12. Bxe6 Qxe6+ 13. Qe2 Qxe2+ 14. Kxe2 Nbd7
{ White is slightly better having a bishop versus a knight in a relatively open position with pawns on both flanks. His advantage is, however, minimal and Black can hold with precise play. }
15. Rhe1 O-O-O 16. Kf1 { with ideas of Re7 and Ng5 is White's best move. }
16... h6 17. Re7 Rhf8
{ This was all covered in the theoretical section of the course, specifically in the10. d5 #5 alternative line in chapter 11. Black covers the f7 pawn and is ready to neutralize White's rook with ...Rde8 next. }
18. Bxf6
{ White exchanges his bishop so as to go after the f7 pawn with Ne5.   18.Rd1  with the idea of sacrificing an exchange after  18...Rde8   18...g6  or  18...b6  are good alternatives  19.Rexd7  Nxd7  20.Bxg7  Rg8  21.Bxh6  was far more testing. Nonetheless, Black should hold with precise play after  21...Ne5  22.Nxe5  Rxe5  .  White can press for many moves by playing Be3, g2-g3 and then start pushing the h-pawn down the board. Provided White avoids the exchange of rooks, Black will find it hard to create any counterplay. The second player can hold with precise play, but it is no fun. This unpleasant possibility is the reason my main recommendation on move 10 in the theory section was 10...Nbd7! }
18... Nxf6 19. Ne5 Rfe8
{ is an easy enough solution, killing the game.   19...a5  is an interesting machine suggestion, who is not bothered by Rxf7 since ...Rd2 will give Black excellent counterplay. }
20. Rxe8 Rxe8 21. Nxf7
{ Black is not bothered by this move as he'll soon recoup the pawn. } 21... Ng4
22. f3
{ 22.h3  is strongly met by  22...Nxf2  when  23.Kxf2   23.Nxh6  Nxh3  changes nothing.  Rf8  followed by ...Rxf7 restores material equality with a dead drawn endgame. }
22... Ne3+ { The c2 pawn now drops. } 23. Kf2 Nxc2 24. Rc1
{ Hoping for a cheapo, which probably took Mamedyarov ms to realize. } 24...
Re7 { Of course not  24...Nd4??  which blunders the rook to  25.Nd6++- } 25.
Rxc2
{ 25.Nd6+  cxd6  26.Rxc2+  Kd7=  is dead equal.   25.Nxh6  also doesn't bring White anything. After  25...Nd4  Black is threatening ...Re2. White should play  26.Rc4  Re2+  27.Kg3  Rd2=  with the idea ...b5 works well. }
25... Rxf7 { The knights are off the board and a draw was soon agreed. } 26.
Ke3 Kd7 27. Rd2+ Ke7 28. Rc2 Kd7 29. Rd2+ Ke7 30. Rc2 Kd7 31. Rd2+
{ The 10. d5 variation leads to a two results endgame for White and one that Mamedyarov held in his sleep.    Incidentally, the following was the World-Champion's tweet about this uneventful game: @@StartBlockQuote@@When Mamedyarov and Karjakin play, everybody knows what's gonna happen. -Magnus Carlsen@@EndBlockQuote@@½-½ @@StartBracket@@31@@EndBracket@@ Karjakin,S @@StartBracket@@2750@@EndBracket@@ -Mamedyarov,S @@StartBracket@@2764@@EndBracket@@ Saint Louis 2019 }
