[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model games"]
[Black "0-1 Renet,O (2520)-Prie,E (2480) Clichy 1995"]
[Result "*"]

{ The following game is a miniature between French GMs Olivier Renet and Eric Prie from the 1995 Clichy tournament. Eric Prie is a Scandi 'hero', having played the opening very successfully against GM opposition for over three decades. Here he defeated a GM in only 14 moves! }
1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 c6
{ The more flexible  4...Bf5!  was my recommendation in the theory section. There's no need to spend a tempo on ... c6 immediately. While the bishop belongs on f5, Black can do without ...c6 in many lines. This gives the second player the option of developing the b8 knight in one go, when ...O-O-O can become interesting to pressure the d4 pawn, as well as the option of breaking in the center with ...c7-c5 in one go. }
5. Nf3 Bf5 6. Bd2 Nf6 7. Ne4
{ White unleashes a discovered attack on Black's queen, his point being that after }
7... Qb6 { he can now spoil Black's structure with } 8. Nxf6+ gxf6
{ It's unclear White has achieved much with his knight sortie. In exchange for the compromised structure, Black now has the open g-file to operate with and the pawn on f6 prevents White from jumping into e5. }
9. Bc4 Rg8 10. Bb3 a5 { Goes after White's light-squared bishop, provoking }
11. a4
{ There was no need for this move, which weakened the b4 square.   White could have and, in fact should, have ignored Black's 'threat' with  11.O-O  the point being that after  11...a4  12.Bc4  Qxb2  13.Rb1  Qxc2  14.Qxc2  Bxc2  15.Rxb7  White is fully mobilized and already has a rook on the 7th, affording the first player more than enough compensation for the missing pawn. }
11... Na6 12. Qe2
{ White clears the back rank, getting ready to castle long but little did he know what Black had in store! It's understandable that with the g-file open, White opted against castling short. However, the king would have been pretty safe on that isle as Black would have had a hard time bringing pieces over to the kingside.   12.O-O  was a better option. There's no need to be scared of  12...Bh3?  which loses material to  13.Ng5! }
12... Nb4 13. O-O-O { Loses outright to the stunning } 13... Nd3+ 14. cxd3
{ 14.Kb1  is also no good.  14...Qxb3  15.cxb3  Now the discovered attack  15...Nf4+  nets Black a piece.  16.Ka2  Nxe2  17.Rhe1  Bc2  18.Ra1  Bd3-+  It's clear Black's knight won't be trapped so he's simply a piece up. }
14... Qxb3
{ With the a4 pawn about to drop and his king very exposed, White was so disgusted with his position that he resigned.    0-1 @@StartBracket@@14@@EndBracket@@ Renet,O @@StartBracket@@2520@@EndBracket@@-Prie,E  @@StartBracket@@2480@@EndBracket@@ Clichy 1995 }
*

