[White "Model games"]
[Black "0-1 Heimann,A (2622)-Nisipeanu,L (2655) Magdeburg 2020"]
[Result "*"]

{ The following is a model game in the 3. Nf3 variation between GMs Andreas Heimann and Liviu-Dieter Nisipeanu. }
1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nf3 Nf6
{ 3...Bg4  was my recommendation in the theory section. Despite Black not following my preferred approach, the game is still instructive. }
4. d4 Bg4 5. Be2 Nc6
{ The pressure on the d4 pawn forces White to take action. } 6. c4 Qh5
{ 6...Qf5  is more reliable. After  7.O-O  O-O-O  8.Be3  e5  Black has good play as mentioned in thebonus chapter on the 2...Nf6 Scandi. }
7. h3
{ is a complete waste of tempo. The bishop on g4 is untouchable as the h3 pawn is pinned.   7.Be3!  is far better. The point is that  7...O-O-O  8.Nbd2!  blocks the d-file, meaning  e5  here fails to break down White's center. The first player can simply push the d-pawn forward  9.d5+=  and enjoy a slight advantage due to the extra space in the center. }
7... O-O-O { Black is ready to strike in the center with ...e5. } 8. Be3 e5 9.
d5 e4 10. Nd4
{ is a mistake, which could have allowed Black to gain a strong initiative.   10.Nfd2  was a better option. After  10...Ne5  11.Nc3  Nd3+  12.Kf1  Bxe2+  13.Qxe2  Qg6=  The position is hard to assess. The e4 pawn is potentially a weakness but White has a hard time attacking it. Black should be fine. }
10... Bb4+
{ Black let a big opportunity pass by.   10...Ne5!  was much stronger! Following  11.Bxg4+  Nexg4  12.O-O  Bd6  Black has a strong initiative. For example  13.Re1  Bh2+  14.Kh1  is forced.   14.Kf1??  loses on the spot to  14...Nxe3+  15.fxe3  Qg6-+  14...Bf4!  15.Qe2  Qg5∓  The knight on g4 is still untouchable. Black will play ...Nxe3 next with a big advantage. }
11. Nd2
{ And White returns the favor.   11.Nc3  was much better.  11...Bxe2  12.Ndxe2  Ne5  13.Qa4  Nd3+  14.Kf1∞  leads to a similar position to 10. Nfd2. }
11... Bxe2 { Black doesn't miss his chance now. Following a set of exchanges }
12. Qxe2 Ne5 13. Qxh5 Nxh5
{ White's position is riddled with light-squared weaknesses. Black's kingside pawn majority is also a big asset. }
14. b3 c6 15. O-O
{ 15.dxc6  loses to  15...Nd3+  16.Ke2   16.Kf1  Bxd2  17.Bxd2  Rxd4-+  Nhf4+  17.Kd1  Bc3-+ }
15... cxd5
{ is an imprecise move order, but not because of this move.   Black should have started with  15...Bxd2  16.Bxd2  cxd5∓ }
16. cxd5
{ 16.Rad1!  was necessary. Following  16...Bxd2  17.Rxd2  dxc4  18.bxc4  Rd7=+  with the idea ...Rhd8 is better for Black but White is still very much in the game. }
16... Bxd2 17. Bxd2 Rxd5 18. Bc3
{ blunders the game away.   18.Be3  was more much more tenacious, intending to meet  18...Nd3?!  with   18...Re8∓  is what Black should play with a significant advantage.  19.Ne2  heading to either g3 or c3 to attack the e4 pawn. }
18... Nd3 { Now Black's pieces are too dominant. } 19. f3 e3 20. Rad1 Nhf4
{ White was defenseless against Black's multiple ideas, especially ...e2 and so he threw in the towel. It's not every day you see a 2600+ GM go down in 20 moves with the White pieces.   0-1 @@StartBracket@@20@@EndBracket@@ Heimann,A @@StartBracket@@2622@@EndBracket@@-Nisipeanu,L @@StartBracket@@2655@@EndBracket@@ Magdeburg 2020 }
