[Round "?"]
[White "Model games"]
[Black "0-1 Sutovsky,E (2687)-Van Wely,L (2691) Istanbul 2012"]
[Result "*"]

{ The following is a miniature in the 5. Nf3 mainline of the Scandinavian between GMs Emil Sutovsky and Loek Van Wely from the 2012 Istanbul Olympiad. Emil tends to go for very aggressive lines with the White pieces, and this game was certainly no exception! }
1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c6
{ I don't have much faith in this line but it is still playable.   You'll recall that  5...Bf5  was my recommendation in thetheory section. }
6. Bd2 Bf5 7. Ne5
{ is an unusual move and much less common than 7. Bc4. White wants to roll Black over on the kingside with g4 next. }
7... Nbd7 8. g4
{ Sutovsky stays true to his style, playing aggressive lines wherever possible. In this particular position, such a caveman-style advance fails to impress.   The more reserved  8.Nc4  was a better option. }
8... Be6
{ is the best square for the bishop.   8...Bg6?  9.f4!  e6  10.h4  would have given Sutovsky exactly what he was looking for. }
9. f4
{ In for a penny, in for a pound! Sutovsky is not one for half measures. } 9...
O-O-O
{ is inaccurate.   9...Nxe5!  was the correct way to punish White's aggression. After  10.fxe5  Nxg4  11.Bg2  g6  12.Ne4  Qb6  13.c3  Bh6=+  White is two pawns down and I fail to see much if any compensation. }
10. Qf3
{ was almost surely based on a miscalculation.   10.Bc4!  would've given White the position he was seeking. For example  10...Nxg4  runs into the powerful   10...Bxc4  is a better option when  11.Nxc4  Qa6  12.b3  e6  13.Qe2=  is roughly level.  11.Nd5!  A move I'm sure Sutovsky would have found in seconds. After  11...Qa4  12.Nc3  Qa5  13.Ne4±  Black's queen is being pushed around while White is improving his position. Black's in big trouble. }
10... Nxe5 11. dxe5
{ blunders the game away.   White was still in time to avoid disaster with  11.fxe5  Nxg4  12.h3  Nh6  13.Bxh6  Bd5!  14.Qg4+  e6  15.Bg5∓  White is worse but still very much in the game. }
11... Rxd2
{ Boom! This move must have come as a total shock. White has no good way of meeting it. }
12. exf6
{ 12.Kxd2  is no improvement.  12...Bd5  Black exploits the fact that the c3 knight is pinned.  13.Qe3  Ne4+!  Check!  14.Kc1  Nxc3  15.Rg1  Nxa2+-+  leaves Black with a decisive material advantage. }
12... Rxc2 13. Bd3 Rxb2 14. Rc1 exf6
{ Black has three extra pawns and easily converted his advantage. White could have already resigned but continued for a few more moves }
15. O-O h5 { Hunting season is on! White's king is very exposed. } 16. g5 fxg5
17. Nd1 Bc5+ 18. Kh1 g4
{ with the threat ...Bd5 to follow sealed the deal. What a crushing miniature with the Scandi!   0-1 @@StartBracket@@18@@EndBracket@@ Sutovsky,E @@StartBracket@@2687@@EndBracket@@-Van Wely,L @@StartBracket@@2691@@EndBracket@@ Istanbul 2012 }
