[White "Bonus: 2...Nf6 Scandi | Portuguese Gambit & Others"]
[Black "Overview"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this chapter, I propose an aggressive blitz and rapid repertoire based on the 2...Nf6 Scandinavian and the fiery Portugese and Icelandic Gambits. }
1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6 3. d4
{ White's 3rd move alternatives such as  3.Bb5  ,  3.Nf3  and  3.Nc3  are also covered in this chapter.   Against  3.c4  you can choose either the Icelandic Gambit with  3...e6  or instead  3...c6  . These options are the topic of thenext chapter. }
3... Bg4
{ Despite being objectively dubious, the Portuguese Gambit is an excellent blitz and rapid weapon. White has to be quite precise in order to get an advantage with Black having a whole array of devious tricks and traps at his disposal.  Have fun learning and playing this provocative gambit!  Note: If you're an advanced/master-level player, I do not recommend employing this bonus repertoire consistently in classical time controls as it is significantly inferior to the 2...Qxd5 3...Qa5 Scandinavian.  In the excellent book Smerdon’s Scandinavian, GM David Smerdon put it best: @@StartBlockQuote@@Make no mistake about it: from any fundamental mainstream chess perspective, the @@StartSquare@@Portuguese Gambit@@EndSquare@@ has to be, should be unsound. If you are the sort who likes to attack no matter the risks, if you enjoy coffeehouse gambits and highly unorthodox tactical skirmishes, if you revel in adventure in each game or want to unsettle your opponent and get the fight onto your home turf from move one, then this just might be for you.@@EndBlockQuote@@ }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Bonus: 2...Nf6 Scandi | Portuguese Gambit & Others"]
[Black "Repertoire clashes"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6 3. d4
{ 3.Nf3  Bg4  was not considered in the Chessable course Smash the Scandinavian by ZacAttack.  4.c4  was recommended in the Chessable course Lifetime Repertoires: Sethuraman's 1.e4. Clickhere for more details.   4.Bb5+  Nbd7  5.h3  Bh5  6.Nc3  a6  7.Be2  was recommended in the Chessable course Lifetime Repertoires: Wesley So's 1.e4 and in the book Kaufman's New Repertoire for Black and White. The clash with GMs Wesley So and Larry Kaufman's suggestions can be foundhere.   IM Andrew Greet in the book Beating Unusual Chess Defences: 1.e4 also went for  7.Be2  with the specific clash occurringhere.   3.c4  c6  4.d4  cxd5  5.Nc3  g6  6.Qb3  Bg7  7.cxd5  O-O  8.Be2   8.Nge2  a5  was not considered in the book The Panov-Botvinnik Attack: Move by Move by IM Lorin D'Costa. Clickhere for more details.  Na6  9.Bf3  Qb6  10.Nge2  was suggested by IM Sam Collins in the Chessable course The Furious Panov-Botvinik. Clickhere for more information.   10.Qxb6  axb6  11.Nge2  was also recommended by IM Lorin D'Costa in the book The Panov-Botvinnik Attack: Move by Move. Clickhere for more info.   3.Bb5+  Nbd7  4.Nf3  was recommended in the Chessable course Keep it Simple 1.e4 by IM Christof Sielecki and in the database Complete Repertoire against the Alekhine and Scandinavian by GM Zahar Efimenko. The details can be foundhere.   4.c4  a6  5.Bxd7+  Qxd7  6.d3  Qg4  was not considered by GM Avetik Grigoryan in the video series Crush the Scandinavian for chessmood.com  7.Qxg4  Bxg4  8.Nf3  was my suggestion in my 1.e4 course Crush the Alekhine and the Scandinavian as mentionedhere.   6.Nf3  was the choice of IM Chris Baker and FM Graham Burgess in the book A Startling Chess Opening Repertoire. Clickhere for the clash. }
3... Bg4 4. f3
{ 4.Nf3  was IM Andrew Greet's choice in the book Beating Unusual Chess Defences: 1.e4. More info can be foundhere.   4.Be2  was recommended in the book Chess Openings for White, Explained by GMs Lev Alburt, Roman Dzindzichashvil, and Eugene Perelshteyn. Clickhere for the specific clash.   4.Bb5  was recommended in the book GM Repertoire: 1.e4 vs Minor Defences by GM Parimarjan Negi as denotedhere.   It was also suggested in the book A Simple Chess Opening Repertoire for White by IM Sam Collins. More information can be foundhere. }
4... Bf5 5. g4
{ 5.Bb5+  was recommended by GM John Shaw in the book Playing 1.e4. Caro-Kann, 1...e5 and Minor Lines and in the Chessable course 1.e4: A Comprehensive White Repertoire by NM Elijah Logozar. Clickhere for the specific clash. }
5... Bg6 6. c4
{ was recommended in the book Kaufman's New Repertoire for Black and White by GM Larry Kaufman. Clickhere for the details.   GM Justin Tan also opted for this variation in the book 1.e4! The Chess Bible with the specific clash occurringhere. }
