[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Bonus: 2...Nf6 Scandi | Portuguese Gambit & Others"]
[Black "Inspirational game #1: 0-1 Ye,J (2560)-Damaso,R (2415) Macau 1996"]
[Result "*"]

{ Before jumping straight into theory, let's go through one of the most exciting games ever played in the Portuguese Gambit. This and the subsequent games by the creative Portuguese IM Rui Damaso are the reason the variation bears the name of his country.  In 1996, Portugal and China met for a round-robin match in Macao, a former Portuguese colony. In round three, Damaso bamboozled one of China's top GMs with 3...Bg4, taking him down in style: }
1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6 3. d4 Bg4 4. Be2
{ is a solid variation, where White returns the pawn in order to quickly castle kingside. If surprised by the novel 3...Bg4 I'd probably opt for this 'safe' option as well. }
4... Bxe2 5. Qxe2 Qxd5 6. Nf3 e6 7. O-O
{ is a sensible option, getting the king to safety.   As we'll see in the theory section,  7.c4!  is the best way to fight for an opening advantage. }
7... Bd6 8. c4 Qh5
{ Black is threatening to win on the spot with ...Bxh2+, taking advantage of the fact that White's queen on e2 is unprotected. }
9. Nc3 Nc6 10. h3 O-O-O
{ The kings are castled on opposite sides of the board. We all know what that means, whoever gets to the opponent's king first tends to win. The race is on! }
11. Be3 g5
{ is very enterprising. Objectively, Black should have prepared this pawn advance with ...Rhg8, but hey White must have been sweating seeing Black sacrifice a second pawn! }
12. Nxg5 { is essentially forced. White cannot allow ...g5-g4 on the board. }
12... Qg6 13. Qf3
{ is inaccurate, allowing Black to generate a big initiative with 13...Bb4!   Retreating with  13.Nf3!  was far superior. After  13...Rhg8  14.Nh4  Qg7  While Black seems to have a dangerous initiative on the kingside, objectively White is much better here. For example:  15.Rad1  getting ready to break with d5.  15...Ne7  16.Qf3+-  with ideas of c5 and d5 is very strong. }
13... Bb4 14. Rfd1
{ is a blunder that costs White the game. Black's enterprising play is rewarded.   Better was  14.Nce4!  Be7!  15.Nxf6  Bxf6  when Black would still have had excellent compensation. }
14... Bxc3 15. bxc3 h6 { All of a sudden, White's knight has no squares. } 16.
d5 { Doesn't help as Black can simply jump forward with } 16... Ne5 17. Qe2
hxg5 18. Bxa7 { This pawn is completely irrelevant. } 18... Qf5 19. Rab1 Ne4
{ is both natural and strong. Black had an even stronger option at his disposal.   19...Rxh3!!  would have been a magnificent way to seal the deal.  20.gxh3  Rh8!  Black's attack is unstoppable. }
20. Bd4 g4 { Blasts open the h-file. White's king is toast! } 21. Qb2
{ was White's only threat in the entire game. Black easily stopped it with }
21... b6 22. Qa3 gxh3 23. Bxb6
{ Desperation.   23.Qa8+  is only a check. After  23...Kd7-+  White has no follow-up. }
23... Nf3+ { Boom goes the dynamite! } 24. Kf1
{ After  24.gxf3  White gets mated by force with  24...h2+  25.Kg2  Qh3+  26.Kh1  Qxf3 }
24... hxg2+ 25. Ke2 Ng3+
{ Black throws yet another knight at White's king. He's only getting started... }
26. fxg3 Qe4+ 27. Be3 g1=N+
{ And he's back! The knight comes back from the dead with decisive effect. }
28. Kf1
{ White could have resigned but decided to sportingly allow the following fitting finale }
28... Qxc4+ 29. Kg2 Rh2#
{ What an explosive outing of 3...Bg4 by IM Rui Damaso, the first of many amazing victories to come. He didn't have to wait long as 4 rounds later he got a chance to play it again. Head on over to the next game to see how he fared!   0-1 @@StartBracket@@29@@EndBracket@@ Ye,J  @@StartBracket@@2560@@EndBracket@@-Damaso,R @@StartBracket@@2415@@EndBracket@@ Macau 1996 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Bonus: 2...Nf6 Scandi | Portuguese Gambit & Others"]
[Black "Inspirational game #2: 0-1 Wang,Z (2540)-Damaso,R (2415) Macau 1996"]
[Result "*"]

{ The following is a game from the same 1996 China-Portugal team match. As GM David Smerdon details in his book, the legend goes that following Damaso's stunning tactical victory over Ye Jiangchuan, the Chinese team spent the next three days trying to refute the outrageous 3...Bg4 gambit. Their approach was that the way to punish this unprincipled gambit was to take all of Black's material and hold onto it.   Round 7 comes and after all that preparation, GM Wang Zhao essayed 1. e4 and IM Damaso repeats 3...Bg4. Now let's see how all that preparation the Chinese team turned out: }
1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6 3. d4 Bg4 4. f3 Bf5 5. c4
{ This was the concept the Chinese team came up with: hold onto the extra pawn. }
5... e6 { Damaso decides to immediately undermine White's center. } 6. dxe6
{ gives Black exactly the sort of play he was looking for.   6.Nc3  exd5  7.g4  is far more challenging. }
6... Nc6
{ A remarkable concept: there's no need to capture the e6 pawn as White is under no position to open the e-file towards his king. }
7. Be3 Bb4+
{ 7...Nb4  is more precise and my recommendation in the theory section. } 8.
Nc3
{ 8.Nd2  was a better square for the knight.  8...Qe7  9.a3  Ba5  10.b4  O-O-O  with excellent compensation. White's position is hard to handle. }
8... Qe7
{ Once again, Black could care less about the e6 pawn. He instead lines up his queen against White's king and clears the way for ...O-O-O. }
9. d5
{ is a mistake.   White should have stepped out of the d-file with  9.Qc1  which also covers the e3 bishop. }
9... O-O-O
{ Black completes development bringing the rook into the game. The knight on c6 is untouchable due to the pin along the d-file. White is way behind in development and already in big trouble. }
10. Qa4
{ In a difficult position, White blunders the following stunning tactical shot }
10... Nxd5 { Crash, bang, wallop! White's position now collapses. } 11. cxd5
Qh4+ 12. Kd1
{ 12.g3  loses the queen to  12...Bxc3+  13.bxc3  Qxa4-+   12.Ke2  is also no good on account of the beautiful  12...Nd4+!!  13.Bxd4  Qxd4  14.Rd1  Qe5+  15.Ne4  Bxe4  16.Qxb4  Bc2+-+ }
12... Rxd5+
{ White was dead lost and likely so impressed with Black's play that he sportingly played }
13. Nxd5 Qe1#
{ Checkmate - a fitting finale to this marvelous miniature!   Turns out that all that preparation resulted in GM Wang being checkmated in 13 moves, an even worse fate than his colleague GM Ye Jianchuan suffered 4 rounds earlier. These two games brought 3...Bg4 into the limelight and IM Damaso collected several more GM scalps throughout the years. He continues to play the Portuguese Gambit to this very day.   0-1 @@StartBracket@@13@@EndBracket@@ Wang,Z @@StartBracket@@2540@@EndBracket@@-Damaso,R @@StartBracket@@2415@@EndBracket@@ Macau 1996 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Bonus: 2...Nf6 Scandi | Portuguese Gambit & Others"]
[Black "Inspirational game #3: 0-1 Vaibhav,S (2542)-Carlsen,M (2834) 2018"]
[Result "*"]

{ Jumping forward more than two decades since Damaso's stunning victories, the current World-Champion Magnus Carlsen essayed the Portuguese Gambit against GM Suri Vaibhav in the 2018 Pro Chess League. }
1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6 3. d4 Bg4
{ Carlsen unleashes the Portuguese Gambit. As we're about to see, White was completely unprepared to meet it! }
4. f3 Bf5 5. c4 { White decides to try and hold onto to his extra pawn. } 5...
e6 { Black immediately undermines White's center, the point being that } 6.
dxe6 { is strongly met by } 6... Nc6
{ which is a recurring theme in the Portuguese Gambit. Black maximizes his lead in development, welcoming }
7. exf7+
{ 7.Be3  is a better move when  7...Nb4  8.Na3  c5  gives Black good play. }
7... Kxf7
{ The e-file is now open, making White's king on e1 very uncomfortable. Let's take stock: Black is two pawns down but has developed three minor pieces and is putting firm pressure on White's d4 pawn. Conversely, White has yet to develop a single piece. }
8. Be3
{ is a blunder that White never recovered from.   8.Ne2  was necessary although White is still not in the clear after  8...Nb4  threatening to jump into both d3 and c2. }
8... Bb4+ { Black clears the way for ...Re8 with tempo. } 9. Kf2 Re8
{ Black brings another piece into the game and now has 5 pieces in the attack. }
10. Nc3 Rxe3
{ Boom goes the dynamite! Black lures White's king out into the open. } 11.
Kxe3 Nxd4
{ is a strong move, but Black had an even stronger option at his disposal.   The stunning  11...Bc2!!  is Black's strongest option. The bishop is untouchable as  12.Qxc2  Qxd4+  13.Ke2  Re8+  leads to checkmate. }
12. Kf2
{ The knight on d4 is taboo as   12.Qxd4  runs into  12...Qe7+  13.Kd2   13.Kf2  Bc5-+  wins White's queen.   13.Kf4  loses on the spot to  13...Nh5+  14.Kxf5  Qe6+  15.Kg5  Be7+  16.Kxh5  Qf5  Rd8  14.Qxd8  Qxd8+  15.Ke1  Qd4-+  Black has an overwhelming position. }
12... Bc5
{ This retreating move threatens several deadly discoveries with the knight. White tried to go after Black's bishop with }
13. Na4 Bc2
{ Forks the queen and the knight.   13...Nc2+  was also winning.  14.Nxc5  Qe7  15.Ne4  Bxe4  16.fxe4  Qc5+-+ }
14. Nxc5 Bxd1 15. Rxd1 Qe7
{ Needless to say, White has nowhere near enough for the queen. Carlsen easily converted his advantage into a full point. }
16. b4 { 16.Nxb7  Re8-+  with the threat of ...Qe3+ is decisive. } 16... Re8
17. Bd3 { The knight cannot be taken since   17.Rxd4  Qe1  is checkmate! }
17... Qe3+ 18. Kf1 b6
{ 18...Ng4!  would have won on the spot.  19.fxg4  Qf4+  20.Nf3  Nxf3  21.gxf3  Qxf3+-+ }
19. Ne4 Nxe4 20. Bxe4 { Carlsen kept it simple with } 20... c5
{ 20...Rxe4!  was decisive.  21.fxe4  Qf4+-+ } 21. bxc5 Rxe4 22. fxe4 Qf4+ 23.
Ke1 Qxe4+ 24. Kf2 Qc2+ 25. Ke1 bxc5
{ is a classy finish. There's no defense against ...Qxg2, which prompted resignation.   A very nice miniature by the World-Champion. White was not prepared for the Portuguese Gambit and was dead lost 8 moves into the game!  0-1 @@StartBracket@@25@@EndBracket@@ Vaibhav,S @@StartBracket@@2542@@EndBracket@@-Carlsen,M @@StartBracket@@2834@@EndBracket@@ PRO Chess League INT 2018 }
*

