1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6
{ The 2...Nf6 Scandinavian is objectively dubious, but a good blitz and rapid weapon nonetheless. White has to be quite precise in order to get an advantage with Black having a whole array of devious tricks and traps at his disposal. }
3. Nc3 { is frequently seen at the amateur level and is completely harmless. }
3... Nxd5 { Black recoups the pawn without any concessions. } 4. Nxd5
{ only helps Black centralize his queen with 4...Qxd5.   4.Nf3  Nxc3  5.bxc3  g6  6.d4  Bg7=  followed by ...O-O and ...c5 is very comfortable. }
4... Qxd5 5. Nf3
{ This is a more favorable version of the3. Nf3 variation of the 2...Qxd5 Scandinavian for Black having already exchanged a pair of knights. In particular, White can no longer harass our queen with Nc3.   5.Qf3  is simply met with  5...Be6  6.d4  Nc6  7.c3  O-O-O= }
5... Bg4 6. Be2 Nc6
{ is the best square for the knight, controlling the key d4 square. } 7. d4
O-O-O
{ Lines up the rook against White's d4 pawn, which Black can further undermine with ...e5 on the next turn. }
8. c3 e5 9. dxe5 Qe4 { Unleashes a discovered attack on White's queen. } 10.
Bd2 Nxe5 { White is completely pinned down and already dead lost. } *

