1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6
{ The 2...Nf6 Scandinavian is objectively dubious, but a good blitz and rapid weapon nonetheless. White has to be quite precise in order to get an advantage with Black having a whole array of devious tricks and traps at his disposal. }
3. Nc3 { is frequently seen at the amateur level and is completely harmless. }
3... Nxd5 { Black recoups the pawn without any concessions. } 4. Nf3
{ In these situations, the best course of action is to develop our pieces actively and take up as much space as possible. }
4... Bg4
{ The bishop is most active on g4.   There are several good alternatives in  4...g6  and  4...Bf5 }
5. Be2 { Neutralizing the pin is White's most common continuation. } 5... e6 6.
h3
{ 6.O-O  allows Black to jump in with  6...Nf4  to grab the bishop pair. Following  7.d4  Nxe2  8.Qxe2  Nc6=  Black is in great shape with ...Bd6 and ...O-O coming next. }
6... Bh5 7. O-O Nxc3
{ There are other options but this is the simplest, compromising White's queenside pawn structure. Black will simply complete development with ...Bd6, ...O-O, and ...Nd7 and enjoy a good game. }
8. bxc3 Bd6 9. d4 O-O 10. Re1 Nd7
{ Black has no problems whatsoever and can look to engineer the ...c5 break. }
