1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6
{ The 2...Nf6 Scandinavian is objectively dubious, but a good blitz and rapid weapon nonetheless. White has to be quite precise in order to get an advantage with Black having a whole array of devious tricks and traps at his disposal. }
3. Bc4
{ is a natural square for the bishop. However, simply allowing Black to retake the pawn cannot pose any problems. }
3... Nxd5 4. Nf3 Bg4
{ is the usual square for our light-squared bishop. It's particularly strong here that White already spent a tempo Bc4, meaning the pin can't simply be broken with Be2. }
5. O-O e6 6. h3
{ 6.d4  can be met with  6...Be7  7.c3  O-O  8.Nbd2  Nd7=  Black is very comfortable with ideas of ...Nb6 and ...c5. }
6... Bh5 7. d4 Be7 8. Be2
{ The bishop wasn't doing much on c4 so White retreats it to break the pin and clear the way for c2-c4. }
8... O-O 9. c4
{ Alternatively  9.Ne5  is answered by  9...Bxe2  10.Qxe2  Nd7=  intending to exchange off the knight on e5 and later break with ...c5. }
9... Nb6 10. Be3 Nc6
{ Black is now threatening to win a pawn with @@StartBracket@@or at the very least spoil White's structure@@EndBracket@@with  11.--  Bxf3  12.Bxf3  Nxc4 }
11. Nbd2 f5
{ Gains space on the kingside with the obvious threat of ...f4 to trap White's bishop. ...Bf6 to attack the d4 pawn is also on the agenda with a good game. White's pawn center is more of a target than an asset. }
