1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6
{ The 2...Nf6 Scandinavian is objectively dubious, but a good blitz and rapid weapon nonetheless. White has to be quite precise in order to get an advantage with Black having a whole array of devious tricks and traps at his disposal. }
3. Bb5+ { is a good move, disrupting Black's natural development. } 3... Nbd7
4. Nc3
{ is harmless. First, the bishop is pushed back with 4...a6.   4.Nf3  is also possible. After  4...Nxd5  5.d4  e6  This move was not covered in the Chessable course Keep it Simple 1.e4 by IM Christof Sielecki or in the database Complete Repertoire against the Alekhine and Scandinavian by GM Zahar Efimenko. However, it is not a clean equalizer. White can keep a small but pleasant edge with  6.O-O  Be7  7.c4  N5f6  8.Nc3  O-O⩲  While White is objectively slightly better due to his superior control over the center, Black is very solid. }
4... a6 5. Be2 { And now } 5... b5
{ followed by ...Bb7 will ensure Black picks up the d5 pawn sooner rather than later. }
6. Nf3 Bb7 7. O-O g6
{ Black will first develop his kingside before capturing the d5 pawn. It certainly isn't going anywhere so there's no rush in regaining it immediately. }
8. d4 Bg7 9. Re1 O-O 10. Bf1 Nxd5
{ Restores material equality with excellent prospects. } *

