1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6
{ The 2...Nf6 Scandinavian is objectively dubious, but a good blitz and rapid weapon nonetheless. White has to be quite precise in order to get an advantage with Black having a whole array of devious tricks and traps at his disposal. }
3. Bb5+ { is a good move, disrupting Black's natural development. } 3... Nbd7
4. c4 a6 { Puts the question to the bishop. } 5. Bxd7+ Qxd7
{ Black recaptures with the queen to have the option of playing ...Qg4 next. }
6. d3
{ 6.d4  can be undermined with  6...e6  After  7.dxe6  Qxe6  8.Qe2  b5  9.c5  Bb7=  gives Black a good game. }
6... e6
{ Immediately undermining the d5 pawn is the most incisive approach.   The simpler  6...Qg4  heading for an endgame is given as analternative recommendation. }
7. dxe6 Qxe6+ 8. Qe2
{ White forces the queens off the board hoping to make the extra pawn count in the ensuing endgame. }
8... Bb4+
{ Not happening! White doesn't have enough time to consolidate the extra material. }
9. Nc3 Qxe2+ 10. Kxe2
{ Alternatively  10.Ngxe2  is strongly met by  10...Bf5  forcing the pawn forward.  11.d4  O-O-O  12.Be3  Rhe8  13.O-O-O  Ng4=  with huge pressure on White's position. The first player needs to tread carefully to maintain the balance. }
10... Bf5 11. Nf3 O-O-O
{ The d3 pawn is under fire and White's king on e2 is very uncomfortable. Black will restore material equality in no time. }
