1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6
{ The 2...Nf6 Scandinavian is objectively dubious, but a good blitz and rapid weapon nonetheless. White has to be quite precise in order to get an advantage with Black having a whole array of devious tricks and traps at his disposal. }
3. Bb5+ { is a good move, disrupting Black's natural development. } 3... Nbd7
4. c4 a6 { Puts the question to the bishop. } 5. Ba4
{ is surprisingly White's most popular move. I say surprisingly because Black gets very easy play after }
5... b5
{ A very powerful break, deflecting the c4 pawn from the protection of the one on d5. }
6. cxb5 { 6.Bb3?  bxc4  7.Bxc4  Nb6=+  is already better for Black } 6... Nxd5
{  } 7. bxa6 Bxa6
{ Let's take stock. Black has a monster bishop on a6, raking down the a6-f1 diagonal, a strong knight on d5 and two semi-open files on the queenside - all for just one pawn! That's a bargain in my book. }
8. Ne2
{ White must block our bishop in order to castle.   8.Nf3??  blunders  8...Nf4-+  threatening to the end the game at once with ...Nxg2#, not to mention  ...Nd3+. 8 moves into the game and White is already dead lost. }
8... Nb4 { 8...Bxe2  9.Kxe2  e6  is good too } 9. O-O Bxe2
{ Initiates a forced series of exchanges, leading to a balanced endgame after }
10. Bxd7+ Qxd7 11. Qxe2 Qd3 12. Qxd3 Nxd3 13. Nc3 g6
{ White's queenside is paralyzed granting Black full and long-lasting compensation for the pawn deficit. Coming up are ...Bg7, ... f5, ...Kf7 and ...Rhb8 with strong queenside pressure. If White isn't careful, Black can even take over. }
