1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6
{ The 2...Nf6 Scandinavian is objectively dubious, but a good blitz and rapid weapon nonetheless. White has to be quite precise in order to get an advantage with Black having a whole array of devious tricks and traps at his disposal. }
3. Bb5+ { is a good move, disrupting Black's natural development. } 3... Nbd7
4. c4 a6 { Puts the question to the bishop. } 5. Ba4
{ is surprisingly White's most popular move. Surprisingly because Black gets very easy play after }
5... b5
{ A very powerful break, deflecting the c4 pawn from the protection of the one on d5. }
6. cxb5 Nxd5 7. Nf3 N5b6
{ Once again, dropping back the knight works wonders. The bishop is chased away from the defense of the b5 pawn, allowing us to recoup the pawn. }
8. Bc2
{ White must preserve the light-squared bishop as otherwise Black's bishop on c8 would become an unopposed, menacing force along the a8-h1 diagonal. }
8... axb5 9. Be4
{ White's bishop looks active on e4 but it'll soon be chased back with ...Nf6. }
9... Ra6 10. d4 Nf6 11. Bd3 c6
{ secures the d5 outpost for our knights. Black will bring out his pieces with ...g6, ...Bg7, ...O-O and ...Be6/g4 with excellent prospects. White has been left with an isolated pawn on d4, which is a big target. }
