1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6
{ The 2...Nf6 Scandinavian is objectively dubious, but a good blitz and rapid weapon nonetheless. White has to be quite precise in order to get an advantage with Black having a whole array of devious tricks and traps at his disposal. }
3. Nf3
{ is a simple yet effective approach. White decides against immediately occupying the center and prefers to instead develop his kingside first. }
3... Bg4
{ Black wants to capture the d5 pawn with the queen, when he'd be ready to meet c2-c4 with the intermezzo ...Bxf3. }
4. Bb5+
{ White disrupts Black's plan with this check, which forces us to interpose a piece on d7 thus stopping ...Qxd5.   4.Be2  Qxd5  5.d4  is covered via the 3. d4 Bg4 4. Nf3 Qxd5 5. Be2 move order. }
4... Nbd7 5. h3 Bh5 6. Nc3 a6
{ Black needs to get rid of White's bishop to go after the d5 pawn with ...Nb6. }
7. Be2
{ 7.Ba4  runs into  7...b5  8.Bb3  Nc5=  when Black can eliminate the b3 bishop at any moment when the d5 pawn will then drop. Black had no problems in 0-1 @@StartBracket@@27@@EndBracket@@ Golubev,M @@StartBracket@@2461@@EndBracket@@-Gukesh,D @@StartBracket@@2563@@EndBracket@@ Chess. com INT 2020. }
7... Nb6 8. d4 Nfxd5
{ It's important to take on d5 with this knight as the alternative   8...Nbxd5?  runs into  9.Nxd5  Nxd5  10.c4±  Keeping the knight on b6 stops White from getting in c4. }
9. Nxd5 Qxd5
{ In the Chessable course Lifetime Repertoires: Wesley So's 1.e4 and in the book Kaufman's New Repertoire for Black and White: A Complete, Sound and User-Friendly Chess Opening Repertoire, GMs Wesley So and  Larry Kaufman only considered the inferior   9...Nxd5  It's stronger to capture the d5 pawn with the queen, which is very active in the center of the board and slows down White's c2-c4 central expansion. }
10. O-O e6
{ As pointed out by IM Andrew Greet in the book Beating Unusual Chess Defences: 1 e4: Dealing with the Scandinavian, Pirc, Modern, Alekhine and other tricky lines, White has the upper hand here with the plan of expanding in the center with b2-b3 and c2-c4.  Black's position is nevertheless fully playable. He can complete development with ...Be7, ...O-O and can then look to target the d4 pawn with ...Rd8. }
