1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6
{ The 2...Nf6 Scandinavian is objectively dubious, but a good blitz and rapid weapon nonetheless. White has to be quite precise in order to get an advantage with Black having a whole array of devious tricks and traps at his disposal. }
3. d4 { is White's most popular move. } 3... Bg4
{ is known as the Portuguese Gambit, also called the Jadoul Gambit. It was first introduced into master play by Carl Göring. Black wants to provoke the weakening move f3, which would take away the most natural square for White's g1 knight. We'll generally meet c2-c4 with ...e7-e6 to blast open the center and attack White down the central e and d-files. }
4. Be2 { is too cooperative. } 4... Bxe2 5. Qxe2
{ Also possible is  5.Nxe2  which doesn't alter Black's plan.  5...Qxd5  6.O-O  Nc6  7.Be3  e6  8.Nd2  Bd6  9.c4  Qf5=  gives Black good play. }
5... Qxd5
{ Black was able to recapture on d5 with the queen, which typically means he is absolutely fine. This is no exception, Black is indeed doing very well with good play against White's d4 pawn based on ...Nc6 and ... O-O-O. }
6. Nf3 e6 7. O-O
{ 7.Nc3  Qa5  8.Bg5  Nbd7  9.O-O  Be7=  is absolutely fine for Black.   7.Bf4  is well met by the simple  7...Bd6= }
7... Nc6 8. Rd1 { 8.c4?  runs into the intermezzo  8...Nxd4!  Oops... } 8...
Qf5
{ is a good prophylactic move, stepping out of c2-c4 followed by d4-d5.   This move was not considered in the book Chess Openings for White, Explained by GMs Lev Alburt, Roman Dzindzichashvil, and Eugene Perelshteyn. }
9. c4 O-O-O
{ The kings are castled on opposite wings and the race is on! With ...Rg8 and ...g5-g4 coming very fast, I see no reason for Black to be any worse.   A sample continuation is  10.Nc3  Be7  11.Be3  Rhg8  12.b4  Bxb4  13.Qb2  Bxc3  14.Qxc3  g5⭢ }
*

