1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6
{ The 2...Nf6 Scandinavian is objectively dubious, but a good blitz and rapid weapon nonetheless. White has to be quite precise in order to get an advantage with Black having a whole array of devious tricks and traps at his disposal. }
3. d4 { is White's most popular move. } 3... Bg4
{ is known as the Portuguese Gambit, also called the Jadoul Gambit. It was first introduced into master play by Carl Göring. Black wants to provoke the weakening move f3, which would take away the most natural square for White's g1 knight. We'll generally meet c2-c4 with ...e7-e6 to blast open the center and attack White down the central e and d-files. }
4. Nf3 Qxd5
{ As usual, when Black is allowed to take on d5 with the queen undisturbed, he's got little to worry about. The point is Black can quickly target the d4 pawn with ...Nc6 and ...O-O-O. }
5. Be2 { Breaking the pin is more sensible than 5. Nc3. } 5... Nc6
{ It's important to note that we are NOT threatening  6.--  Bxf3  7.Bxf3  Qxd4??  due to the intermezzo  8.Bxc6+−  winning our queen.  Instead, we clear the way for ...O-O-O to attack the d4 pawn. }
6. h3 { forces Black to play } 6... Bxf3
{ Watch out: do not go for the at first sight tempting  6...Qh5  which doesn't work due to  7.O-O  O-O-O  8.hxg4  Nxg4  9.Bf4!+−  when Black has no attack whatsoever and is just lost. }
7. Bxf3 Qd7
{ Watch out:  7...Qxd4??  blunders the queen to the in-between move  8.Bxc6!  bxc6  9.Qxd4+− }
8. c3 e5
{ It's important to play this move first instead of  8...O-O-O  due to  9.Qb3! }
9. O-O
{ 9.dxe5  is too cooperative. After  9...Qxd1  10.Kxd1  O-O-O  11.Kc2  Nxe5=  The lead development easily offsets White's bishop pair advantage. After White retreats the bishop, Black can quickly complete development with ...Bc5 and ...Rhe8. Black is in great shape.   Finally  9.d5  is well met by  9...Ne7  10.c4  Ng6  11.O-O  Bc5=  followed by ...O-O with excellent prospects. Black has a greatly improved version of the Two Knights Tango or the Mexican Defence. After castling, the second player can look forward to generating an attack with...Qf5 and ...Nh4. }
9... O-O-O
{ White's bishop pair is offset by Black's strong pressure on the d4 pawn. } *

