4. Nf3 Qxd5
{ As usual, when Black is allowed to take on d5 with the queen undisturbed, he's got little to worry about. The point is Black can quickly target the d4 pawn with ...Nc6 and ...O-O-O. }
5. Be2 { Breaking the pin is more sensible than 5. Nc3. } 5... Nc6 6. O-O
{ 6.Be3  has also been tried. Black can continue with  6...e5  7.Nc3  Bb4  8.O-O  Bxc3  9.bxc3  O-O  N  improves over the game 1-0 @@StartBracket@@31@@EndBracket@@ Kolev,A @@StartBracket@@2568@@EndBracket@@-Damaso,R @@StartBracket@@2412@@EndBracket@@ Skopje 2002. After  10.c4  Qd6  11.c3  Rfe8=  Black has an excellent game. White has no chance of being better with doubled c-pawns. }
6... O-O-O 7. c4 Qh5 8. h3
{ is a common mistake in practice.   8.Be3  is strongly met by  8...e5!  ∓  Black had a clear advantage, going on to win in 0-1 @@StartBracket@@45@@EndBracket@@ Hou,Y @@StartBracket@@2629@@EndBracket@@-Muzychuk,A @@StartBracket@@2566@@EndBracket@@ Beijing 2013.   8.d5  is also no good due to  8...e6! }
8... Nxd4 { Hello! This beautiful shot is almost decisive. } 9. hxg4
{ White should play  9.Nxd4  when  9...Bxe2  10.Qxe2  Rxd4∓  leaves Black a healthy pawn up. }
9... Nxg4
{ The knight on d4 is untouchable due to ...Qh2#. White is busted as there's no good way of meeting the threat of ...Nxf3+, either eliminating the knight in order to deliver checkmate on h2 or picking up White's queen on d1. }
