1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6
{ The 2...Nf6 Scandinavian is objectively dubious, but a good blitz and rapid weapon nonetheless. White has to be quite precise in order to get an advantage with Black having a whole array of devious tricks and traps at his disposal. }
3. d4 { is White's most popular move. } 3... Bg4
{ is known as the Portuguese Gambit, also called the Jadoul Gambit. It was first introduced into master play by Carl Göring. Black wants to provoke the weakening move f3, which would take away the most natural square for White's g1 knight. We'll generally meet c2-c4 with ...e7-e6 to blast open the center and attack White down the central e and d-files. }
4. Nf3 Qxd5
{ As usual, when Black is allowed to take on d5 with the queen undisturbed, he's got little to worry about. The point is Black can quickly target the d4 pawn with ...Nc6 and ...O-O-O. }
5. Be2 { Breaking the pin is more sensible than 5. Nc3. } 5... Nc6 6. O-O
{ 6.Be3  has also been tried. Black can continue with  6...e5  7.Nc3  Bb4  8.O-O  Bxc3  9.bxc3  O-O  N  improves over the game 1-0 @@StartBracket@@31@@EndBracket@@ Kolev,A @@StartBracket@@2568@@EndBracket@@-Damaso,R @@StartBracket@@2412@@EndBracket@@ Skopje 2002. After  10.c4  Qd6  11.c3  Rfe8=  Black has an excellent game. White has no chance of being better with doubled c-pawns. }
6... O-O-O 7. Be3 { is White's most solid approach. } 7... Qf5
{ Black steps out of c2-c4 is now ready to break in the center with ...e5. The queen is better placed on f5, from where it supports ...Nb4-c2 in certain variations, than on h5. Moreover, keeping the h5 square unoccupied allows Black to expand on the kingside with ...h5. }
8. c4 e5 9. d5 e4
{ is a nice counterblow. The knight on c6 is untouchable due to the pin along the d-file. }
10. Nd4
{ Worse is  10.Nfd2  Ne5  11.Nc3  a6=  when Black is very comfortable. } 10...
Nxd4 11. Bxd4 h5
{ Maintains the bishop on g4. This move was not considered in Beating Unusual Chess Defences: 1 e4: Dealing with the Scandinavian, Pirc, Modern, Alekhine and other tricky lines by IM Andrew Greet. }
12. Nc3 c5
{ holds White's center at bay. Black has good prospects on the kingside with ideas of ...Bd6 and ...Qe5.   Note that  13.dxc6  is strongly met by  13...Bc5!  14.Qb3  bxc6  15.Bxc5  Qxc5  with good prospects. For example  16.Rad1  Rxd1  17.Rxd1  Bxe2  18.Nxe2  Ng4=  And now the attack on the f2 pawn forces White on the defensive. Black's king is safer than it looks at first sight, while the White monarch can find itself under attack after ...e3 later on. The position is dynamically balanced. }
