1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6
{ The 2...Nf6 Scandinavian is objectively dubious, but a good blitz and rapid weapon nonetheless. White has to be quite precise in order to get an advantage with Black having a whole array of devious tricks and traps at his disposal. }
3. d4 { is White's most popular move. } 3... Bg4
{ is known as the Portuguese Gambit, also called the Jadoul Gambit. It was first introduced into master play by Carl Göring. Black wants to provoke the weakening move f3, which would take away the most natural square for White's g1 knight. We'll generally meet c2-c4 with ...e7-e6 to blast open the center and attack White down the central e and d-files. }
4. f3 Bf5 5. c4 e6 { Here we go, Black's about to have a lot of fun! } 6. Qb3
{ is also a mistake. } 6... exd5
{ White is more than welcome to capture the b7 pawn. } 7. Qxb7 Nbd7
{ For a mere pawn, Black already has three pieces in the game. Conversely, all of White's pieces bar his queen occupy the starting squares. }
8. c5 Bxc5
{ Boom! Black clears the back rank for ...O-O and a fast ...Re8. White is far too undeveloped to deal with this. }
9. dxc5 Rb8 10. Qxa7 O-O
{ Coming next are ...Re8 and/ or ...Qe7 with a huge lead in development. Almost all of our pieces are already in the game, while White's forces are still snoozing on the back rank. White is in big trouble. }
