3. d4 { is White's most popular move. } 3... Bg4
{ is known as the Portuguese Gambit, also called the Jadoul Gambit. It was first introduced into master play by Carl Göring. Black wants to provoke the weakening move f3, which would take away the most natural square for White's g1 knight. We'll generally meet c2-c4 with ...e7-e6 to blast open the center and attack White down the central e and d-files. }
4. f3 Bf5 5. c4 e6 { Here we go, Black's about to have a lot of fun! } 6. dxe6
Nc6
{ White is more than welcome to take on f7 and open the e-file for our pieces! }
7. exf7+
{ 7.Be3  allows  7...Nb4  The deadly threat of ...Nc2+ forces  8.Na3  when  8...fxe6  9.Be2  c5=  gives Black good play. }
7... Kxf7 8. Be3
{ is White's most popular time. Despite being 5 times more common than the alternatives, White is already losing after this move!   8.Ne2  is White's best choice although he's still not in the clear after  8...Nb4=  which threatens to jump into d3 and c2.   8.d5??  isn't any better. After  8...Nb4  9.Na3  Bc5  White is in big trouble with ...Re8+ coming next. For example  10.Be2  Re8  11.Kf1  Nh5  12.g4  Rxe2  13.Qxe2  Bd3-+  pins and wins. White can resign. }
8... Bb4+ 9. Kf2 { White steps out of the e-file but it's a little too late! }
9... Re8 10. a3 Rxe3
{ Boom goes the dynamite! Black eliminates White's only developed piece and lures White's king out into the open. }
11. Kxe3
{ 11.axb4  runs into  11...Rd3!  A beautiful move that interferes with the queen's protection of the d4 pawn. Following  12.Bxd3  Qxd4+  13.Kf1  Bxd3+  14.Ne2  Re8  15.Nbc3  Qe3+−  The e2 knight will drop with ...Nd4 coming next. White is busted. }
11... Be1
{ is a stunning move that spells the end for White. His king cannot retreat and definitely won't survive out in the open!   The bishop is untouchable as  12.Qxe1  Qxd4+  13.Ke2  Re8  is checkmate!   Another good option is  11...Bc2!  which wins White's queen. }
