1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6
{ The 2...Nf6 Scandinavian is objectively dubious, but a good blitz and rapid weapon nonetheless. White has to be quite precise in order to get an advantage with Black having a whole array of devious tricks and traps at his disposal. }
3. d4 { is White's most popular move. } 3... Bg4
{ is known as the Portuguese Gambit, also called the Jadoul Gambit. It was first introduced into master play by Carl Göring. Black wants to provoke the weakening move f3, which would take away the most natural square for White's g1 knight. We'll generally meet c2-c4 with ...e7-e6 to blast open the center and attack White down the central e and d-files. }
4. f3 Bf5 5. Bb5+ Nbd7
{ Black blocks the check and is now threatening to win back the pawn with ...Nxd5. }
6. c4 { is yet another way of trying to keep hold of the d5 pawn. } 6... e6
{ As usual, Black does best in immediately undermining White's center. } 7.
dxe6
{ 7.g4  fails to yield anything significant after  7...Bg6  8.dxe6  fxe6  9.Ne2  c6  10.Ba4  Now  10...Nxg4!  gives Black the initiative. }
7... Bxe6
{ Black is now threatening ...c6, kicking the bishop away, followed by ...Bxc4. This effectively forces }
8. d5
{ Simple development with  8.Nc3  runs into  8...c6  9.d5  Bxd5  10.cxd5  cxb5=  when White's d5 pawn is now isolated and a big target.   8.Qe2?  is a big mistake due to  8...c6  9.Ba4  Qa5!  10.Nc3  Bb4  when White has no good way of dealing with the threats of ...Bxc3+ and ...Qxa4. For example  11.Qc2  Bxc3  12.bxc3  O-O-O−+  when there's no way White is surviving this. }
8... Bf5 9. Nc3 Bc5
{ Black could also have developed his bishop to b4. I prefer to post it on c5, which makes it hard for White to castle kingside. }
10. Qe2+ { If you're feeling adventurous, you can roll the dice with } 10...
Kf8
{ with the creative idea of playing ...Kg8, ...Qf8, and ...Re8!   Objectively speaking, Black should head for an endgame with  10...Qe7  , which is given as analternative recommendation. }
11. g4 { is exactly the sort of mistake Black is hoping for! } 11... Nxg4
{ Sacrifices on g4 and the Portuguese Gambit, name a more iconic duo! } 12.
fxg4 Qh4+ { The only game in my database continued } 13. Kd1
{ Oops, this is not the right square for the king.   13.Kd2  is the only way to stay in the game. After  13...Bxg4  14.Nf3  Qh6  15.Kc2  Qg6  16.Kb3  c6=  Black has full compensation and the initiative to boot with ...Re8 on the agenda. White's king is certainly not happy with its current position! }
13... Bxg4
{ 13 moves into the game and Black was already winning in 0-1  (37)  Goh,W  (2403)  -Laylo,D  (2504)  Manila 2008.   For example  14.Nf3  Qh5  15.Rf1  Ne5−+  is lights out. }
