1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6
{ The 2...Nf6 Scandinavian is objectively dubious, but a good blitz and rapid weapon nonetheless. White has to be quite precise in order to get an advantage with Black having a whole array of devious tricks and traps at his disposal. }
3. d4 { is White's most popular move. } 3... Bg4
{ is known as the Portuguese Gambit, also called the Jadoul Gambit. It was first introduced into master play by Carl Göring. Black wants to provoke the weakening move f3, which would take away the most natural square for White's g1 knight. We'll generally meet c2-c4 with ...e7-e6 to blast open the center and attack White down the central e and d-files. }
4. f3 Bf5 5. Bb5+ Nbd7
{ Apart from  6.c4  ,  White can also choose to reinforce the d5 pawn with } 6.
Nc3 a6 7. Ba4 b5 8. Bb3 Nb6 9. Nge2
{ 9.g4  can simply be met with  9...Bc8  followed by .. Bb7 which will recoup the d5 pawn. }
9... a5
{ is Black's most aggressive option, threatening to trap White's light-squared bishop with a4.  This move was not considered by GM John Shaw in the book Playing 1.e4. Caro-Kann, 1...e5 and Minor Lines nor in the Chessable course 1.e4: A Comprehensive White Repertoire by NM Elijah Logozar. }
10. Ng3 Bc8 11. a3
{ 11.a4  can simply be bypassed with  11...b4  12.Nce4  Nfxd5  13.O-O  g6+=  Black can complete development with ...Bg7 and ...O-O. There's not really much he should be worried about here. }
11... a4 12. Ba2 Nfxd5 13. Nxb5 Ba6
{ Black has sacrificed one pawn to ensure White's king stays in the center. }
14. c4 c6 15. cxd5 Bxb5 16. dxc6 e6
{ The machine naturally gives White a significant edge here due to the extra material. In a practical game, Black has very decent chances with ...Bd6 and ...O-O coming next. Importantly, White's king is stuck in the center. }
