[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Bonus: 2...Nf6 Scandi | Portuguese Gambit & Others"]
[Black "3.d4 4. f3 5. g4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6
{ The 2...Nf6 Scandinavian is objectively dubious, but a good blitz and rapid weapon nonetheless. White has to be quite precise in order to get an advantage with Black having a whole array of devious tricks and traps at his disposal. }
3. d4 { is White's most popular move. } 3... Bg4
{ is known as the Portuguese Gambit, also called the Jadoul Gambit. It was first introduced into master play by Carl Göring. Black wants to provoke the weakening move f3, which would take away the most natural square for White's g1 knight. We'll generally meet c2-c4 with ...e7-e6 to blast open the center and attack White down the central e and d-files. }
4. f3 Bf5 5. g4
{ is arguably White's most critical variation. Several high-level correspondence games have shown Black is in trouble in this variation, with White objectively having a clear advantage in all the lines.  OTB blitz and rapid chess is, however, an entirely different beast. Despite the engine laughing at Black's position in most of the subsequent variations, Black scores well in this line. The reason is that White weakens several dark squares and his king lacks pawn cover. }
5... Bg6 6. c4
{ is both materialistic and strong. White holds firmly onto his extra pawn.   6.h4  can simply be blocked with  6...h5   6.Bb5+  is well met by  6...c6!  7.dxc6  Nxc6=  with fantastic play against White's d4 pawn. }
6... e6
{ 6...c6?!  doesn't work very well because of  7.Nc3  cxd5  8.g5  Nfd7  9.cxd5±  White has a big edge here. }
7. Nc3 c5
{ Undermining White's central pawns is a recurrent theme in the Portuguese Gambit. After extensive analysis, I believe this is Black's best practical chance of muddying the waters.  This move was not considered in the book Kaufman's New Repertoire for Black and White: A Complete, Sound and User-Friendly Chess Opening Repertoire by GM Larry Kaufman. }
8. Be3 exd5 9. g5 Nfd7 10. cxd5 Be7
{ Black plans to quickly castle kingside and bring his rook to the e-file in an attempt to exploit White's lack of kingside development. While White is objectively clearly better, converting it into a full point is far from trivial. }
