1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6
{ The 2...Nf6 Scandinavian is objectively dubious, but a good blitz and rapid weapon nonetheless. White has to be quite precise in order to get an advantage with Black having a whole array of devious tricks and traps at his disposal. }
3. c4 c6 4. d4 cxd5
{ We've transposed into the Panov variation of the Caro-Kann. } 5. Nc3 g6
{ is an offbeat and fully viable system that avoids having to learn a ton of forced lines. It has been played by several super-GMs such as Kamsky and Grischuk so we're definitely in good company!   The idea is to prioritize rapid development of the kingside with ...Bg7 and ...O-O without worrying about the d5 pawn. We're happy to temporarily sacrifice it in exchange for dynamic piece play. }
6. Qb3 Bg7 7. cxd5
{ We're not really worried about this as White won't be able to hold onto the d5 pawn in the long run. }
7... O-O 8. Nge2
{ intending to reinforce the d5 pawn with Nf4 doesn't really work. } 8... a5
{ with the idea ...a4 to remove a key defender of the d5 pawn.  This move was not considered in the book The Panov-Botvinnik Attack: Move by Move by IM Lorin D'Costa. }
9. g3
{ 9.Nf4?!  runs into  9...g5=+   9.a4?!  critically weakens the b4 square, which Black can immediately exploit with  9...Na6=+  followed by ...Nb4. The d5 pawn will soon drop. }
9... a4 10. Nxa4 Qxd5 11. Qxd5 Nxd5
{ Despite currently being a pawn down, Black has a lead in development. The d4 pawn is likely to fall and it turns out that White is the one that has to tread carefully to stay in the game. }
*

