3. c4 c6 4. d4 cxd5
{ We've transposed into the Panov variation of the Caro-Kann. } 5. Nc3 g6
{ is an offbeat and fully viable system that avoids having to learn a ton of forced lines. It has been played by several super-GMs such as Kamsky and Grischuk so we're definitely in good company!   The idea is to prioritize rapid development of the kingside with ...Bg7 and ...O-O without worrying about the d5 pawn. We're happy to temporarily sacrifice it in exchange for dynamic piece play. }
6. Qb3 Bg7 7. cxd5
{ We're not really worried about this as White won't be able to hold onto the d5 pawn in the long run. }
7... O-O 8. Be2
{ with the idea Bf3 is White's most challenging option. Alternatives are considered below. }
8... Na6
{ is an important move. ...Nbd7-b6 doesn't work here because White is in time to reinforce d5 with Nh3-f4.   The text with the idea ...Qb6 to exchange off a key defender of the d5 pawn is a better plan. Black will then regain this pawn with ...Rd8 and ...Nb4. }
9. Bf3 Qb6 10. Qxb6
{ 10.Nge2  allows  10...Qxb3  when White can hardly for an edge. After  11.axb3  Rd8  12.O-O  Nc7=  The d5 pawn is about to drop. Black is very comfortable as IM Sam Collins himself recognized in the Chessable course The Furious Panov-Botvinik. }
10... axb6 11. Nge2 Nb4 12. O-O Rd8
{ Black will regain the d5 pawn on the next turn with a good game. The doubled b-pawns aren't significant as White cannot easily get to them.   A sample continuation is  13.d6  Rxd6  14.Bf4  Rd7  15.Rfd1   Alternatively  15.Rad1  Nfd5  16.Be5  Now  16...Nxc3!  was not considered by IM Lorin D'Costa in the book The Panov-Botvinnik Attack: Move by Move. After  17.Nxc3  Bxe5  18.dxe5  Ra5=  Black has zero problems.  15...Nfd5  16.Bg3  Nxc3  17.bxc3  Nc6=  White's rook on a1 is tied down to the defense of the a2 pawn and cannot easily attack Black's doubled-pawns. The second player can look to break with ...e5 next. }
